window.ARTICLES = [{"id": 34437538531485, "title": "Understanding and Resolving Degraded Codes in Medicus", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34437538531485", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains what degraded codes are, why they appear in Medicus, and how to resolve them. It covers: Degraded codes: Clinical codes that Medicus cannot fully interpret when a patient record is transferred from another system, which can affect certain functions such as prescribing. Resolving degraded codes: How to locate degraded codes and replace them with valid SNOMED CT equivalents, either from the Degraded Codes task or directly from the patient record. How code recognition works in Medicus When a patient record arrives from another clinical system, Medicus checks whether it recognises the clinical codes in that record. If a code is recognised, for example a SNOMED CT code, it is imported and stored as normal. If a code cannot be recognised or validated, Medicus flags it as degraded. A degraded code means Medicus cannot fully interpret the clinical meaning provided by the previous system. This can happen for several reasons. Read Code to SNOMED CT mapping If the previous system used Read Codes, Medicus converts these using the NHS England PBCL mapping tables, which provide a nationally maintained mapping between Read Codes and their SNOMED CT equivalents. Because this mapping is nationally defined, Read Codes are converted automatically and do not trigger degraded codes. Local codes from other providers Some clinical systems use locally created codes that do not have a national mapping to SNOMED CT. When Medicus receives one of these codes during a record transfer, it cannot reliably convert it, so the code is marked as degraded. Nationally defined transfer-degraded codes In some cases, the previous system may have already replaced an unrecognised code with a nationally defined transfer-degraded code before the record was sent, for example: 196461000000101 | Transfer-degraded drug allergy (record artifact) When Medicus receives a code like this, it means the previous system could not interpret the original code, the code was degraded in that system, and the previous practice did not replace it with a valid clinical code before transferring the record. As the original clinical meaning is unknown, Medicus cannot automatically restore it. This behaviour is consistent across all clinical systems and is a mandatory requirement for NHS foundation systems. Impact of degraded codes When a code is degraded in Medicus, certain functions may be restricted. In particular, prescribing may be blocked where the degraded code could affect prescribing safety. This follows nationally mandated rules designed to protect patient safety and maintain data integrity. How to resolve a degraded code If a degraded code is preventing prescribing, it can usually be resolved by replacing it with a valid SNOMED CT equivalent. There are two ways to do this. From the Degraded Codes task To view and resolve degraded codes in bulk, go to Modules > Workflow > Registration activity > GP2GP Degraded Codes . Select the degraded code you want to resolve, then select Add new code . Search for and select the correct SNOMED CT code, then save the changes. Once the entry has been updated, the degraded code will be resolved and prescribing will be available again. From the patient record From the journal You can also resolve a degraded code directly from an individual patient's journal. Open the patient record and use the filter in the journal to select Show degraded entries . Locate and click on the relevant degraded code to open the slideover panel with additional details. Select Click here to resolve , then select Add new code and enter the correct SNOMED CT equivalent. Save the changes and the code will update. Prescribing will be available again once the record has been saved.   National standards The handling of degraded codes follows nationally agreed rules and guidance, ensuring consistent behaviour across all clinical systems."}, {"id": 16394207045021, "title": "Activating your Medicus Account", "section": "Login & Account Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16394207045021", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose When a management user adds you to Medicus, you will be prompted to follow the steps outlined in this guide to set up your account. Account activation steps You will receive an email that looks like this: To setup your account and login, you need to click the link in the welcome email to create a password and set up two factor authentication to securely access your account: \n First, create a secure password and then re-type it under Confirm password. \n Next, set up two factor authentication. Note: you will need to have downloaded an authentication app to your smartphone e.g. Google Authenticator or Microsoft Authenticator. \n \n Using your authenticator app, scan the QR code to pair your Medicus account to the app. \n Enter the 6 digit token generated by the authenticator app. \n Click Complete Setup - you should now have access to your Medicus account. \n Expired activation link The activation link in the email is active for 30 days. If the link is clicked once it has expired you will see the following: Follow the on screen instructions and contact your internal Medicus administrator for a new activation email."}, {"id": 16427764723357, "title": "How to Pair/Unpair your NHS Smartcard", "section": "Login & Account Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16427764723357", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose Login with your NHS Smartcard is required to use functionality within Medicus that interacts with the NHS spine services. In order for you to login to your Medicus account using your NHS Smartcard and access, you will first need to pair your Smartcard with your Medicus account. This guide outlines the steps required to pair/unpair your NHS Smartcard. Navigating to your account settings First, you will be required to login to Medicus using your username, password and one time password. Next, navigate to your account setting by first clicking on your account name in the bottom left hand corner of the screen. Then select My Account to be taken to your Login & Security page. Pairing your NHS Smartcard To pair a new Smartcard, click Pair Smartcard. This will connect to the NHS Care Identity Service to pair your Smartcard. If you have already entered your PIN (e.g. when you logged into your computer) then your Smartcard will be paired, otherwise you will be prompted to enter your PIN. You can now login using your Smartcard. Note that if you are logged in with another Smartcard, you will not be able to complete the action above. A banner alerting you to this will be displayed. Unpairing your NHS Smartcard To unpair a Smartcard, select the Paired Smartcard field within the Login Details section. You'll be taken to a view on the right side of the screen where you have the option to unpair the Smartcard. You'll be prompted to confirm that you'd like to go head and unpair the Smartcard. Select the Y es, unpair button to unpair the Smartcard. The Smartcard will no longer be associated to the Medicus account."}, {"id": 32567521003165, "title": "Troubleshooting Smartcard Issues", "section": "Login & Account Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32567521003165", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose If you receive an error when logging into Medicus on completing actions using your smartcard, you may need to do some troubleshooting to understand what may be causing the issue.  This error is not related to your Medicus account, but following the steps below should help to resolve the error and allow you to log in or complete the action. The following information is taken from NHS England's troubleshooting guide. Troubleshooting steps When trying to log in with a smartcard, you may see a Smartcard Authentication Failure error. You can see an example of this error below. It might start with the number 400_ or 500_. This can happen because: \n NHS Credential Management is not running or is out of date \n You've recently installed or updated NHS Credential Management but have not rebooted the device \n NHS Identity Agent is not running or is out of date \n The smartcard is not in the reader \n Your smartcard is blank or faulty \n You do not have any roles on your smartcard \n Your browser is not supported \n You've cancelled login, or lost your network connection just before login completed \n You are using the NHS Chrome extension \n Check the smartcard is in the reader Make sure your smartcard is facing the right direction in the reader, and that the reader is not damaged, and try again. If it still doesn't work, try in a colleague's machine if possible. Check your smartcard is active You will have to contact your  Registration Authority . They can check your profile has an active smartcard with the right roles applied. If you can log in with NHS Identity Agent successfully, but do not see the role selection screen, it's likely you do not have any roles on your profile, and therefore cannot access any service at all. Check your workstation setup Use the setup checker tool  to identify the specific issue causing the error. Check Credential Manager is running \n \n Find NHS Credential Management in your application tray \n \n \n \n Right click and select Exit \n \n \n Search NHS Credential Management in your Windows toolbar \n Double click on NHS Credential Management to re-open it \n \n Check that the icon appears in your application tray   \n For anything else Smartcard problems are almost always due to your software or device setup, and you will need to contact your local IT support team. Depending on your organisation, this may be through your IT helpdesk, or via a dedicated  Registration Authority  team. There are further instructions for IT teams here."}, {"id": 20558198529693, "title": "The Medicus Homepage", "section": "Medicus Overview, Navigation & Tasks", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20558198529693", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose This article explains how to navigate the Medicus homepage. Medicus is designed so that your workload and tasks are accessible directly from the homepage, without needing to search through the system. This article covers: My Appointments: Gives clinical users a snapshot of their day, including upcoming appointments, arrived patients, and consultation notes. Appointment Book: Provides a practice-wide view of all scheduled appointment diaries for the day. Navigation Bar: Allows you to move between the main areas of Medicus. My Task List: Shows all open tasks assigned to you as an individual or to any teams you are in. My Appointments When you log in as a clinical user, you will be taken directly to the My Appointments page. This gives you an at-a-glance view of your day, including your upcoming appointments, arrived patients, incomplete consultation notes, and completed consultations. You can start a consultation with an arrived patient directly from this page. You can start a consultation with an Arrived patient directly from here. Displaying Non-Appointment Activity If you have any Non-appointment activity scheduled (e.g. breaks, meetings, patient admin), it will also appear within My Appointments alongside your booked appointments. Appointment Book The next tab along will take you to today's appointment book, so you can get a practice-wide view of all of the scheduled appointment diaries for that day. Reception staff can book in patients directly from this page. Navigation Bar On the left-hand side navigation bar, you can navigate to different areas of Medicus: \n Homepage - T his will take you back to the 'My Appointments' tab on the homepage. \n \n \n Patient finder - T his is the easiest way to locate a patient record in Medicus. \n \n \n Chat - T his will open up the instant message functionality, where you can message an individual or a group of people. \n \n Modules - I f you need to navigate to different modules within the system, you can find the modules menu here. \n \n My Task List Also on the left-hand side navigation bar on the homepage are any open tasks which are assigned to you as an individual or any teams that you are in. Here you can see the task type, with the number on the right-hand side showing how many open tasks are in the list. Selecting a task type will take you to the specific task list for you to begin working through."}, {"id": 29335965499933, "title": "Read-Only Access User Guide", "section": "Medicus Overview, Navigation & Tasks", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/29335965499933", "roles": ["HCA", "Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose External clinical staff may require access to Medicus, for example, to view the health record of a patient within a community setting. It is the decision of the practice who they provide access to and what level of access individuals should be given. This user guide provides information on how someone with read-only access of Medicus can review the patient record. Login & Account Management You can login to Medicus on any device that runs a modern browser, including on a tablet or mobile. You can login to Medicus by heading to england.medicus.health on a modern browser that's connected to the internet. Login and account management works in the same way for all users, including those with read-only access. Information about login and account management can be found within the following user guides: \n Activating your Medicus Account \n Logging in to Medicus \n How to Pair/Unpair your NHS Smartcard with your Medicus Account \n Resetting a Forgotten Password \n How to Change your Medicus Account Password \n How to Reset your Two Factor Authentication \n Navigating to the Patient Record The easiest way to navigate to the patient record in Medicus, is by using the patient finder which is on the left hand side navigation bar. There's a detailed user guide on using the patient finder here: Using the Patient Finder Finding Information on the Patient Record Clinical Summary The first page you'll be taken to on the patient care record is the clinical summary page. Here, you'll be able to see a snapshot of the patient's current care, including: \n Safeguarding risks, reasonable adjustments or medico legal flags on the patient banner. \n Current active problems (major and minor). \n Current allergies, repeat medications, acute medications prescribed in the last 12 months, medication prescribed elsewhere and over-the-counter medication. \n Last key observations added to the record. \n The last 3 months worth of consultations, documents and results. \n Upcoming future actions / recalls tracked at the GP practice. \n Links to the local Shared Care Record, Summary Care Record and GPConnect Record. \n The typical layout of the Clinical Summary in the Medicus patient record. Consultation Notes Consultation notes can be found in the journal, the second tab along on the care record. The journal is the full health record of the patient with the most recent entry first. You can use the journal filters on the right hand side to filter by consultation notes so you can easily find what you're looking for. Here you can see a filtered view of journal showing only consultation notes. Documents Documents can be found in the journal, the second tab along on the care record. The journal is the full health record of the patient with the most recent entry first. You can use the journal filters on the right hand side to filter by document so you can easily find what you're looking for. You can select 'View Document' to review the document and any clinical coding added when the document was workflowed. Here you can see a filtered view of the journal showing only documents. Medications If you require a deeper dive on medications than the information available on the clinical summary page, then you can view the Medication Regimen tab on the care record. From this page you'll be able to see detailed information on a patient's repeat medications such as remaining issues, when a medication was last issued and the EPS status for prescriptions. Clicking into each prescription will open the 'View Prescription' screen for your review. Selecting a prescription from the medication regimen page opens up the view prescription screen. For a more historical view on medications, you can also review the Medication History tab. Investigation Results Investigation results can be reviewed in two different ways on the patient record: \n By filtering by investigation results on the journal, similar to when you're looking for consultation notes or documents. This might be the preferred method if you're looking for one investigation report in particular. \n By navigating to the Results and Observations tab on the care record. This tab will provide you with a breakdown of all previous investigation results. This view is helpful if you're looking at what investigations the patient has had as a whole, and reviewing trends over time. \n Administrative Information If you want to review administrative information for a patient, you can navigate to the administrative section of the record from the left hand side navigation bar. Support For any technical support you can contact the Medicus help desk on support@medicus.health . Any queries on local Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) or system access should be agreed between the GP practice and the external providers who require their staff to have a read-only Medicus account."}, {"id": 17157806047389, "title": "System Requirements", "section": "Medicus Overview, Navigation & Tasks", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17157806047389", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose This guide will provide information and guidance on supported devices and browsers required to use Medicus. Supported Devices Medicus is a web based clinical system. There are no specific restrictions on devices that can be used with Medicus. Any device that is capable of running a desktop web browser within the supported browser versions listed below can be used. Some of the supported browsers impose a minimum set of requirements on end-users which are documented here: \n Google Chrome browser system requirements \n Microsoft Edge system requirements \n Supported Browsers To provide the best experience, Medicus only supports specific web browsers. Where a web browser is not supported, access is blocked for clinical safety reasons. Desktop Browsers The following web browsers are supported on desktop devices: \n \n Google Chrome  (released within last 24 months) \n \n Microsoft Edge  (released within last 24 months) \n \n Apple Safari  on Mac OS X only (released within last 24 months) \n Mobile Browsers The following web browsers are supported on mobile devices: \n \n Google Chrome  (released within last 24 months) \n \n Apple Safari  on iOS only (released within last 24 months)"}, {"id": 16305852109725, "title": "Using the Patient Finder", "section": "Medicus Overview, Navigation & Tasks", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16305852109725", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose The main way to find a patient record in Medicus is to use the patient finder tool. This guide outlines how to use the patient finder. Locating the patient finder In the left hand menu of Medicus, you can click the magnifying glass icon and Patient Finder text which will open the patient finder. Once the search dialog opens any recently visited patients are displayed before any search term has been entered. There are two options for finding a patient: \n Text search. \n Advanced search. \n Using the text search The text search works on either a patient name, date of birth (DOB) or NHS number. The text search has been designed for you to find patients as quickly and easily as possible, whilst ensuring you search for the right patient. Using advanced search If you do not know the patient's name, DOB or NHS number, you can use the advanced search in the patient finder to look for a patient using other information. For example, you may know which clinician saw the patient last and when. Click the Advanced options button on the patient finder. You'll then be taken to the advanced search form where you can search for registered patients using additional information. Search results For both the text search and advanced search, the results are displayed in the same way. Clicking on a result will take you to the patient record for the chosen patient. The Good Practice Guidelines for GP Electronic Patient Records recommends the following to reduce the risk of patient misidentification: \"It is essential to match patients across several data fields to get a positive match and we advise that current best practice to achieve (near) certain identification requires a confirmed match in all the following data fields; \n Last name (or family name) \n First name (calling name) \n Date of birth \n NHS number \n Sex (administrative gender) \n Address (including postcode) \n Source: Main heading (publishing.service.gov.uk) (P.104) Deceased patients Deceased patients will be returned in search results and can be identified by the presence of a badge on the patient result card that says 'Deceased'."}, {"id": 16307657510557, "title": "Resetting a Forgotten Password", "section": "Login & Account Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16307657510557", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n In the event of a forgotten password, you can follow the steps outlined in this guide to reset your password and regain access to your account. \n Steps to reset your password \n From the login page, select the Forgotten Password link. Enter your registered email address as prompted and select Send reset instructions. You can return to the login page from here if needed to do so. \n If your email is recognised as being associated to a Medicus account, you will be informed that an email containing instructions on how to reset your password has been sent to you. \n If your email is entered incorrectly and is not associated with a Medicus account, you will be informed of this on screen and prompted to check that the email address entered is correct. \n The email contains a unique link to reset your password. Note that the link will only be active from 1 hour after receiving the email. \n \n By following the link within the email, you will be taken to a page prompting you to create a new password. \n Once this form is submitted, you will then be prompted to enter a 6 digit one-time passcode from your authenticator app. \n Once you've entered this passcode and selected Verify your password will be changed. You will now be able to enter your email and new password at the login page to regain access to your Medicus account."}, {"id": 16428271125149, "title": "How to Change your Medicus Account Password", "section": "Login & Account Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16428271125149", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose If you need to change your account password, the steps outlined in this guide will show you how to do this. Navigating to your account settings Navigate to your account setting by: \n Select your name in the bottom left corner of the screen \n Select My Account from the settings \n Changing your account password On the Login and Security screen, click on the password field in the Login Details section which will open a form to change your password: Enter your current and new password in the relevant fields, and select save changes. Your new password will now be required when logging in via this method."}, {"id": 16452436304029, "title": "Generating a Two-Factor Authentication Recovery Code as an Administrator", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16452436304029", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose During the login process, it is possible that a user may no longer be able to generate a one-time passcode from their Authenticator app. Due to the sensitivity of the data held within Medicus, only an administrative user can recover their account by generating a 2FA recovery code. This guide covers the steps required to action this. Steps to generate a 2FA recovery code 1. From the modules menu on the side navigation bar select Staff Administration. 2. From the staff list, locate and select the staff member that you would like to resend the recovery code to. This will open up the staff details. 3. Select Login & Security on the side navigation bar. 4. Select the Generate 2FA recovery code button. 5. The following screen is displayed which shows the recovery code. It is valid for 24 hours. Once the expiry time has passed, a new recovery code is generated. 6. Provide the recovery code to the user who is trying to login. They are able to enter the recovery code by selecting Enter recovery code from the 2FA login flow. 7. If the user enters the code incorrectly, or enters an expired code, an error is displayed on the screen. Otherwise, if entered correctly the user will be able to regain access to their account. 8. Once they are logged in, you can direct them to their My account settings to reset their 2FA."}, {"id": 16395675543453, "title": "Logging in to Medicus", "section": "Login & Account Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16395675543453", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose This guide outlines the different login options for Medicus and how to troubleshoot login issues if needed. There are two ways to login to your Medicus account: \n Using your NHS Smartcard (CIS2). \n Using your username and password, which will generate a one time passcode from your authenticator app. \n Logging in using the latter option, via username and password, won't allow you to use functionality within Medicus that interacts with the NHS spine services. This guide includes step by step instructions on both Medicus login methods. Logging in with your NHS Smartcard Medicus integrates with the  NHS Care Identity Service 2 (CIS2)  to allow you to login with your NHS Smartcard.  You'll need your Smartcard and Smartcard PIN to access Medicus. To login with your Smartcard, click 'Login with Smartcard'. If you have already entered your PIN (e.g. when you logged into your computer) then you will be logged in, otherwise you will be prompted to enter your PIN and then logged in. Note: You will need to login with your username and password first and complete the one-time pairing between your Smartcard and you Medicus user account before you can login via the above method. Logging in with username and password Logging in with a username, password and one-time password (OTP) allows you to use all of the features of Medicus except those that interact with the NHS Spine (e.g. PDS tracing). To login with your username and password, simply enter your username and password and click 'Login'. Then open your Authenticator app and enter the 6 digit OTP. Requesting a recovery code If your authenticator app is not working and you cannot generate an OTP. You can contact your local team administrator who will be able to generate and provide a recovery code for you."}, {"id": 32237110842525, "title": "Managing Capacity for Patient Request Inbound", "section": "Patient Requests", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32237110842525", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains the various features available in Medicus that supports you to manage your capacity for inbound Patient Requests, including opening hours, temporary pause and information banners. The article will also show you what the form looks like to patients when each of these features are used. Opening Hours You can manage when patients can submit requests by setting open hours. To set opening hours go to Modules > Front Door > Patient Requests > Medical or Admin Requests and select the currently set opening hours next to Form opening hours. You can then configure the opening hours for patient requests. Firstly, choose the expected response time before a patient request which will be shown to patients when completing requests. You can then choose from a few options to set when patients can submit medical requests: \n Same hours Monday - Friday (Not including weekends) \n Always open (Including weekends) \n Custom Schedule \n Same hours Monday - Friday  If you choose Same Hours Monday - Friday, you can set the opening and close times which will be applied every weekday. Always Open If you choose Always Open, then the form will always be available for patients to submit requests. Custom Schedule If you choose Custom Schedule, you can set opening periods for each day. You can set multiple opening periods per day, for example, to close access to submit requests during lunchtime. Patient view of expected response time and opening times Patients will see expected response time before and after submitting their request. If requests are open, the patient will see the closing time for requests. If requests are closed, the request option will be greyed out and the patient will see the opening time for requests. Temporary pause  The temporary pause feature can help practices manage demand and reduce the risk of your practice feeling overwhelmed. You can choose the date and time you want online consultations to be available again, along with a message which will show to patients while it is paused. You can suspend either Medical or Admin requests, or both. To temporarily pause requests, go to Modules > Front Door > Patient Requests > Medical or Admin Requests and select Temporarily pause requests. Select a date and time that you would like to pause requests until. The pause will end automatically at the date and time chosen but you can manually remove the pause at any time. You can also customise the message that will be shown to patients on the online consultation form when requests are paused. Patient view of paused requests This is how the form appears to patients when requests are paused.  Editing or removing a temporary pause To edit or remove a temporary pause, select Edit/remove on the current pause. You can then either edit the text and Save Changes or Remove Pause. Information Banner You may need to let patients know that response times may be delayed or inform them of things like practice closures. You can do this using the information banner. To do this Modules > Front Door > Patient Requests > Medical or Admin Requests and select Add Information Banner. You can add the information banner to either Medical or Admin requests, or both. You can then add the message for patients on the information banner and then select Add Banner. Patient view of the information banner Patients will see the information banner after selecting which request type they are wanting to submit and after entering their personal details.  Editing or removing an information banner To edit or remove an information banner, select Edit/remove on the current banner. You can then either edit the text and Save Changes or Delete Banner."}, {"id": 16469048743837, "title": "User Roles & Permissions", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16469048743837", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose In Medicus, users are granted permissions by giving each user a 'user role'. User roles grant a user access to a set of permissions. Permissions grant a user role access to actions and/or views of data within Medicus. A user can be assigned more than one user role, for example, they may need all of the permissions that a Doctor has but also need the permissions of Clinical Management if their role within the practice means they need access to audit logs. This user guide outlines how user roles and permissions are broken down within Medicus. Permissions \n \n Name \n Description \n \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n Grants access to things that any user could do such as change their password. \n \n \n View Patient Administrative Details \n Allows the user to perform actions such as find a patient, view demographic and contact information. \n \n \n Update Patient Administrative Details \n Allows the user to update demographic and contact information. \n \n \n View Patient Care Records \n \n Allows the user to view the care record of a patient. \n Please note: for clinical safety reasons, Medicus does not implement permissions that grant or deny access to individual sections of a patient’s care record. \n \n \n \n Update Patient Care Records \n Allows the user to update the care record of a patient. \n \n \n Manage Users \n Allows the users to add new staff members to Medicus and update their user roles. \n \n \n View Staff Administrative Details \n Allows the user to view administrative details such as staff demographic and contact information on the staff profile. \n \n \n Update Staff Administrative Details \n Allows the user to update administrative details such as staff demographic and contact information on the staff profile. \n \n \n Configure Medicus \n Allows the user to manage the setup and configuration of Medicus. \n \n \n Information Governance Audit \n Allows the user to view audit logs and other information governance features. \n \n \n Manage Content \n Allows the user to create and maintain content such as consultation templates. \n \n User roles \n \n Name \n Permissions \n \n \n Clinical Management \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n View Patient Administrative Details \n Update Patient Administrative Details \n View Patient Care Records \n Update Patient Care Records \n Manage Users \n View Staff Administrative Details \n Update Staff Administrative Details \n Configure Medicus \n Information Governance Audit \n \n \n \n Operational Management \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n View Patient Administrative Details \n Update Patient Administrative Details \n View Patient Care Records \n Update Patient Care Records \n Manage Users \n View Staff Administrative Details \n Update Staff Administrative Details \n Configure Medicus \n Information Governance Audit \n \n \n \n Doctor \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n View Patient Administrative Details \n Update Patient Administrative Details \n View Patient Care Records \n Update Patient Care Records \n \n \n \n Nurse \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n View Patient Administrative Details \n Update Patient Administrative Details \n View Patient Care Records \n Update Patient Care Records \n \n \n \n Pharmacist \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n View Patient Administrative Details \n Update Patient Administrative Details \n View Patient Care Records \n Update Patient Care Records \n \n \n \n Healthcare Practitioner \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n View Patient Administrative Details \n Update Patient Administrative Details \n View Patient Care Records \n Update Patient Care Records \n \n \n \n Clinical Admin \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n View Patient Administrative Details \n Update Patient Administrative Details \n View Patient Care Records \n Update Patient Care Records \n \n \n \n Clerical \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n View Patient Administrative Details \n Update Patient Administrative Details \n View Patient Care Records \n Update Patient Care Records \n \n \n \n IT Support \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n Configure Medicus \n \n \n \n Content Author \n \n Staff Basic Actions \n Manage Content"}, {"id": 18443627942813, "title": "Creating eMED3 Fit Notes", "section": "Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18443627942813", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose During or after a consultation, you may need to issue a MED3 fit note to a patient to sign them off work, or recommend that the patient's employer makes adjustments to help them back to work. This user guide will show you how to issue an eMED3 fit note from Medicus. Creating a fit note There are two routes to creating a fit note for a patient: \n From a consultation - This is the most likely route, as typically MED3 fit notes are issued after a consultation where a clinician will assess a patient's fitness for work. \n \n From the care record. \n Creating a fit note from a consultation To create a fit note from a consultation, you can find 'Fit note' from the actions menu, or you can use a '/' to open up the quick action options.     Creating a fit note from the patient record To create a fit note from the care record, select 'Fit note' from the 'Actions' menu in the top right hand corner of the page.     Completing the fit note form Creating a fit note from a consultation or from a patient record will open up the 'New Fit Note' form. You can either send the fit note to the patient electronically, issue a printed fit note, or select 'Issued by hand' if you don't need to print a copy. Once saved, previously issued fit notes are visible in the patient journal."}, {"id": 34114889662493, "title": "Managing Video Appointments", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34114889662493", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose For services that primarily offer video appointments, this guide will show you how to book and manage video appointments. Booking video appointments Patient appointments can be booked in Medicus in a few different ways: \n From the Appointment Book tab on the homepage \n From a patient's care record \n From a consultation \n From a book appointment task \n Booking an appointment from the appointment book To book an appointment from the Appointment Book, either from the homepage or the scheduling module, hover over the appointment slot you want to book and click Book. Booking an appointment from the Care Record To book a patient appointment from a patient's Care Record, select the 'Actions' dropdown menu from the top right hand corner. Select Appointment to proceed. This will open up two options: \n \n View appointment book  - selecting this option will open up the Appointment Book where you can view appointment diaries with available appointments to book the patient into. \n \n Free appointment finder  - selecting this option will take you through the free appointment finder workflow. \n Booking an appointment from a consultation The option to book a patient appointment during a consultation is found at the bottom of the New consultation form. This will open up two options: \n \n View appointment book  - selecting this option will open up the Appointment Book where you can view appointment diaries with available appointments to book the patient into. \n \n Free appointment finder  - selecting this option will take you through the free appointment finder workflow. \n You can also create a book appointment task if you don't have time to book a follow up appointment during the consultation. Booking the appointment All routes to appointment booking take you to the New Appointment form. Appointment details Some of the appointment details have been pre-populated in line with the appointment diary settings. If required, you can override the delivery mode, duration or NHS slot category by clicking Change . You can double check that the appointment is set up for Video by checking the Delivery Mode. Starting a video appointment When it is time for the appointment, the patient will need to be sent a link to join their video consultation.  To do this go to the appointment book, select the patient and then Go to Consultation. This will take you to the waiting room for the consultation. To share the video call link with the patient select Share Video Link. This will then open up the Share Video Consultation Link modal. You will be shown the patient's contact details that the message will be sent to which you can modifying by selecting Modify Recipient Details . To join the video consultation, select Join Video Call. This will then start the video call for the patient to join. Completing the consultation Select Start Consultation, this will open the New Consultation modal to add your consultation notes. Read more about completing consultation notes here. Once you have completed the consultation notes click Complete consultation to save the notes."}, {"id": 18537085147677, "title": "Recording a Note on the Patient Banner", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18537085147677", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose Notes are a generic way to capture information about a patient on their care record. Notes can be added either as free text or clinically coded. Notes can be used to flag safeguarding risks, legal and reasonable adjustments on the patient banner. This user guide will show you how to record a note against a patient's care record in Medicus. Recording a note on the care record To record a note in Medicus, select Actions in the top right hand corner and then select Note. This will open up the New Note form. If you'd like to add a coded note, type into the Code as field. As you type you'll be presented with a list of SNOMED CT codes to choose from. If you would like to add a free text note, use the Note field in the form. Selecting certain codes, for example a safeguarding risk code, will automatically check the Flag on patient banner box. Make sure you check this is checked or unchecked before proceeding based on whether you want the note to flag on the patient banner. Select Save once you've completed the form. Viewing the note on the patient banner If the note you've added is a safeguarding risk, legal or reasonable adjustment then it should be displayed on the patient banner so every staff user can see this information."}, {"id": 34753000173853, "title": "Provisioning and Upgrading a NHS Login account for patients", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34753000173853", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains how to set up and upgrade NHS login accounts for patients who cannot complete the standard verification process themselves. To access online services such as the NHS App and view their GP record, patients need an NHS login account with full identity verification (P9). This page covers: Viewing NHS login account details: Allows you to check whether a patient already has an NHS login account and what their current verification level is. Provisioning an account: Allows you to create a new P9-verified NHS login account on behalf of a patient who does not have one. Upgrading an account: Allows you to request an upgrade to P9 for a patient who has an NHS login account but has not completed full identity verification. Identity Verification History: Shows a record of all provisioning and upgrade requests made for the patient from your practice. This feature is available in NHS jurisdictions only. The Online Access tab All NHS login account management takes place on the patient's Administrative Record . Go to the patient's administrative record and then select the Online Access tab. The page contains two sections: NHS Login Account and Online Access Permissions . The information banner at the top of the page explains what patients need to access online services and provides a link they can use to set up their own NHS login if they prefer. Viewing a patient's NHS login account details When you open the Online Access tab, Medicus automatically looks up the patient's NHS login account using their NHS number. The NHS Login Account card will show one of the following states: No account   The patient does not have an NHS login account. A Provision account button will be shown if no request has been made in the last 7 days. Account exists but not fully verified (P0 or P5)   The patient has an account but has not completed full identity verification. A warning banner will prompt you to take action, and the account's username, mobile phone number, and current verification level will be displayed. Fully verified (P9)   The patient's account is fully verified. The username, mobile phone number, and verification level are displayed. No further action is required. The Provision account and Upgrade account options will not appear if the patient does not have an NHS number on their record, is under 11 years of age, or if a request has already been submitted in the last 7 days. Provisioning a new NHS login account You can provision a new NHS Login account for a patient who has no existing NHS login account and needs one creating on their behalf. Before submitting, you must verify the patient's identity in person. Select Provision account to open the Provision NHS Login Account form. \n Identity Verification   Record how the patients identity was verified in the How was the patient's identity verified? field - for example, documents presented, vouching with record confirmation, or personal vouching. Select who carried out the verification from the Who verified the patient's identity? dropdown, which is pre-populated with your name but can be changed to any active staff member. Add any additional notes in the Additional information field if needed. \n NHS Login Account Details   Check the pre-filled email address and mobile phone number are correct (these are pulled from the patients record). These will be used by the patient to access their account. Select Submit to send the request. Submitting request After submitting, NHS login will email the patient a link to complete their account setup. This link expires after 7 days.  If a request has been submitted in the last 7 days, the Provision account button will be replaced with a message showing who made the request, when, and which email address was used. Upgrading an existing NHS login account to P9 Use this when a patient already has an NHS login account but their identity verification level is P0 or P5. As with provisioning, you must verify the patient's identity before submitting the upgrade request. From the NHS Login Account card, select Click here to verify in the warning banner, or select the upgrade option directly. This opens the Upgrade NHS Login Account form. Complete the Identity Verification section in the same way as for provisioning.  In the NHS Login Account Details section, the patient's existing username and mobile phone number are shown automatically - these are pulled from their NHS login account and cannot be edited here. If the patient wants to use different details, they will need to update them in the NHS App first.  Select Submit to send the upgrade request. NHS login will email the patient a link to complete the identity verification upgrade process, which expires after 7 days. If a request has already been submitted in the last 7 days, the upgrade option will be replaced with a message showing the request details. Viewing the identity verification history The Identity Verification History appears on the Online Access tab whenever one or more provisioning or upgrade requests have been submitted for a patient from your practice. It shows the date, verification method, who verified the patient, who recorded the request, and any additional notes. FAQ What should the patient do if their NHS number is linked to more than one NHS Login account? The patient will need to contact NHS Login directly to resolve the issue. They can be contacted through their contact form. How old do patients need to be to provision an NHS Login account? Patient needs to be 11 years and over to provision an NHS Login account. Can an NHS Login account be provisioned if the patient does not have an NHS number? The patient requires an NHS number in order to provision an NHS Login account."}, {"id": 34917795263389, "title": "Setting up a Check-In Kiosk", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34917795263389", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains how to set up and manage the Medicus self-service check-in kiosk, which allows patients to check in for their appointments using a tablet in your waiting area. These features include: Pairing a kiosk: Connect a tablet to your Medicus account so it can be used for patient check-in. Approving and rejecting pairing requests: Review and manage incoming kiosk pairing requests from within Medicus. Patient check-in flow: How patients use the kiosk to check in for their appointment by entering their date of birth. Removing a kiosk: Decommission a kiosk that is no longer in use. Hardware requirements Your practice is responsible for sourcing and managing kiosk tablets. The tablet will need: \n An internet connection \n A. touch screen \n At least 4GB of RAM \n A web browser that can run in kiosk mode (where the browser cannot be exited). iPads and Android tablets are both supported. \n Setting up a kiosk Pairing the kiosk Before patients can use the kiosk, it needs to be paired with your Medicus account. This is a two-step process: the kiosk submits a pairing request, and a Medicus user then approves it. To start, your tablet should be set up in kiosk mode with the browser pointing to the Medicus kiosk URL. https://kiosk.england.medicus.health/ Once loaded, the tablet will display a Pair Kiosk screen asking for your Medicus tenant ID. Your tenant identifier can be found in Medicus at Modules > Organisation Details .  Enter it on the tablet and select Pair . The tablet will then display an Awaiting Approval screen showing a Kiosk ID and instructions to approve the request in Medicus. If the tenant ID is not recognised, the tablet will show a validation message asking you to check the ID and try again. If there is a temporary connection problem, the tablet will show a Pairing unavailable screen with a Try again button. Approving a pairing request Once the tablet has submitted a pairing request, it will appear in Medicus at Modules > Front Door > Kiosks .  Select the kiosk entry to open the View Kiosk panel, which shows the kiosk details. Select Approve pairing request and the tablet will update automatically within a few seconds to show the check-in screen. Rejecting a pairing request If you do not recognise a pairing request or want to decline it, open the View Kiosk panel and select Reject pairing request . The tablet will return to the initial pairing screen. Patient check-in flow Once the kiosk is paired, patients can use it to check in for their appointment. The kiosk walks them through entering their date of birth step by step. First, the patient selects who they are checking in for: Myself or Someone else .  They then select their birth month, their birth day, and finally type in their birth year using the on-screen keyboard. Once the date of birth is entered, the kiosk searches for a face-to-face appointment for that patient today. If a match is found, the kiosk displays the patient's name and appointment time with confirmation that check-in has been completed.  If the room the appointment is held in has check-in instructions, they will be displayed on this page. The screen returns to the start automatically after 10 seconds, or immediately when Next patient is selected. Check-in errors If the kiosk cannot find an appointment for the date of birth entered, it will display a Sorry, we could not check you in message and direct the patient to reception. This can happen in several situations:  \n No appointments were found for that date of birth today \n More than one patient shares that date of birth and have an appointment today \n The patient has multiple appointments today \n \n The appointment has already been started \n In each case, the patient can select Start again to try again or go to reception for help. \n \n Inactivity timeout If a patient stops interacting with the kiosk for 30 seconds, a prompt appears asking Would you like to continue? with a countdown.  The patient can select Yes, continue to carry on, or No, return to start to go back to the beginning. If the countdown reaches zero, the kiosk returns to the start screen automatically. Removing a kiosk To remove a kiosk, go to Modules > Front Door > Kiosks and select the kiosk you want to remove. In the View Kiosk panel, select Remove kiosk and confirm by selecting Yes, remove . The tablet will return to the pairing screen the next time it checks in."}, {"id": 16305115607581, "title": "Managing your Organisation Details", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16305115607581", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose In Medicus, you can view and edit details about your organisation directly from the 'organisation details' module. This guide will provide instructions on how to do this. Viewing your organisation details Navigate to the Organisation Details page by selecting 'Modules' from the left side navigation bar, and then select 'Organisation Details.'   From here, you're able to view basic and contact details relating to your organisation. Editing your organisation details To edit your organisation details, simply select the field you wish to edit. You'll be presented with a pop-up to enter the updated details. Once updated, select 'save changes'. Required fields are marked with an asterisk. Note that if you're updating the organisation telephone and fax numbers, the country code is also required. The ODS code, parent ODS code and tenant identifier fields within the organisation basic details are unable to be updated. These fields are setup by Medicus during implementation and are viewable only."}, {"id": 29586230806301, "title": "XML Schema for Consultation Templates", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/29586230806301", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "XML Schema <?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<xs:schema xmlns:xs=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema\" elementFormDefault=\"qualified\">\n\n <!-- ===== Simple types ===== -->\n <xs:simpleType name=\"snomedCode\">\n <xs:restriction base=\"xs:string\">\n <xs:pattern value=\"[0-9]+\"/>\n <xs:minLength value=\"6\"/>\n </xs:restriction>\n </xs:simpleType>\n\n <xs:simpleType name=\"nonEmptyString\">\n <xs:restriction base=\"xs:string\">\n <xs:minLength value=\"1\"/>\n </xs:restriction>\n </xs:simpleType>\n\n <!-- ===== Attribute groups ===== -->\n <xs:attributeGroup name=\"conditionAttributes\">\n <xs:attribute name=\"else\" type=\"xs:string\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"if\" type=\"xs:string\"/>\n </xs:attributeGroup>\n\n <xs:attributeGroup name=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\">\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"conditionAttributes\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"name\" use=\"required\">\n <xs:simpleType>\n <xs:restriction base=\"xs:ID\">\n <xs:pattern value=\"[A-Za-z][A-Za-z0-9_]+\"/>\n </xs:restriction>\n </xs:simpleType>\n </xs:attribute>\n <xs:attribute name=\"label\" type=\"xs:string\"/>\n </xs:attributeGroup>\n\n <!-- ===== Core container types ===== -->\n <xs:complexType name=\"layoutElementContainerType\">\n <xs:sequence>\n <!-- Permit any of these tags in any order in any number -->\n <xs:choice minOccurs=\"0\" maxOccurs=\"unbounded\">\n <xs:element name=\"section\" type=\"sectionType\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"fieldset\" type=\"fieldsetType\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"infoBanner\" type=\"infoBannerType\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"warningBanner\" type=\"warningBannerType\"/>\n\n <xs:element name=\"checkbox\" type=\"checkboxType\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"checkboxGroup\" type=\"checkboxGroupType\">\n <!-- identity constraint on local element -->\n <xs:key name=\"checkboxOptionValue\">\n <xs:selector xpath=\"./checkboxOption\"/>\n <xs:field xpath=\"@value\"/>\n </xs:key>\n </xs:element>\n\n <xs:element name=\"radioButtons\" type=\"radioButtonsType\">\n <xs:key name=\"radioOptionValue\">\n <xs:selector xpath=\"./radioOption\"/>\n <xs:field xpath=\"@value\"/>\n </xs:key>\n </xs:element>\n\n <xs:element name=\"select\" type=\"selectType\">\n <xs:key name=\"selectOptionValue\">\n <xs:selector xpath=\"./selectOption\"/>\n <xs:field xpath=\"@value\"/>\n </xs:key>\n </xs:element>\n\n <xs:element name=\"textInput\" type=\"textInputType\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"textarea\" type=\"textareaType\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"quantity\" type=\"quantityType\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"date\" type=\"dateType\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"time\" type=\"timeType\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"bloodPressure\" type=\"bloodPressureType\"/>\n\n <xs:element name=\"footer\" type=\"xs:string\"/>\n </xs:choice>\n </xs:sequence>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"topLevelFormElementType\">\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <!-- ===== Root: the ONLY global element... all templates must be in a consultationTemplate tag ===== -->\n <xs:element name=\"consultationTemplate\">\n <xs:complexType>\n <xs:sequence>\n <xs:element name=\"presentingReasonCodes\" type=\"presentingReasonCodesType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"form\" type=\"formType\"/>\n </xs:sequence>\n <xs:attribute name=\"version\" use=\"required\" fixed=\"1.0\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n </xs:element>\n\n <!-- ===== Form with required title ===== -->\n <xs:complexType name=\"formType\">\n <xs:complexContent>\n <xs:extension base=\"layoutElementContainerType\">\n <xs:attribute name=\"title\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n </xs:extension>\n </xs:complexContent>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <!-- ===== Presenting reason codes ===== -->\n <xs:complexType name=\"presentingReasonCodesType\">\n <xs:sequence>\n <xs:element name=\"code\" type=\"snomedCode\" maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n </xs:sequence>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <!-- ===== Layout element types ===== -->\n <xs:complexType name=\"sectionType\">\n <xs:complexContent>\n <xs:extension base=\"layoutElementContainerType\"/>\n </xs:complexContent>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"fieldsetType\">\n <xs:complexContent>\n <xs:extension base=\"layoutElementContainerType\">\n <xs:attribute name=\"title\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n </xs:extension>\n </xs:complexContent>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"infoBannerType\">\n <xs:simpleContent>\n <xs:extension base=\"xs:string\">\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"conditionAttributes\"/>\n </xs:extension>\n </xs:simpleContent>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"warningBannerType\">\n <xs:simpleContent>\n <xs:extension base=\"xs:string\">\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"conditionAttributes\"/>\n </xs:extension>\n </xs:simpleContent>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <!-- ===== Form control types ===== -->\n <xs:complexType name=\"checkboxType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"ifChecked\" type=\"ifCheckedType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n </xs:all>\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"text\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"value\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"checkboxGroupType\">\n <xs:sequence>\n <xs:element name=\"checkboxOption\" type=\"checkboxOptionType\" maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n </xs:sequence>\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"twoColumns\" type=\"xs:boolean\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"checkboxOptionType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"ifChecked\" type=\"ifCheckedType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n </xs:all>\n <xs:attribute name=\"label\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"value\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"radioButtonsType\">\n <xs:sequence>\n <xs:element name=\"radioOption\" type=\"radioOptionType\" maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n </xs:sequence>\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"radioOptionType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"ifChecked\" type=\"ifCheckedType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n </xs:all>\n <xs:attribute name=\"label\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"value\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"selectType\">\n <xs:sequence>\n <xs:element name=\"selectOption\" type=\"selectOptionType\" maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n </xs:sequence>\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"selectOptionType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"ifSelected\" type=\"ifSelectedType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n </xs:all>\n <xs:attribute name=\"label\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"value\" use=\"required\" type=\"nonEmptyString\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"textInputType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"ifTextSet\" type=\"ifTextSetType\"/>\n </xs:all>\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"textareaType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"ifTextSet\" type=\"ifTextSetType\"/>\n </xs:all>\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"quantityType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"ifValueSet\" type=\"ifValueSetType\"/>\n </xs:all>\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"unit\" type=\"xs:string\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"minValue\" type=\"xs:float\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"maxValue\" type=\"xs:float\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"dateType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"ifValueSet\" type=\"ifValueSetType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n </xs:all>\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"maxDate\" type=\"xs:date\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"minDate\" type=\"xs:date\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"timeType\">\n <xs:complexContent>\n <xs:extension base=\"topLevelFormElementType\"/>\n </xs:complexContent>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"bloodPressureType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"ifValueSet\" type=\"ifValueSetType\"/>\n </xs:all>\n <xs:attributeGroup ref=\"topLevelFormElementAttributes\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"decimalPlaces\" type=\"xs:string\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"maxValue\" type=\"xs:float\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"minValue\" type=\"xs:float\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <!-- ===== Conditional blocks ===== -->\n <xs:complexType name=\"ifCheckedType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"careRecordNote\" type=\"careRecordNoteType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"careRecordAllergyIntolerance\" type=\"careRecordAllergyIntoleranceType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n </xs:all>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"ifSelectedType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"careRecordNote\" type=\"careRecordNoteType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n <xs:element name=\"careRecordAllergyIntolerance\" type=\"careRecordAllergyIntoleranceType\" minOccurs=\"0\"/>\n </xs:all>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"ifTextSetType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"careRecordNote\" type=\"careRecordNoteType\"/>\n </xs:all>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"ifValueSetType\">\n <xs:all>\n <xs:element name=\"careRecordObservation\" type=\"careRecordObservationType\"/>\n </xs:all>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <!-- ===== Care record elements ===== -->\n <xs:complexType name=\"careRecordNoteType\">\n <xs:attribute name=\"code\" type=\"snomedCode\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"heading\" use=\"required\" type=\"snomedCode\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"note\" type=\"xs:string\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"careRecordAllergyIntoleranceType\">\n <xs:attribute name=\"code\" type=\"snomedCode\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"heading\" use=\"required\" type=\"snomedCode\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n <xs:complexType name=\"careRecordObservationType\">\n <xs:attribute name=\"code\" use=\"required\" type=\"snomedCode\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"heading\" use=\"required\" type=\"snomedCode\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"unitOfMeasure\" type=\"snomedCode\"/>\n <xs:attribute name=\"additionalInformation\" type=\"xs:string\"/>\n </xs:complexType>\n\n</xs:schema>   Template Structure Explained (Plain English) Root Element Every template must be wrapped in a <consultationTemplate version=\"1.0\"> tag. It contains two children: \n \n <presentingReasonCodes> (optional) — one or more SNOMED CT codes indicating why the patient is presenting - this is used to prompt the user to use the template when they enter the presenting reason into their consultation \n \n <form> (required) — the form itself, which must have a title \n \n Layout Elements Forms are built by nesting these structural elements: \n \n \n \n \n \n Element \n Purpose \n \n \n \n <section> \n A grouping container with no title \n \n \n <fieldset> \n A titled grouping container \n \n \n <infoBanner> \n Inline informational message \n \n \n <warningBanner> \n Inline warning message \n \n \n <footer> \n Plain text footer \n \n \n Sections and fieldsets can be nested and can contain any combination of layout and input elements. Input Controls These are the form fields available to collect clinical data: \n \n Element \n Key Attributes \n \n \n \n <checkbox> \n \n name , label , text , value \n \n \n \n <checkboxGroup> \n \n name , label , twoColumns — contains <checkboxOption> children \n \n \n <radioButtons> \n \n name , label — contains <radioOption> children \n \n \n <select> \n \n name , label — contains <selectOption> children \n \n \n <textInput> \n \n name , label \n \n \n \n <textarea> \n \n name , label \n \n \n \n <quantity> \n \n name , label , unit , minValue , maxValue \n \n \n \n <date> \n \n name , label , minDate , maxDate \n \n \n \n <time> \n \n name , label \n \n \n \n <bloodPressure> \n \n name , label , minValue , maxValue , decimalPlaces \n \n \n \n All top-level input elements share a required name attribute (must start with a letter and contain only letters, numbers, and underscores). Option values within <checkboxGroup> , <radioButtons> , and <select> must be unique within their parent. Conditional Blocks Each input element can trigger actions when a value is set, using a conditional child element: \n \n Trigger Element \n Used On \n Can Contain \n \n \n \n <ifChecked> \n \n checkbox , checkboxOption , radioOption \n \n \n careRecordNote , careRecordAllergyIntolerance \n \n \n \n <ifSelected> \n selectOption \n \n careRecordNote , careRecordAllergyIntolerance \n \n \n \n <ifTextSet> \n \n textInput , textarea \n \n careRecordNote \n \n \n <ifValueSet> \n \n quantity , date , bloodPressure \n \n careRecordObservation \n \n \n Care Record Writes These define what gets written to the patient's care record when a condition is met: \n \n <careRecordNote> — writes a coded note; requires a heading SNOMED code, with optional code and note text \n \n <careRecordAllergyIntolerance> — records an allergy or intolerance; requires a heading SNOMED code with optional code \n \n \n <careRecordObservation> — records a clinical observation (e.g. blood pressure, a quantity); requires both code and heading SNOMED codes, with optional unitOfMeasure and additionalInformation \n \n SNOMED Codes Any attribute typed as a SNOMED code must be a numeric string of at least 6 digits."}, {"id": 21550803681565, "title": "Task Lists", "section": "Medicus Overview, Navigation & Tasks", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21550803681565", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose You can access any task lists from your Medicus homepage. This user guide will show you how to access and view task lists. Task lists You can select a task list from your homepage which contains tasks assigned only to you or a team that you are in. Organisation wide task lists can be accessed from within the Workflow module. Each task list is title with the task type followed by the assignee in brackets. Task lists are ordered by: \n Priority -  high priority tasks are moved to the top. \n \n Due date -  overdue tasks will appear before tasks which are due at a later date. \n \n Creation date \n This is to ensure the most important tasks are moved to the top and worked on first. You can also filter the list on the right hand side of the page. By default task lists only show open tasks, but you can amend this using the filters on the right if you wish to do so."}, {"id": 33024183876381, "title": "How to mark a patient as deceased - NHS Practices", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/33024183876381", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose When a patient has passed away, you will need to mark the patient as deceased in their medical record. This article will show you how to mark a patient as deceased in Medicus for NHS practices. In England, a patient can be marked as deceased on Medicus in one of two ways: \n By a user manually recording the patient as deceased (informal notification of death) \n Via a PDS update (formal notification of death) - the NHS learned of the death via the National Records Office and updated the PDS. \n Manually marking a patient as deceased Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. From the patient's administrative record, scroll to the bottom and you will see the option to Record Patient's Death. Here you are required to enter the Date of Death and Time of Death (optional). This action will record the patient as deceased with a death notification as \"informal\", update the PDS and request deduction from Primary Care Support England. Once recorded, the death information will be stored in the patient's administrative record. A patient de-registration task (which alerts the practice to cancel upcoming appointments, resolve incomplete tasks etc.) will be raised after NHAIS has sent a deduction (i.e. confirmed the deduction request). Practices should maintain a local process if you need to take action to prevent e.g. notification of upcoming appointments prior to this confirmation from NHAIS being received. Cancelling a deduction request To cancel a patient deduction request, from the Administration Record, select Record patient as not deceased.  This will decouple the the PDS link which stops any more updates happening between the local record and the PDS.  You will need to cancel the patient deduction request which you have sent to PCSE via Medicus, by either emailing the registrations team at:  pcse.registrations-preston@nhs.net putting ‘ Cancellation of deduction request’  in the email subject line, or calling PCSE on 0333 014 2884."}, {"id": 21064234706205, "title": "Requesting Investigations and Tests", "section": "Investigations Requesting & Results", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21064234706205", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n If you need to request any laboratory tests, screening tests, radiology or imaging investigations you can send these from Medicus. The majority of investigation requests and results are recieved via the MESH mailbox. This user guide will show you how to request an investigation from Medicus. \n Requesting an investigation \n There are two ways to create a new prescription in Medicus: \n \n From a patient's care record. \n From a consultation. \n \n Creating an investigation request from a patient's care record \n To create an investigation request from the care record, select the 'Actions' dropdown menu in the right hand corner of the patient record. Select 'Investigation request' from the list. \n \n This will open up the investigation request options form. \n Creating an investigation request from a consultation \n To request an investigation whilst completing a new consultation form you can either: \n 1. Select 'Investigation request' from the 'More actions' dropdown list. \n 2. Use / as a shortcut to open up the actions menu and select 'Investigation request'. \n \n This will open up the investigation request options form. \n Here you can will have the option to launch the Order Comms system you typically use (e.g. ICE or tQuest) and order investigations in the same way you do now. \n Awaiting results \n Requested investigations will be visible on the Patient Journal with the 'Awaiting Results' label."}, {"id": 20588903518877, "title": "Receiving, Reviewing & Filing Investigation Results", "section": "Investigations Requesting & Results", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20588903518877", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n When investigation results are received in the MESH mailbox, Medicus will create a 'Review Investigation Results Task' ready for review and filing. This user guide will show you how to review and actions investigation results. \n Matching to a patient \n The investigation report should match to a patient automatically, however, if Medicus was unable to do this, the report will be found in the 'Unmatched Investigation Results' task list and a banner will be displayed at the top of the task. \n You'll need to either match the report to a registered patient or discard the report. \n \n Selecting 'Match to patient' opens up the patient finder for you to search and select a patient to match the investigation report to. \n \n Before matching the report, Medicus will display a side by side comparison of the details in the report and the selected patient so you can check and confirm this is the correct patient before proceeding. \n \n Once matched, the task will be moved into the 'Investigation Results' task list. \n Removing a matched patient \n If there is a scenario where in investigation report has been matched to the wrong patient, then you can remove the matched patient ID from the report. \n To do this, select 'Remove matched patient' from the actions menu. \n \n This will open up a pop-out form for you to confirm you'd like to proceed before removing the matched patient. \n Reviewing and filing \n The task is displayed with the investigation report on the left hand side and the task details on the right. \n When an investigation result comes with a reference range, Medicus compares the results to the stated reference range and if the result is outside the range then the task is set to high priority.  \n Note: if the results has many references Medicus will not make a comparison. \n \n \n Filing comments can be added to individual investigation results or the whole report. \n You can click  Normal Result, no action required  to quickly add this as a filing comment or can selct a different 'quick filing comment' from a dropdown list for ease.  \n   \n If there is  Outstanding Investigation Requests,  you can choose to match the result to the corresponding request. \n   \n You can also do this if the result has already been filed. From the patient journal, click  View Report  on the filed result. \n Then click on the pencil icon next to  Investigation Requests  and you will be able to select the request you want to match the result to. \n \n   \n Once you've completed your review, added your filing comments and completed any follow on actions, select 'File results'. \n This will file the investigation against the patient's record. Selecting 'View Results' from the journal entry will open up details of the filed report. \n \n Discarding a report \n You may need to discard a report if the patient was not registered at the practice. Discarding a report will set the filing status to 'Discarded' and the task will be resolved. \n Selecting 'Discard report' button will open up a pop-out form where you'll need to provide a reason before discarding. \n \n If you need to recover the discarded report later, it's possible to do so. You can filter the task list by discarded and recover the discarded task from there."}, {"id": 28405883567261, "title": "Creating Consultation Templates", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/28405883567261", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Overview Consultation templates are effectively custom forms that appear on the left hand side of a consultation. You can define the layout, elements (like checkboxes, text inputs, and banners), and associated conditions (e.g. insert a code into the record). Whilst we publish our own \"out of the box\" templates (e.g. for Asthma Reviews), practices sometimes want to create their own templates either for themselves or for sharing with others. To create a Consultation Template go to the Consultation module and select Templates > Create template.    Getting Started 1 ) Our consultation template feature uses a simple XML schema to define the content which is then dynamically rendered in the Medicus user interface (so you'll need to be able to understand simple XML like this): <checkbox name=\"50e51f076881431f9e5b8cc7d552a9d3\" value=\"I have given advice about quitting smoking today\"> \n <ifChecked> \n <careRecordNote heading=\"Concept ID\" code=\"Concept ID\" note=\"Your free text note\" /> \n </ifChecked> \n</checkbox> 2 ) It is much easier to write templates if you have a text editor that has the XML schema (XSD) configured because this will suggest the different elements of a template for you as you type OR we have found that tools such as Claude or ChatGPT are good at converting a specification for the template into the XML structure if you provide the tool with your specification and the Medicus XSD.   \n \n Setting up the Consultation Template Schema in VS Code \n \n Using an XSD in Visual Studio Code (VS Code) to validate XML files and enable autocomplete is relatively straightforward. \n Follow these steps to set it up: \n 1. Install VS Code \n \n Download VS code \n 2. Install the XML Extension in VS Code \n \n \n Open VS Code. \n Go to the Extensions view ( Ctrl+Shift+X or Cmd+Shift+X on Mac) \n Search for and install the XML extension (e.g., \"XML\" by Red Hat) \n \n 3. Add the Consultation Template XML Schema \n \n \n Create a new XML file in VS Code called ConsultationTemplate.xsd \n Add the XML content from this support article \n \n Save it somewhere on your computer \n \n 4. Reference the XSD in Your Consultation Template \n \n \n Create a new XML file which you will write your first template in \n Paste this starting point of a consultation template into your file \n \n <?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\"?>\n<consultationTemplate version=\"1.0\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation=\"path/to/your-schema.xsd\">\n\n<presentingReasonCodes>\n <code></code>\n</presentingReasonCodes>\n\n<form title=\"\">\n \n</form>\n\n</consultationTemplate> \n Go to your ConsultationTemplate.xsd file, right click on the tab and click “Copy relative path” \n \n Replace path/to/your-schema.xsd with the relative path to your XSD file. For example: /Users/timgray/ConsultationTemplate.xsd \n \n If you have setup the schema correctly then you should start to get autocomplete suggestions \n Errors or warnings will appear in the Problems tab ( Ctrl+Shift+M or Cmd+Shift+M on Mac) if the XML doesn't comply with the XSD \n Hover over the highlighted issues to see detailed error messages \n \n You are now setup to start making templates. \n   \n \n Starting Your Template XML File \n Make sure you have followed the steps to setup VS Code for using our XML schema first, it will make writing templates easier. \n Every XML file should begin with this line: \n <?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\"?> \n Then, add the root element <consultationTemplate> to begin the structure of your template. It should include the version number (which is currently 1.0): \n <consultationTemplate version=\"1.0\"> \n <!-- Content goes here --> \n</consultationTemplate> \n \n \n \n Note: If you are using schema validation (explained above then the XML will look like this instead: \n \n <consultationTemplate version=\"1.0\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation=\"/Users/timgray/consultationTemplate.xsd\">\n <!-- Content goes here --> \n</consultationTemplate> \n   \n   \n Adding a Form \n Inside the <consultationTemplate> , you need a <form> element. The form must have a title: \n <form title=\"Example Form Title\"> \n <!-- Form elements go here --> \n</form> \n \n   \n Adding Layout Elements \n You can use layout elements like sections, fieldsets to organize your form. For example: \n <form title=\"Patient Form\"> \n <section>\n <fieldset title=\"\">\n <!-- Add form elements like textInput, date, etc. -->\n </fieldset>\n </section> \n</form> \n Sections are only needed for more complex templates. It is best to ignore them when getting started. \n Fieldsets apply a header and a borderline around the group of form elements. \n   \n Adding Form Elements \n You can include different types of inputs or information, such as: \n Text Input \n <textInput name=\"patientName\" label=\"Patient Name\" /> \n \n Select Dropdown \n <select name=\"gender\" label=\"Gender\"> \n <selectOption label=\"Male\" value=\"M\" /> \n <selectOption label=\"Female\" value=\"F\" /> \n</select> \n   \n [within a <form> , type < to see what available elements there are]: \n More specialist elements: \n Blood pressure \n Blood pressures are specialist elements. The example below can be copied and pasted for ease but shows the exact structure of a blood pressure element: \n <bloodPressure name=\"v09af945dfc4049929375e2facae43172\" label=\"Blood pressure\">\n <ifValueSet>\n <careRecordObservation heading=\"715851000000102\" code=\"75367002\" unitOfMeasure=\"259018001\"/>\n </ifValueSet>\n</bloodPressure> \n Quantity \n Quantity allows you to insert a range of different observations. The example below can be copied and pasted for ease but shows the exact structure of an observation such as BMI: \n <quantity name=\"v0cb19274a1704d1aaac9850d2fd95dec\" label=\"BMI\" unit=\"kg/sq. m\">\n <ifValueSet>\n <careRecordObservation heading=\"715851000000102\" code=\"60621009\" unitOfMeasure=\"258896009\"/>\n </ifValueSet>\n</quantity> \n   \n Adding Conditions \n Some elements can have conditions based on user actions: \n Example: Insert a coded if a checkbox is selected \n <checkbox name=\"allergyCheck\" value=\"I have given advice about quitting smoking today\"> \n <ifChecked> \n <careRecordNote heading=\"Concept ID\" code=\"Concept ID\" note=\"Your free text note\" /> \n </ifChecked> \n</checkbox> \n   \n Attributes Names & Values \n Most elements require a name which is the unique reference to the element within the template. \n The name: \n \n Can’t start with a number \n Must be unique \n \n The best way to generate them is to use Online GUID Generator Tool and then type a letter before you paste in the UUID. \n For example: v0cb7c209ae02426693db980306cbc919 . This just means that you will always have a unique name. The XML will fail validation if the name isn’t unique or in the right format. \n Some elements also require a value (e.g. radio options). This is how the particular form control is referenced (e.g. how Medicus knows that you selected “Yes” and not “No”. \n The easiest thing is to adhere to the same principles as name . \n   \n Example Template \n Here’s an example to see what it looks like as you start to build out a template: \n <?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\"?>\n<consultationTemplate version=\"1.0\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation=\"/Users/timgray/consultationTemplate.xsd\">\n\n<presentingReasonCodes>\n <code></code>\n</presentingReasonCodes>\n\n<form title=\"Title\">\n\n<fieldset title=\"Fieldset\">\n\n <checkbox name=\"v0cb7c209-ae02-4266-93db-980306cbc919\" text=\"Test checkbox\" value=\"v2tw7c209-ae02-2953-93db-980306cbc871\">\n <ifChecked>\n <careRecordNote heading=\"\" code=\"\" note=\"\"/>\n </ifChecked>\n </checkbox>\n\n <textInput name=\"v8e802dee-0930-48de-aab2-a73b710505b8\" label=\"Test input\">\n <ifTextSet>\n <careRecordNote heading=\"\" code=\"\" note=\"\"/>\n </ifTextSet>\n </textInput>\n\n <textarea name=\"v22b07d29-d30e-459b-a650-2e202fc7424b\">\n <ifTextSet>\n <careRecordNote heading=\"\" code=\"\" note=\"\"/>\n </ifTextSet>\n </textarea>\n\n <date name=\"v5a835843-8200-4840-b73a-0908fcc11e9a\" label=\"Test date picker\">\n <ifValueSet>\n <careRecordObservation heading=\"\" code=\"\" unitOfMeasure=\"\"/>\n </ifValueSet>\n </date>\n\n <bloodPressure name=\"v252268ea-ff0c-4e9e-9287-4a3aaaff0148\">\n <ifValueSet>\n <careRecordObservation heading=\"\" code=\"\" unitOfMeasure=\"\"/>\n </ifValueSet>\n </bloodPressure>\n\n <select name=\"vad1919e7-6f5c-417a-ad53-7bed7498b359\" label=\"Test select\">\n <selectOption label=\"\" value=\"va83cddf4-89ab-4c9b-b0d3-e2dd763be335\">\n <ifSelected>\n <careRecordNote heading=\"\" code=\"\" note=\"\"/>\n </ifSelected>\n </selectOption>\n </select>\n\n <quantity name=\"vbf2d7b87-854b-4723-922d-2aa51c09a0c8\" label=\"Test observation\">\n <ifValueSet>\n <careRecordObservation heading=\"\" code=\"\" unitOfMeasure=\"\"/>\n </ifValueSet>\n </quantity>\n\n</fieldset>\n\n</form>\n\n</consultationTemplate>"}, {"id": 34913065552029, "title": "Managing Subscribed Questionnaires", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34913065552029", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains how to preview and manage the questionnaire templates your organisation has access to through subscribed content packages. These features include: Preview latest version: Allows you to view how a subscribed questionnaire template will appear to patients before deciding whether to use it. Hide from use: Allows you to prevent a specific subscribed questionnaire template from appearing as an option when sending communications, without unsubscribing from the package it belongs to. Previewing a subscribed questionnaire template You can preview subscribed questionnaire templates to see how it will appear to patients before using it in a communication. This is useful when you are subscribed to multiple similar questionnaires and you want to compare them before deciding which to use. To preview a template, go to Modules > Communications > Patient Questionnaire Templates and select the Subscribed Templates tab.  Select the template you want to view. On the template page, select Preview latest version and the questionnaire will open in a new browser tab. Hiding and unhiding a questionnaire template Hiding a template from use If multiple subscribed packages include similar questionnaires, you can hide individual templates to avoid duplicate options appearing when staff send communications. To hide a template, go to Modules > Communications > Patient Questionnaire Templates , select the Subscribed Templates tab, and open the template.  Select Hide from use and confirm by selecting Yes, hide . The template will no longer appear when inserting a questionnaire into a communication, and a Hidden from use tag will appear next to it in the Subscribed Templates list.   To filter the list by status, use the Available for use filter and select either Available or Hidden . Making a hidden template available again Open the hidden template from the Subscribed Templates tab and select Make available for use from the banner at the top of the page. The template will be available again immediately when inserting questionnaires into communications."}, {"id": 18421463712413, "title": "Marking a Consultation as Incorrect or Hidden", "section": "Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18421463712413", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose If a mistake has been made during a consultation, elements of the consultation or whole consultations can be marked as incorrect in Medicus. They can also be hidden, which removes the consultation from the patient's record. This user guide will show you how to mark a consultation as incorrect or hidden. Marking a consultation as incorrect From the care record, select the consultation that should be marked as incorrect. This will open up the View Consultation form. Select Edit consultation to proceed. This will open up the Edit Consultation form. Scroll to the bottom and open the More actions list. Select Mark elements as incorrect. The Mark as Incorrect pop-out contains three options: Whole consultation - The entire consultation is incorrect. Specific topics - One or more consultation topics is incorrect. Specific headings - One or more of history, examination, assessment and plan is incorrect. Selecting an element from the list will open up additional details to enter. If you've select specific topics or headings, you'll be ask to specify these. You'll also be prompted to enter a reason in the free text box. Leaving the visibility as Mark as incorrect only will leave the original entry as visible but greyed out. Hiding an incorrect consultation In scenarios where a consultation needs removing from a patient's record, for example if a consultation was added to the wrong patient record, then select Remove from record in the visibility section. You'll need to confirm that you want to proceed with this action before saving."}, {"id": 34752604337693, "title": "Managing Clinical Cases", "section": "Clinical Cases", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34752604337693", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains how to create, view, update, link care to, and close Clinical Cases in Medicus. Clinical Cases are available to Community Services. Before using them, your administrator will need to have set up at least one case type — see Configuring Clinical Cases for guidance on this. This article covers: Creating and managing cases: Allows staff to open a clinical case for a patient, update its details, and close it when the care episode is complete. Linking care to a case: Allows appointments, consultations, documents, communications, and individual care record elements to be connected to a clinical case for accurate reporting. Creating a clinical case Go to Modules > Clinical Cases > Open Cases and select New case . Search for and select the patient. If they already have a record in Medicus, the case will be linked to it automatically. If not, a new patient record will be created first. Once the patient is confirmed, the New Clinical Case form will open. Select a Case type from the dropdown - only active types are shown, and if only one exists it will be pre-selected.  If the chosen case type requires a commissioned service, the Commissioned service field will be mandatory; otherwise it's optional. If only one active commissioned service exists, it will be pre-selected automatically. You can add free-text notes in Additional details if needed. Select Create case to save and you'll be returned to the Open Cases page where the new case will appear in the list. Editing a clinical case Open the case from Open Cases , Closed Cases , or the patient's Administrative Record and select the edit icon on the View Clinical Case slideover. Update the case type, commissioned service, or additional details and select Save changes . Viewing clinical cases Open cases To see all currently open cases across your organisation, go to Modules > Clinical Cases > Open Cases . Cases are listed oldest first. Select any case to open the View Clinical Case slideover, which shows the case type, commissioned service, status, additional details, and an audit history. Closed cases Go to Modules > Clinical Cases > Closed Cases to see all completed cases, listed most recently closed first. The closed case view includes the same details as an open case, plus who closed it and when. Cases on a patient's record You can view all cases for a specific patient from their Administrative Record . Select the Clinical Cases tab to see all open and closed cases.  Linking care to a clinical case Via an appointment When booking an appointment, a Linked Clinical Case field appears on the form for Community Service organisations. If the appointment service requires a clinical case, this field is mandatory; otherwise it's optional. Select the relevant case from the dropdown - both open and closed cases are shown, labelled with their type and date. If the patient has only one open case, it will be pre-filled. When the encounter is started from the appointment, it automatically inherits the linked case. Via a consultation When creating or editing a consultation, a Clinical case field is available. If the patient has one open case, it will be pre-filled.  All care record elements created within the consultation will inherit the same case. If you update the case on the consultation later, all linked care record elements will update to match. Via an inbound document A Clinical case field is available in the Document Details section of a Document for Action . Select the edit icon to update it -any care record elements linked to the document will inherit the case. Via a communication Any booking links, questionnaires, and questionnaire responses created from a communication automatically inherit the clinical case linked to that communication. Linking ad-hoc care record elements When creating a care record element outside of an appointment or consultation, a Clinical Case field will appear on the form for Community Service organisations.  If the patient has only one active case, it will be pre-filled. Both open and closed cases are available to select.  Closing a clinical case To close a case, open it from Open Cases or the patient's Administrative Record and select Close case in the View Clinical Case slideover. In the Close Clinical Case form, the Closed date time is pre-filled with the current date and time. You can change this to a past date if needed, but a future date cannot be set. Select Close case to confirm. The case status will change to Closed, it will move from Open Cases to Closed Cases , and the closing practitioner and date will be recorded on the case. See Configuring Clinical Cases for setting up case types, commissioned services, and appointment service requirements."}, {"id": 34752067244573, "title": "Configuring Clinical Cases", "section": "Clinical Cases", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34752067244573", "roles": ["ANP", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains how to configure Clinical Cases in Medicus. Clinical Cases are available to Community Services . Before staff can start creating cases, an administrator needs to set up case types and, where relevant, commissioned services. This article covers: Case Types: Allows you to define the categories of clinical case your organisation uses and control whether each type requires a link to a commissioned service. Commissioned Services: Allows you to configure the NHS service agreements under which care is delivered, supporting accurate reporting and payment. Appointment Service settings: Allows you to make linking a clinical case mandatory when booking appointments for a specific service. Case types Case types let you categorise the different kinds of care your organisation provides - for example, ADHD Assessment or ASD Assessment. To manage them, go to Modules > Clinical Cases > Case Configuration. Adding a case type Select Add case type to add a new case type. Enter a unique name for the case type - this is what staff will see when creating a new case.  Under Commissioned Service requirements , tick Require link to a commissioned service if care under this type is delivered through an NHS agreement. When enabled, staff will need to select a commissioned service before they can save a case of this type. Leave it unticked for private or non-commissioned care. Select Save and the new case type will appear on the configuration page. Editing a case type Select a case type from the list to open its details, then select the edit icon. Update the name or commissioned service requirement and select Save changes . Existing cases linked to this type are not affected. Archiving a case type If a case type is no longer needed, select it from the case type list and choose Archive , then confirm by selecting Yes, archive . The case type will be removed from the configuration page and will no longer be available when creating new cases. Existing cases like to the case type are not affected. Commissioned services Commissioned services represent the NHS service agreements your organisation operates under. To manage them, go to Modules > Clinical Cases > Case Configuration. Adding a commissioned service Select Add service to open the form. Enter a unique name for the service (e.g. \"ADHD Assessments - Dorset ICB\") and the NHS Service Agreement Identifier. This is the unique code for your service agreement. Both must be unique across your active commissioned services. Use the Commissioning Organisation field to search for and select the organisation responsible for the contract. Select Add service to save, and the service will appear on the configuration page. Editing a commissioned service Select a commissioned service from the list and use the edit icon to open the Edit Commissioned Service form. Update the name, service agreement identifier, or commissioning organisation and select Save changes . Archiving a commissioned service Select the commissioned service, choose Archive , and confirm by selecting Yes, archive . The service will be removed from the configuration page and can no longer be selected for new cases. Existing cases linked to the commissioned service are not affected. Requiring a clinical case for appointments When setting up an appointment service, you can make linking a clinical case mandatory for all bookings under that service. This is useful where every appointment is part of a commissioned care pathway. When creating or editing an Appointment Service , tick Require link to a clinical case under Clinical case requirements . Staff booking appointments for this service will then need to select a case before they can save the booking. See Managing Clinical Cases for creating, viewing, linking, and closing cases."}, {"id": 34996558762653, "title": "Managing Tasks During Staff Absence", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34996558762653", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains the options available in Medicus for managing tasks when recording a staff absence. These features include: Task reassignment: Reassign incomplete tasks at the point of recording an absence. Task cover: Nominate a colleague to see the absent staff member's tasks on their own homepage for the duration of the absence. Task reassignment When you record an absence, Medicus checks whether the user has any outstanding tasks so that you have the option to reassign them to another member of staff. To record an absence, go to the staff member's profile by going to Modules > Staff and User Management > Staff List. Find the staff member's profile and then select Absence > New absence. If the staff member has incomplete tasks, an Incomplete Tasks section appears. Use the Reassign to field for each task type to move them to another staff member or team. It's not required to reassign all task types. Select Record absence to save. Setting task cover At the bottom of the Record Staff Absence form, select the checkbox in the Task Cover section, then use the Staff providing cover picker to choose a colleague. Any active staff member can be selected. Select Record absence to save. Note: Task cover only applies to tasks assigned directly to the absent staff member, not tasks assigned to their teams. Medicus also does not notify the covering staff member automatically. Let them know separately using your usual processes. How task cover appears on the covering staff member's homepage During the absence, the covering staff member sees an additional task group on their homepage labelled with the absent staff member's name, for example Dr Dawn Armstrong's Tasks. Once the absence ends, this group is removed automatically. Editing task cover To add or change task cover after an absence has been recorded, go to the staff member's Absences tab and select the absence to open the Edit Staff Absence slideover. If cover is already set, the covering staff member will be pre-populated in the picker. Viewing task cover from the staff record The All Absences table on a staff member's Absences tab includes a Task cover provided by column. If no cover is set, a dash is displayed."}, {"id": 34914311366429, "title": "Setting up a Call-In Board", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34914311366429", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n This article explains how to set up and use the Medicus call-in board, which allows clinicians to notify waiting patients when they are ready to be seen. These features include: \n Adding a call-in board: Set up a new board linked to a specific site, so that patient call-ins are displayed on a TV screen in your waiting area. \n Calling a patient in: Notify a patient from the Appointment Lobby that their clinician is ready by their name and room to appearing on the waiting room screen. \n YouTube playlist integration: Play a YouTube playlist on the call-in board screen. \n Editing and removing a board: Update a board's name or YouTube settings, or remove a board that is no longer in use. \n \n Setting up a call-in board \n The call-in board works on any smart TV that can run an internet browser, including the built-in browser on Samsung TVs. \n Adding a new board \n To add a call-in board, go to Modules > Front Door > Call-In Boards and select Add call-in board .  \n Enter a name for the board (for example, \"Downstairs waiting room\") and select the site it belongs to from the Site dropdown. If you want to display a YouTube playlist on the screen, you can also enter a YouTube playlist ID at this stage. This is optional and can be added or changed later. \n Select Add and the board will be created.  \n Select the board from the list and View Call-In Board panel will open, showing the board's details and its launch URL. \n Setting up the board on the TV \n Once the board has been created, copy the launch URL shown in the View Call-In Board panel and enter it into the browser on your waiting room TV. \n When the URL is first loaded, the TV screen will display a Pending IP Address Approval message. This is expected. Return to Medicus and select the board from the list.  \n You will see a banner asking you to approve the TV's IP address. Select the link in the banner to add it to the allowed list. \n You will then need to activate the board by selecting Activate board. \n Auto-starting the board on a Windows mini PC \n If you are using a Windows mini PC to run the call-in board, you can configure it to open automatically when the PC starts up. \n In the user's Documents folder, right-click and select New > Shortcut .  \n For the shortcut location, enter the following, replacing <CALL-IN-BOARD-URL> with your board's launch URL: \n \"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Microsoft\\Edge\\Application\\msedge.exe\" -kiosk --edge-kiosk-type=fullscreen --autoplay-policy=no-user-gesture-required <CALL-IN-BOARD-URL> \n Name the shortcut Medicus Call-In Board , then copy it into the following folder (Administrator privileges are required): \n C:\\ProgramData\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Start Menu\\Programs\\Startup \n Note that the user will still need to be logged in when the PC first boots up. \n \n Calling a patient in \n When a clinician is ready to see a patient, they can notify them from the Appointment Lobby. The Call patient in button appears on the left of Patient present - start consultation when the appointment is face-to-face and a call-in board is active at the appointment's location. \n Select Call patient in and the patient's name and room will appear on the waiting room screen. A notification will confirm the patient was called in. \n If the Call patient in button is greyed out, hovering over it will show the reason, for example if the appointment has no site, if it is not a face-to-face appointment, or if the patient has already been called in. \n The patient's name is removed from the screen automatically when the clinician selects Patient present - start consultation and the consultation begins. \n \n YouTube playlist integration \n You can set up a YouTube playlist to play on the call-in board screen when no patients are waiting. This is useful for displaying health information videos in the waiting room. \n To add or update a playlist, open the board from Modules > Front Door > Call-In Boards and select the edit icon. Enter the playlist ID in the YouTube playlist ID field. The playlist ID is the part of the playlist URL that appears after ?list= . \n Some browsers block video autoplay with sound. If the playlist does not start automatically, select the edit icon on the board, check Mute audio under Extra Settings. You can also enable Enable closed captions if preferred and then select Save changes. After saving, refresh the TV screen and the playlist will play automatically. \n The playlist will play on the left side of the screen, with the list of called-in patients shown on the right. The video plays automatically on a loop when the board loads. \n \n Editing a call-in board \n To edit a board's name or YouTube settings, go to Modules > Front Door > Call-In Boards and select the board. Select the edit icon in the View Call-In Board panel, make your changes, and select Save changes . \n Note that the site a board is linked to cannot be changed after the board has been created. \n \n Removing a call-in board \n To remove a board, go to Modules > Front Door > Call-In Boards and open it from the list of call-in boards. Select Remove board and c onfirm by selecting Yes, remove . The TV screen will update at its next check-in and display a message that the board has been removed."}, {"id": 34992504498461, "title": "Inactive Patient Records and Privacy Officer Alerts", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34992504498461", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains how Medicus handles access to inactive patient records and how your practice's privacy officer can review and acknowledge access alerts. These features include: Inactive patient access restrictions: When a staff member attempts to view an inactive patient's record, Medicus restricts access and requires a reason before allowing entry. An alert is automatically sent to the nominated privacy officer. Privacy officer alert tasks: A dedicated task type that allows your privacy officer to review, audit, and acknowledge instances of inactive patient record access. Inactive patient records What is an inactive patient? A patient is considered active in Medicus if they have an active registration at your organisation (permanent, temporary, or immediate necessary treatment), or if they have an open clinical case (for Community Providers) or safeguarding case (for Safeguarding teams). Any patient who does not meet these criteria is treated as inactive. When a patient becomes inactive, their record is retained but access to it is restricted. This supports good information governance by ensuring that inactive records are only opened when there is a legitimate reason to do so. Accessing an inactive patient's record If you attempt to open an inactive patient's record, Medicus will display an Inactive Patient - Access Restricted modal before allowing you to open the record. You will need to select a reason for access and provide a short justification. The available reasons are: \n Patient consent \n Legal \n Emergency \n Once you submit, a privacy officer alert task is created and you will be able to view the record. Access is then permitted for the following 24 hours without needing to submit another reason. Note: If your organisation is a safeguarding service, the reason is automatically set to Legal and you only need to provide a free text justification. What access is and is not restricted The restriction applies to the main patient record pages, any task tab that displays the detailed patient record, and starting, editing, or viewing a consultation for that patient. Access is not restricted for patient search results, clinical audit reports, or viewing tasks about the patient (except the patient record tab itself). Inactive patients will still appear by name in search results. Privacy officer alerts What is a privacy officer? A privacy officer is the staff member responsible for reviewing instances of inactive patient record access. They receive a task each time a staff member accesses an inactive patient's record, allowing the practice to audit and uphold information governance standards. Assigning a privacy officer A privacy officer is assigned by setting a staff member as the default task assignee for privacy officer alert tasks. See here for information on how to assign tasks to teams or specific team members. Reviewing privacy officer alert tasks Privacy officer alert tasks appear in Workflow > Data Privacy > Privacy Officer Alerts, as well as on the homepage if the task is assigned to you. Each task includes the patient whose record was accessed, the staff member who accessed it, the date and time of access, the type of access, the reason given, and the free text justification provided. You can filter the task list by status, access type, date and time range, the staff member who accessed the record, or the patient accessed. Acknowledging a task To review an alert, select it from the list. Once you have reviewed, select Acknowledge to mark it as complete."}, {"id": 17689079117725, "title": "Adding a New Appointment Provider to Enable Cross-Organisation Appointments", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17689079117725", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose Through GP Connect, you are able to book appointments at other practices directly from Medicus. For example, if after a consultation a patient needs to be booked into a service not available at your practice, but available at a local practice that you have a relationship with, you can book their appointment directly. To do this, the other practice needs to be configured as an additional appointment provider within the system. This user guide will show you how to add and manage other appointment providers in Medicus to enable cross-organisation appointments. Once in the scheduling module, select Other Scheduling Setup on the left hand side navigation bar. Adding a new appointment provider Adding a new appointment provider requires the Operational Management permission. To add a new appointment provider, select the New dropdown button and then Appointment provider to open up the Add Appointment Provider form. Search for the organisation you'd like to add and select save. Once successfully saved, you'll now be able to book and manage appointments at this organisation for your patients. If appointments were available to your practice to book, but all of the available slots have been taken, the appointment service won't show as available in your external appointment list.  When adding a provider, it's important the provider is set up for GP Connect Appointment Booking to enable cross-organisation appointment management. If a provider is not set up, you will be unable to add them as an appointment provider. Viewing or removing an existing provider To view additional details or remove an existing appointment provider, simply select the appointment provider from the current providers list to open up additional details on the right hand side of the screen. Select Remove Provider if you'd like to remove the provider."}, {"id": 34201303263517, "title": "Appointment Communications", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34201303263517", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose When you book or management a patient's appointment, depending on what communication preferences have been stored for that patient, they will receive communications via their preferred channel to keep them informed. This user guide will show you how Medicus sends communications to patient's about their appointment. Appointment communications are sent to a patient upon booking, cancelling and rescheduling appointments to keep the patient updated about their care. Appointment Confirmation When booking an appointment, at the bottom of the New Appointment form is the Booking Confirmation section. This will default to sending a booking confirmation message to the patient via their preferred channel. All you need to do is check you are happy to send this and keep the box checked before selecting Book. Below shows examples of the appointment confirmation message the patient will receive, depending on the type of appointment. Face to Face Appointment  Video Appointment Telephone Appointment Appointment Cancellation Appointments can be cancelled either by the practice or by the patient using the appointment cancellation link in their appointment reminder.  Below shows examples of the appointment cancellation message the patient will receive, depending on the type of appointment. Face to Face Appointment Video Appointment  Telephone Appointment  Appointment Reminder Appointment reminders are sent at 9am, the day before the appointment. Below shows examples of the appointment reminder message the patient will receive, depending on the type of appointment. Face to Face Appointment Video Appointment  Telephone Appointment"}, {"id": 17368110943005, "title": "Creating and Completing a Consultation", "section": "Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17368110943005", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This user guide will show you how to create and complete a consultation in Medicus. Creating a new consultation There are two ways to create a consultation in Medicus: \n From a patient's care record \n From an appointment \n Creating a new consultation from a patient's care record To start a consultation directly from the patient journal, select Consultation from the Actions dropdown menu in the right hand corner of the care record. This will open up a New Consultation form to populate some details about the consultation. The consultation is not created until you have completed the required details and have clicked the Start consultation button. Creating a new consultation for an appointment The most likely way that you'll create and complete a patient consultation is for a scheduled appointment. From your My Appointments tab, select the appointment that you'd like to start a consultation for. This will take you to an appointment lobby page. From here, you can review the appointment details and patient care record before starting the consultation. If you'd like to edit the consultation details before starting, select the pencil icon. This will open up a form to edit the consultation details. Once you're happy to begin the consultation, select the Start consultation button. If you try start a consultation before the appointment date, you'll see the following pop-up to check you want to start the consultation. Entering consultation notes The consultation form to complete is on the left hand side. The patient record is displayed on the right to refer to during the consultation. To use a consultation template, type /template into any consultation fields. You can then choose the consultation template you would like to use.   If you would like to manually record the consultation, simply type into the following headings to record your consultation notes: \n History \n Examination \n Observations \n Plan \n When entering your consultation notes you can either: \n Enter free text. \n Enter coded notes, by beginning with '.' this will search for clinical codes. \n Complete an action by typing '/' to open up the actions menu. (You can also see the actions menu by clicking on the 'More actions' dropdown link). \n For example, if your patient requires a prescription, you can select prescription from the quick actions menu and complete the new prescription form there and then. You can also link the consultation to an active problem. Follow-up actions Once you've completed your consultation, you may want to create follow up actions from a consultation. For example you may need to: \n Book a follow on appointment. \n Create an Appointment request task. \n Create a general task. \n To do this, select Create task or Book appointment under the follow up actions section. This will open up a pop-out form for you to complete the follow-up action. For example, if you the patient requires an additional appointment but you'd like a different staff member or team to pick up this action, you can create an Appointment request task. This will open up the New Appointment Request Task form. You'll be prompted to enter: \n Details of the appointment which needs to be booked, for example the appointment type and when it should be booked for. \n The staff member or team you want to assign the task to. (This as default will be populated with the default assignee). \n Whether the task is high or normal priority. \n You may also enter a due date or snooze the task until a certain date, but these fields are optional. \n Select Save. The task will be created once you complete the consultation. If you want to book the appointment yourself directly from the consultation, select Book appointment. This will bring out a pop-out form which follows the same booking process as you would when booking a patient appointment through the usual way in Medicus. Confidentiality If needed, you can hide either specific parts or an entire consultation from patient online access and/or Third parties. To do this, select More actions and then Edit confidentiality. This will open up a form for you to edit the confidentiality rules of a consultation. Select Save changes once you've edited the rules. If you mark the whole consultation as confidential from patient online access or third parties, a banner will display at the bottom of the consultation informing you of this. Draft consultations If you'd like to save a consultation in draft and complete it later, click the Save as draft button. Any incomplete consultations saved in draft will appear on your homepage so you can easily access them to complete the consultation. If you haven't completed the consultation within 12 hours, a Complete consultation task will be created in Medicus and assigned to the staff member who created the consultation. Completing the consultation Once you've finalised the consultation, select the Complete consultation button. This will then save the consultation against the patient's care record."}, {"id": 27830341467293, "title": "FP34D PPA Claims", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/27830341467293", "roles": ["Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose Practices can claim for certain high-volume personally administered vaccines and personally administered items using the FP34D form. In this article we'll explain how to use Medicus to run the reports you need to file your claims. You will find these reports in the Reporting & Data Returns module.  Personally administered prescriptions (PPA) With Medicus, you no longer need to retain FP10s as medications are administered. For any medications that attract an administration fee, we display the below pop up at the point of prescribing. This will apply to APM and VPM medications. By default the 'personally administered' box is unchecked.  The prescription is then issued via the Personally Administered workflow and will be included in your monthly totals.  At the beginning of the month, you can use the Personally Administered Prescriptions report to bulk print all the PF10s for medications that have been recorded as personally administered.  To review items that can be claimed as personally administered, but where the box wasn't checked, you can use the Potential Missed Claims report. This tab lists all issues that are eligible for FP34D/PD claims but were not issued as being personally administered. It is designed to help you spot check for missed claims. High volume vaccines To claim for high-volume personally administered vaccines, practices must fill out an FP34D appendix form. The vaccines that can be claimed for are: \n Influenza \n Typhoid \n Hepatitis A \n Hepatitis B \n Meningococcal \n Medicus supports practices with filling out this appendix through the High Volume Vaccines report. This report shows the Vaccines and the Total Number of Doses Administered for each vaccine.   Missed Claims  If the checkbox isn't marked for a prescription that has been personally administered you can use the Potential Missed Claims report to spot check these. This tab lists all issues that are eligible for FP34D/PD claims but were not issued as being personally administered.  If you need to change a prescription to personally administered you can return the prescription to not issued. When re-issuing the prescription, change the issue method by clicking the pencil icon next to the current issue method.  From here, select FP10 Personally Administered and then Save changes. When you then click to Issue the medication it will be counted as personally administered and included in your monthly totals."}, {"id": 32475117023901, "title": "Managing Patient Conversations", "section": "Patient Communications", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32475117023901", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose When sending a one-off patient communication, you can allow the patient to reply to the message. This user guide will show you how to manage patient's replies. Sending a communication to a patient Read more here about how to send a communication to a patient. Managing communication replies from a patient When a patient responds to a communication, their reply will be in the Patient Conversations task list. You can find this by going to Modules > Workflow > Inbound Items. If the reply is assigned to you, you will also see the task list on your homepage. From the Patient Conversations task list, you will see the list of patient replies, ordered by priority. You will be able to see the Latest Reply from the patient from this page. You can also filter the list on the right hand side. To manage a response, select it from the list. This will open the conversation thread where you can see the communication history and take any necessary action.   From the Codes and Actions field, you can: \n Type free text \n Add any clinical coding by typing a \".\" to code \n \n Complete any required actions by typing a \"/\" to open up the quick actions menu - for example, send another message to the patient, prescribe a medication or issue a fit note. \n Note: If a communication is sent to a patient from within a patient request, the patient will be able to respond in the thread until the task is set to Resolved. \n Under Status, you can update the status of the task - for example, if you have sent the patient a message then you can update it to Awaiting patient response and this will show in the main Patient Request task list, which allows you to filter to specific status'. \n You can also assign the communication thread to another team or user in the practice, under Assign To . If no further action needs to be taken on the communication thread, then you can set the status to Resolved and the task will be removed from the task list."}, {"id": 34217971561501, "title": "Managing and prescribing with multiple cost centre codes", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/34217971561501", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article will run through how to manage and prescribe with multiple cost centre codes for organisations which offer commissioned services to multiple ICBs. Adding multiple cost centres codes Multiple cost centre codes can be added to the organisational settings. To do this go to Modules > Prescribing and Medicines Management > Prescribing Configuration. To add a cost centre code, select Add cost centre code. You can then add the cost centre details. You are required to input the Display Name, ODS Code and Parent ODS Code. Click Save to add this cost centre. To add another spurious code, simply select Add cost centre code again. You'll then see the list of cost centre codes saved. Adding multiple spurious codes Multiple spurious codes can be added to the user settings. To do this go to Modules > Staff and User Management >  Select User. To add a spurious code, select Add spurious code. This will be available for users with the prescriber type Doctor. You can then enter the spurious code and give it a name so that you can identify it. To add another spurious code, simply select Add spurious code again. You will then see a list of all the spurious codes configured for the user. Selecting the Cost Centre for a Prescription at the Point of Issuing  For Medical Prescribers If the responsible practitioner has no spurious prescriber codes configured, their Doctor Index Number is used for the cost centre code. Otherwise, if they have one or more spurious prescriber codes configured, a dropdown will be displayed that allows them to choose the code that will be associated with the prescription. The options in the list will be Doctor Index Code and any spurious codes configured. For Non-Medical Prescribers For Non-Medical Prescribers, if the organisation does not have any additional cost centres configured, then the ODS code will be used for the cost centre.  If there are one or more additional cost centres configured, a dropdown will be displayed that allows them to choose the code that should be used for the cost centre.  The options in the list will be the organisation ODS code and any additional cost centres configured."}, {"id": 29669173706141, "title": "Transferring patients to another Medicus practice", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/29669173706141", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose   This article is a step by step guide to transferring patients from one Medicus practice to another. To transfer a patient from one Medicus practice to another, the old practice the patient is leaving needs to generate a code to give to the patient. The patient then gives this code to the new practice they've registered with and we will transfer the record once it's been entered.  Transferring a patient out to another Medicus practice Guidance for the original Medicus practice Note: The patient will need to have registered at the new practice before you're able to complete the below steps. First, you need to locate the patient transferring out. Navigate to your Patient list in the Patient administration module and select the patient transferring out.  Navigate to the Registration tab in the patient's administrative record and click Generate authorisation.  You will see the Patient Record Transfer Authorisation pop up. From here you can print the authorisation and hand it to the patient, they will need to share this code with their new practice. The code is valid for 90 days.    Transferring a patient in from another Medicus practice Guidance for the new Medicus practice Once you have registered the new patient, they can request a transfer code from their previous practice. Follow the steps below to request the patient's record using the code.  First, you need to locate the patient transferring in. Navigate to your Patient list in the Patient administration module and select the patient transferring in.  Navigate to the Registration tab in the patient's administrative record and click Request patient record . A pop up will appear for you to request to transfer the patient's record. Enter the code provided by the patient and click Send request .  Once that request has been sent we will begin the transfer of the patient's record, this should take a few minutes.  Generating a new transfer code  If the patient's new practice don't request the record transfer in the 90 day window before the code expires, you can generate a new code.  Open the patient's Administrative record and go to Registration . Open the unused transfer code and click Cancel . Once the unused code is cancelled you can generate a new code using the steps above."}, {"id": 32568628156445, "title": "Reassigning an appointment diary to another member of staff", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32568628156445", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose There may be circumstances where you need to make ad-hoc changes to the appointment diary due to staff absences but you don't want to make permanent changes to the appointment schedule. This article shows you how to do directly from the appointment book. Reassigning the appointment diary From the appointment book, select the 3 dots in the top right hand corner of the appointment diary that you would like to edit. Select Edit Diary from the drop down list. From the Edit Appointment Diary modal, scroll to the bottom and select which staff member should be allocated to the diary under Staff Requirements . Select Save Changes and the selected staff member will be allocated to the appointment diary."}, {"id": 32570066579869, "title": "Sending a bulk communication", "section": "Long Term Condition Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32570066579869", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose Bulk communication allows you to send the same message to a group of patients. This includes attaching SNOMED codes or documents to your message or collecting structured information from a group of patients by sending questionnaires. Sending a bulk communication Bulk communications can be sent from a patient report or a dashboard. This includes patient reports created by the practice, QOF dashboards and population health registers. To send a bulk communication, open the patient report that you would like to use; for example, your Asthma register. From here, you can either manually select the patients you would like to send a communication or select the tick box in the top line to select all patients. Then select Bulk Send Communication to write a message to the selected patients. You can now write your message to patients, with the option to Use a Template, Insert Questionnaire or Add Booking Link. You can also: \n Attach a document (The same document will be sent to all patients on the list so do not attach any patient identifiable information). \n Attach a SNOMED code \n Schedule the message for later  \n Under the Recipients section, you will see how many patients will receive the message and the delivery route that will be used. When you are happy with the message, you can select Send Now and the bulk communication will be sent to all patients on the list."}, {"id": 32570066603677, "title": "Sending a bulk communication", "section": "Patient Communications", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32570066603677", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose Bulk communication allows you to send the same message to a group of patients. This includes attaching SNOMED codes or documents to your message or collecting structured information from a group of patients by sending questionnaires. Sending a bulk communication Bulk communications can be sent from a patient report or a dashboard. This includes patient reports created by the practice, QOF dashboards and population health registers. To send a bulk communication, open the patient report that you would like to use; for example, your Asthma register. From here, you can either manually select the patients you would like to send a communication or select the tick box in the top line to select all patients. Then select Bulk Send Communication to write a message to the selected patients. You can now write your message to patients, with the option to Use a Template, Insert Questionnaire or Add Booking Link. You can also: \n Attach a document (The same document will be sent to all patients on the list so do not attach any patient identifiable information). \n Attach a SNOMED code \n Schedule the message for later  \n Under the Recipients section, you will see how many patients will receive the message and the delivery route that will be used. When you are happy with the message, you can select Send Now and the bulk communication will be sent to all patients on the list."}, {"id": 20559869582365, "title": "Viewing a Patient's Clinical Summary", "section": "Care Record", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20559869582365", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose A patient's clinical summary page is designed to provide a high level overview of the patient's care record so you can quickly get up to speed. For example, if you have an upcoming consultation with a new patient, you may find it useful to view a snapshot of the patient prior to the appointment. This user guide will show you how to view and interpret the clinical summary page. Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   By default you'll be taken to the patient's clinical summary page. Interpreting the clinical summary page The clinical summary page layout includes all of the recent information about a patient that you might need to access quickly.   Information on the clinical summary page: \n If the patient's birthday is within the last 7 days or next 7 days, Medicus will display a banner informing you of this. \n Any active risk alerts for the patient will be displayed on the patient banner. \n The last 3 consultations for the patient, plus the last consultation where you were the practitioner that the patient saw. \n Any registers the patient is on. \n Upcoming future actions / recalls. \n Upcoming appointments. \n Any outstanding tasks related to the patient. \n Any active allergies recorded for the patient. \n A summary of medications for this patient: \n Any current or discontinued repeat medications. \n Acute medications prescribed within the last 12 months. \n OTC medications or medications prescribed elsewhere. \n \n \n Active and major past problems. \n Documents for this patient from the last 3 months. \n Any test results from the last 3 months. \n Links to the shared care record for the patient. \n Links to a care plan if there is one available for the patient."}, {"id": 32122718313373, "title": "Sending a One-Off Communication from a Patient's Record", "section": "Patient Communications", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32122718313373", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose You can send a one-off communication directly from a patient's record if required. This user guide will show you how to do this. Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   Sending a communication To send a communication from the care record, select the 'Actions' menu in the top right hand corner, and then 'Communication'. This will open up the 'New Communication' form. Enter your message that you'd like the patient to receive in the 'Message' box. As well as entering free text, there are some other things you can add into the communication: \n Use template - Selecting use templates will allow you to choose a communication template that you regularly use so you don't need to type this out every time. \n \n Insert questionnaire - Any questionnaires stored in Medicus can be sent via this method. \n \n Add booking link -  If you are messaging a patient to book into an appointment then you can select 'Add booking link' where you'll be able to specify appointment service, type or a specific clinician that you'd like them to book into themselves. \n \n Add attachment - from computer or from patient record.  \n Patient messages by default will be sent as a sensitive message, meaning the message will only be viewable via a link and by entering their date of birth. By unchecking this box, the message will be sent without privacy controls and will be sent as a simple message.  Once you're happy with the message, you can check the correct channel of communication is selected under the 'Recipients' section. This will default to select whatever communication preferences are recorded for the patient in their administrative record. You can modify the channel of communication if you need to by selecting 'Modify recipient details'. Next, review the summary of the communication and add any SNOMED codes if required. Scheduling the message to send later  You can also schedule the message to send at a later time. You can then add  linked problem or edit the confidentiality setting before pressing 'Send'. Upcoming scheduled messages are visible on the patient's clinical summary page.  How a patient receives the message How patients will receive the message will depend on whether it was sent as a sensitive message. Sensitive message If the message is sent as a sensitive message the recipient will need to complete a verification step before reading the message. The patient will receive a message with a link to the patient portal to view the message:   They will be required to enter their DOB to confirm their identity. This is to ensure it matches the DOB that is stored on their patient record. Once verified, they'll be taken to the message on the patient portal. They will be able to action any appointment booking links or questionnaires from the message by clicking on the associated links. Non-sensitive message If a message is sent as a non-sensitive message, the body of the text will be visible in the text/email.  If a booking link, questionnaire or document were attached to the message, the patient will need to click on the link in the message to access it by completing verification steps."}, {"id": 31743071768733, "title": "Digital Firearms Marker", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/31743071768733", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose This article explains how to use Medicus to comply with the specific requirements of firearm/shotgun licensing in England. Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   Recording a new application or notification for a Firearms license To record a Firearms application or notification in Medicus, select 'Actions' in the top right hand corner and then select 'Firearm License'. A modal will open where you can create a record entry for: \n New applications for certificates \n Notification that the patient has a firearm/shotgun certificate \n Notification that the patient no longer has a firearm/shotgun certificate \n Notification that the patient's application for a firearm/shotgun certificate has been rejected  \n A review of the patient's record for suitability to hold a firearm license \n Police notification of your concern regarding the patient's suitability for a firearm license \n Viewing the status of the firearm certificate Once a record entry has been saved, it will appear in the patient's banner or as a note in the patient's journal. New application for certificate Notification that the patient has a firearm/shotgun certificate \n \n Notification that the patient no longer has a firearm/shotgun certificate - shown as a Note on the Patient's Journal \n \n \n Notification that the patient's application for a firearm/shotgun certificate has been rejected  \n \n \n A review of the patient's record for suitability to hold a firearm license - shown as a Note on the Patient's Journal \n \n \n Police notification of GP concern regarding the patient's suitability for a firearm license"}, {"id": 28201369300253, "title": "Recording Routine Observations", "section": "Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/28201369300253", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose When recording observations there's a standard list that will often be recorded in one encounter, Medicus provides a template where some or all of these observations can be recorded and coded. This user guide shows you how to use the Routine Observations action to record these from the patient's care record.    Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   Accessing the routine observations form To access the Routine Observations from the Patient's care record click Actions then Routine Observations .  To record Routine Observations from within a consultation type /Routine in the Observations box and click Routine Observations . Recording Routine Observations The Routine Observations are split into two sections, Breathing & Circulation and Measurements.  Under Breathing & Circulation you can record Oxygen saturation, Respiratory rate, Blood pressure, Heart rate and Temperature. If there is a previous reading available, this will be shown next to the text box with the date. Under the Measurements section you can record the patient's weight and if you select Calculate BMI you will also be prompted to enter the patient's height.  If an observation is inputted which is considered as too high, a warning will be displayed so that the input can be corrected.   You can record some or all of the observations. The only fields required are the date, organisation and name of the person recording the observations.  Once you save the observations they will be added to your consultation notes, or saved to the Journal as Recorded Observations.  Consultation notes Observations in the Journal"}, {"id": 20588877218973, "title": "Sending a One-Off Communication from a Patient's Record", "section": "Care Record", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20588877218973", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose You can send a one-off communication directly from a patient's record if required. This user guide will show you how to do this. Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   Sending a communication To send a communication from the care record, select the 'Actions' menu in the top right hand corner, and then 'Communication'. This will open up the 'New Communication' form. Enter your message that you'd like the patient to receive in the 'Message' box. As well as entering free text, there are some other things you can add into the communication: \n Use template - Selecting use templates will allow you to choose a communication template that you regularly use so you don't need to type this out every time. \n \n Insert questionnaire - Any questionnaires stored in Medicus can be sent via this method. \n \n Add booking link -  If you are messaging a patient to book into an appointment then you can select 'Add booking link' where you'll be able to specify appointment service, type or a specific clinician that you'd like them to book into themselves. \n \n Add attachment - from computer or from patient record.  \n Patient messages by default will be sent as a sensitive message, meaning the message will only be viewable via a link and by entering their date of birth. By unchecking this box, the message will be sent without privacy controls and will be sent as a simple message.  Once you're happy with the message, you can check the correct channel of communication is selected under the 'Recipients' section. This will default to select whatever communication preferences are recorded for the patient in their administrative record. You can modify the channel of communication if you need to by selecting 'Modify recipient details'. Next, review the summary of the communication and add any SNOMED codes if required. Scheduling the message to send later  You can also schedule the message to send at a later time. You can then add  linked problem or edit the confidentiality setting before pressing 'Send'. Upcoming scheduled messages are visible on the patient's clinical summary page.  How a patient receives the message How patients will receive the message will depend on whether it was sent as a sensitive message. Sensitive message If the message is sent as a sensitive message the recipient will need to complete a verification step before reading the message. The patient will receive a message with a link to the patient portal to view the message:   They will be required to enter their DOB to confirm their identity. This is to ensure it matches the DOB that is stored on their patient record. Once verified, they'll be taken to the message on the patient portal. They will be able to action any appointment booking links or questionnaires from the message by clicking on the associated links. Non-sensitive message If a message is sent as a non-sensitive message, the body of the text will be visible in the text/email.  If a booking link, questionnaire or document were attached to the message, the patient will need to click on the link in the message to access it by completing verification steps."}, {"id": 20559840516253, "title": "Viewing the Patient Journal", "section": "Care Record", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20559840516253", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n The journal is a chronological view of a patient's medical history. It can be used to view more detailed information about a patient's recent interactions, and to search and filter for specific entries. This user guide will show you how to view and interpret the patient journal in Medicus. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n   \n The journal can be found on the second tab of the care record. \n   \n Viewing, searching and filtering the journal \n The following care record elements will appear in the journal in chronological order (most recent first): \n \n Allergy \n Document \n Note \n Consultation \n Communication \n Online consultation \n Fit note \n Medications administered \n OTC medication \n Medication prescribed elsewhere \n Observation \n Prescription \n Procedure \n Future action / recall \n Referral \n Vaccination \n \n \n   \n   \n On the right hand side of the journal you can filter by: \n \n Entry type \n Year \n Link to problem \n Organisation \n Practitioner \n Document type \n Clinical specialty \n Record status (e.g. draft or finalised) \n Filing status (e.g. un-filed or filed) \n \n You can filter by multiple filters at the same time. For example, if you wanted to view previous consultations by 1 practitioner you can filter on both the care record element and the practitioner to see the relevant journal entries. \n The number of entries can be seen in brackets next to each filter element, as well as the total entries at the top of the journal filters panel. \n You can also filter the journal using the free text search. The journal will filter as you type. \n Note: \n Please note that there is a known issue where Docman is unable to export annotations from documents. Please check Docman for any annotations when viewing documents that have been imported into Medicus. This gap in the data export from Docman is expected to be resolved by OneAdvanced later in 2025."}, {"id": 20345812943773, "title": "Viewing a Patient's Medication Regimen", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20345812943773", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose The purpose of a patient's Medication Regimen page is to provide you with a snapshot review of the medication a patient should be taking or has previously been prescribed. This user guide will show you how to navigate to and review a patient's Medication Regimen in Medicus. Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.       Viewing the Medication Regimen Select the 'Medication Regimen' tab. Here you can see a clear view of: \n Acute Medications issued within the last 12 months. \n Un-issued acute prescriptions. \n Current repeat medications. \n Discontinued repeat medications. \n Medication prescribed elsewhere. \n Over-the-counter medications. \n Last Medication Review Date \n \n EPS Pharmacy Nominations"}, {"id": 18746224434845, "title": "Viewing a Patient's Summary Care Record", "section": "Care Record", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18746224434845", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The Summary Care Record (SCR) viewer provides access to key information across a number of different healthcare settings. For more information on the SCR, review this guidance on the NHSE website. This user guide will show you how to access a patient's SCR in Medicus. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Viewing the Summary Care Record \n Note:  you'll need to make sure that the SCR viewer is toggled on from the Medicus configuration module. This is automatically set to 'on' during implementation. You'll also need to ensure you are logged into Medicus with your Smartcard. \n Once in the care record, you can view a patient's SCR from the clinical summary page under 'Shared Care'. \n \n This will open up the SCR for your review."}, {"id": 18437502769309, "title": "Viewing and Creating an Allergy on the Patient Record", "section": "Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18437502769309", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n You'll need to record an allergy against a patient record if you believe the patient could suffer a reaction if they come into contact with a substance or drug. Allergies are then displayed whilst prescribing medication to a patient so clinical staff can be warned and informed whilst making clinical decisions. \n This user guide will show you how to create, view and remove allergies in Medicus. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Creating a new allergy \n There are two routes to creating a new allergy in Medicus: \n \n From a new consultation via the quick action functionality \n From the Care Record \n \n To create an allergy from the Care Record, select 'Allergy' from the Actions menu. \n \n This will open up the 'New Allergy' form. \n \n Note:  you may want to create a Yellow Card if this is a new allergy and your patient has had a reaction to a certain prescribed medication. \n Once you've populated the details of the allergy, select 'Save' to save the allergy against the patient record. \n Viewing and editing an allergy \n Allergies will be displayed on the Clinical Summary Page and found in the Patient Journal within the Care Record. \n \n Clicking on the allergy will open up the 'View Allergy' screen. \n \n Selecting any of the pencil icons will allow you to edit details about the allergy. \n \n   \n Allergy warnings when creating a prescription \n When creating a new prescription, current allergies are displayed so you're aware of this information to aid clinical decision making."}, {"id": 18424643155869, "title": "Retrospectively Updating a Consultation", "section": "Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18424643155869", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n If there's an error on a finalised consultation, you can retrospectively edit this in Medicus. This user guide will take you through the steps to retrospectively update a consultation. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Editing a consultation \n From the care record, select the consultation that you'd like to edit. \n \n This opens up the 'View Consultation' pop-out. \n Select 'Edit consultation' to proceed. \n \n You'll then be taken to the 'Edit consultation' screen. \n Editing consultation details \n To edit consultation details, such as: \n \n Date / time \n Mode \n Practitioner \n Additional participants \n Organisation & location \n \n Select the pencil icon in the top right hand corner of the 'Consultations Details' box. \n \n You'll be taken to the 'Edit Consultation Details' form where you can update any of these fields and save changes. \n \n Once you've updated the consultation details that you'd like to edit, scroll to the bottom of the 'Edit Consultation' form and select 'Finish editing'. \n Updating clinical codes and notes \n To change additional details of a consultation, such as clinical coding and notes, select the note or code you would like to edit to open up the 'View Note' screen. \n Select the pencil icon to edit the details. \n \n You'll be taken to the 'Edit Note' form where you can update the code and note. Select 'Save changes' to update the note. \n \n Once you're happy with the updates, select 'Finish editing' to save your changes. \n \n Note:  you won't be able to edit actions that were saved during the original consultation, such as, prescriptions and referrals."}, {"id": 17469724631581, "title": "Prescribing Again and Re-authorising Prescriptions", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17469724631581", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n There may be instances where you need to prescribe an acute prescription again, or re-authorise a repeat prescription for a patient. This user guide will take you through to steps of how to action this in Medicus. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Prescribing an acute prescription again \n To prescribe an acute prescription again, click on the acute prescription from the patient's care record. \n \n This will open up a summary about the prescription. Select the arrow to open up a more detailed 'View Prescription' view. \n Scroll down and select 'Prescribe again' from the 'More actions' menu. \n \n This will open up the 'Prescribe Again' form. \n \n The details from the original prescription will be pre-populated so all you'll need to do is double check the details are correct before proceeding. \n Note: Y ou'll only be able to choose a medication from the dropdown list that has the same VMP code as the medication that was previously prescribed. You won't be able to change the dosage when prescribing again. If you want to change the medication dosage then you'll need to follow the change drug/dosage function in Medicus. \n Re-authorising a repeat prescription \n To re-authorise a repeat prescription, click on the repeat medication from the patient's care record. \n \n This will open up the 'View Prescription' screen. \n Scroll to the bottom and select 'Re-authorise prescription' from the 'More actions' menu. \n \n This will open up the 'Re-authorise Prescription' form. \n \n A banner will be displayed on the form to inform you that a new prescription will be created and the current prescription will be marked as re-authorised. \n The details from the original prescription will be pre-populated so all you'll need to do is double check the details are correct before proceeding. \n Note: Y ou'll only be able to choose a medication from the dropdown list that has the same VMP code as the medication that was previously prescribed. You won't be able to change the dosage when re-authorising a repeat prescription. If you want to change the medication dosage then you'll need to follow the change drug/dosage function in Medicus. \n Re-authorising a repeat dispensing prescription \n Re-authorising a repeat dispensing prescription can be a little more complicated if the start date of the new prescription is before the end of the old prescription. This is because Medicus needs to submit a cancellation request to any prescription issues for the previous prescription that were issued via EPS. \n Sometimes, EPS is not able to cancel the issue. For example, if the prescription is already with the dispenser then you will need to contact the dispenser directly. If the prescription is already with the patient, then you may have to contact the patient. Medicus will inform you of this if this is the case. \n Once the prescription issues status have been updated, the prescription can be re-authorised. \n Complete EPS Cancellation Task \n When requesting a cancellation of an EPS prescription, if the dispenser has already drawn the prescription from the Spine and therefore you need to contact the pharmacy, then Medicus will create a 'Complete EPS Cancellation' task to ensure the action isn't forgotten. The task is under the 'Prescribing' section of the Workflow module and can be found under the task list of whoever actioned the original request. Once you've followed the cancellation instructions on the task, select 'Mark as pharmacy contacted' to complete the task."}, {"id": 17247382946333, "title": "Ending a Prescription", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17247382946333", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n If a patient should no longer have any issues of a prescription then you can end the prescription in Medicus to end the course. This action will most likely be for repeat prescriptions. This user guide will show you how to end a prescription in Medicus. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Ending a prescription \n To end a prescription in Medicus, select the prescription you would like to end from the patient record. \n \n This will open up the View Prescription screen. \n Scroll to the bottom and select 'End prescription' from the 'More actions' menu. \n \n This will open up the 'End Prescription' form. \n You're required to enter a reason from a dropdown list. This is to make sure you're recording if the patient has had a negative reaction to the medication. \n \n If the patient has had a negative reaction to the medication, you'll need to choose 'Clinical contraindication' as the reason. \n This will create an option to also submit a Yellow Card task to make sure any new reactions to medications are submitted to MHRA. \n \n If you select another reason from the list then you won't have the option to submit a yellow card. \n You can enter any additional information you think may be useful before selecting 'End Prescription'. \n \n If the prescription was not issued via EPS then the prescription will simply end and future issues will be shown with a status as 'not issued'. \n Handling cancellation request responses from EPS \n If you're ending a prescription that has been issued via EPS, Medicus needs to retrieve these issues back from EPS. \n Note:  you'll need to be logged in with your NHS Smartcard to end prescriptions that were issued via EPS. \n Once you've entered the discontinuation reason, Medicus will submit a cancellation request to EPS for each prescription issue. \n If the prescription is successfully ended, the discontinuation reason is shown on the 'View Prescription' screen and the issues are displayed as 'not issued'. \n Sometimes, EPS is not able to cancel the issue. For example, if the prescription is already with the dispenser then you will need to contact them directly. If the prescription is already with the patient, then you may have to contact the patient. Medicus will inform you of this if this is the case. \n Complete EPS Cancellation Task \n When requesting a cancellation of an EPS prescription, if the dispenser has already drawn the prescription from the Spine and therefore you need to contact the pharmacy, then Medicus will create a 'Complete EPS Cancellation' task to ensure the action isn't forgotten. The task is under the 'Prescribing' section of the Workflow module and can be found under the task list of whoever actioned the original request. Once you've followed the cancellation instructions on the task, select 'Mark as pharmacy contacted' to complete the task."}, {"id": 17212371172893, "title": "Marking a Prescription as Incorrect", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17212371172893", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n If a prescription is finalised in Medicus but hasn't yet been issued, you can mark is as incorrect in the system if there's been a mistake. Completing this action will amend any future issues to 'not issued' for that prescription. This user guide will show you how to mark a prescription as incorrect. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Marking a Prescription as Incorrect \n To mark a prescription as incorrect, select the prescription from the care record. \n \n This will open up the 'View prescription' form. \n Select the pencil icon in the top right hand corner of the details section. \n \n Note:  remember that you will only be able to mark a prescription as incorrect if it hasn't been issued yet. Double check that the issues are labelled as 'Not issued' before proceeding. \n This will open up the 'Edit Prescription Details' section. \n Select 'Mark as incorrect'. \n \n This will open up the 'Mark as Incorrect' form. \n You can either choose to mark as incorrect only or to remove the prescription from the entire patient record. You might want to do the latter in the extreme scenario that a prescription was created on the wrong patient record. \n You'll be prompted to enter the reason why you are marking the prescription as incorrect. \n \n Once you've proceeded to mark the prescription as incorrect, the prescription will show as greyed out on the record and authorised issues will be cancelled."}, {"id": 17210221579549, "title": "Changing the Drug or Dosage of a Prescription", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17210221579549", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n For scenarios where a patient's medication regime changes over time, for example their drug or dosage needs to be adjusted, you can use the 'change drug/dosage' feature outlined in this guide. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Changing the drug or dosage of a prescription  \n To change the drug or dosage of a prescription, click on the prescription you would like to change from the patient record. \n \n This will open up the 'View Prescription' screen. From here, select 'Change drug/dosage'. \n \n This will open up the 'Change Drug/Dosage' form. \n You're informed at the top of the form that a new prescription will be created and the current prescription will appear in Medicus as discontinued. \n \n Once you've amended the fields you'd like to amend, you can either issue now or issue later. \n Note:  if any of the issues were issued via EPS then Medicus needs to try get these back from EPS. \n Changing the drug or dosage of a repeat dispensing prescription \n Changing the drug or dosage of a repeat dispensing prescription is slightly more complicated as there are multiple issues that the status needs to be identified for and cancelled. \n If the repeat dispensing prescription was not issued via EPS then the workflow is simple and will follow as if it were any other prescription. \n However, if the prescription was issued via EPS then Medicus will need to try get any issues back from EPS that haven't been dispensed yet. \n Note:  you'll need to be logged in with your Smartcard if the prescription was issued via EPS. \n Medicus will request to cancel via EPS any issues which haven't been dispensed yet. \n If any issues are with the dispenser or have already been dispensed to the patient, you'll be notified of this in Medicus and may have to contact either the pharmacy or the patient. \n Complete EPS Cancellation Task \n When requesting a cancellation of an EPS prescription, if the dispenser has already drawn the prescription from the Spine and therefore you need to contact the pharmacy, then Medicus will create a 'Complete EPS Cancellation' task to ensure the action isn't forgotten. The task is under the 'Prescribing' section of the Workflow module and can be found under the task list of whoever actioned the original request. Once you've followed the cancellation instructions on the task, select 'Mark as pharmacy contacted' to complete the task."}, {"id": 17196048024477, "title": "How to Edit a Prescription", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17196048024477", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The following features on a prescription can be edited: \n \n Prescriber endorsements - E.g they may change inline with the NHS drug tariff. \n Dispenser instructions - E.g. a patient may have been bed bound but is no longer. \n Review date - E.g the review date changes after a review has happened. \n \n This guide will show you how to view and the above properties of a prescription in Medicus. \n Points to note: \n \n You cannot edit any clinical properties on the prescription by using the guidance in this article. For this, follow the guidance on 'Changing Drug or Dosage of a Prescription'. \n You cannot edit a repeat dispensing prescription after it has been issued as Medicus cannot communicate the updates to the dispenser. \n \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Editing a prescription \n A prescription can be edited from a patient's Clinical Summary page or Medication Regimen page. Select the medication you'd like to edit to open the 'View Prescription' screen on the right hand side of the page. \n To edit the prescription, click on the pencil icon. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Prescription Details' form. \n \n Once you have edited the details you want to change, select 'Save changes'. The changes should now be visible within the prescription."}, {"id": 17195237651613, "title": "How to Record Medication Prescribed Elsewhere", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17195237651613", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n If a patient is prescribed medication at another organisation, it's useful to record this in the patient record. This user guide will show you how to view and record medications prescribed elsewhere in Medicus. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Recording medication prescribed elsewhere \n There are two ways to record medication prescribed elsewhere in Medicus: \n \n From the care record \n From a consultation \n \n Recording medication prescribed elsewhere from the care record \n To record medication prescribed elsewhere from a patient's care record, select the 'Actions' dropdown menu in the top right hand corner of the patient care record. Select 'Medication prescribed elsewhere' from the list. \n \n Recording medication prescribed elsewhere from a consultation \n To record medication prescribed elsewhere from a consultation, select the 'More actions' dropdown link, and then select 'Medication prescribed elsewhere'. \n \n Completing the medication prescribed elsewhere form \n By following one of the two methods above, you'll be presented with the 'Record Medication Prescribed Elsewhere' form. \n \n The 'Record date' and 'Record author' details are pre-populated, but you can change this if required. \n Press 'Save' once you've completed the form to record this information in Medicus. \n This will be visible on the: \n \n Clinical summary page \n Medication regimen page \n Patient journal"}, {"id": 17192954812957, "title": "How to Record Over-the-Counter Medication", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17192954812957", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Over-the-counter (OTC) medications are useful to record against a patient care record. This guide outlines how to view and record OTC medications in Medicus. \n Navigating to the care record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, you'll be taken to the clinical care record.   \n Recording an OTC medication \n There are two ways to record an OTC medication in Medicus: \n \n From the care record \n From a consultation \n \n Recording an OTC medication from the care record \n To record an OTC medication from a patient's care record, select the 'Actions' dropdown menu in the top right hand corner of the patient care record. Select 'OTC medication' from the list. \n \n Recording an OTC medication from a consultation \n To record an OTC medication from a consultation, select the 'More actions' dropdown link, and then select 'Over-the-counter medication'. \n \n Completing the OTC medication form \n By following one of the two methods above, you'll be presented with the 'Record OTC Medication' form. \n \n The 'Record date' and 'Record author' details are pre-populated, but you can change this if required. \n Press 'Save' once you've completed the form to record this information in Medicus. \n This will be visible on the: \n \n Clinical summary page \n Medication regimen page \n Patient journal"}, {"id": 20605419150365, "title": "The Panic Button", "section": "Medicus Overview, Navigation & Tasks", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20605419150365", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose The panic button can be used in either medical emergencies or physical safety threats. In Medicus there is both a physical and virtual panic button. This user guide will show you how to utilise the panic button feature in Medicus. Panic button configuration The panic button will be configured during the implementation of Medicus. The button is powered from a desktop app that is installed on all devices and starts automatically upon sign on. You shouldn't have to do anything, and the button is designed so that you'll be alerted if there is a configuration or connection issue. Physical panic buttons states The physical panic button uses following states: \n Not plugged in = No light \n Ready = Solid red light \n No signal = Single red flash every 5 seconds (e.g. desktop app is unavailable) \n No connection = Two red flashes every 5 seconds (e.g. internet down) \n Help required = Flashing red light \n Help coming = Pulsing red light \n Setting the location during login It's vital you select your location and site during login to Medicus which will enable the panic button to work. If you do not do this then the panic button will not be available. Note: the location and site will be pre-populated with your previous location from the last time you logged in. Triggering a panic alert You can trigger a panic alert during an emergency by either pressing your physical panic button, or the virtual panic button. This will trigger a panic alert at other users who are at the same site. You can also trigger a panic alert through the keyboard shortcut - ctrl + shift + P. Once you trigger a panic alert, you'll see that both the physical and the virtual panic buttons are flashing.  When someone responds to your panic alert, then you'll notice the light will start to pulse at a lower pace to inform you that help is coming. Responding to a panic alert If a user at the same site triggers their panic button, then you will see a panic alert on your screen. You can choose to respond, or not respond to the panic alert. Note:  if multiple people press their panic button within the same time period, multiple panic alerts will show on your screen, with the oldest alert first. If you are responding to a panic alert, other staff members will be informed on the pop out alert. Cancelling a panic alert Once the incident is over (or if you accidentally triggered the panic button) you can cancel the alert. To do this, select the user settings. From the user settings, select 'Active Panic Alerts'. From the list, select 'Cancel alert'. You'll be taken to a pop up confirming that you want to cancel the alert. If you are happy to proceed, select 'cancel'. Panic button audit logs If you ever need to access audit lots of panic button events, alerts and responses, these can be found in the Audit module of Medicus."}, {"id": 27693272099229, "title": "Implementation Guide for IT / CSU Support", "section": "Implementation Guides for IT Teams", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/27693272099229", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose As Medicus is a web-based application, the IT support resource requirements are much lower than a fully installed clinical system. However, the implementation of Medicus does require a named IT / CSU support contact who can lead  a small number of configuration and IT related tasks. This could in total require no more than 2-3 days of resource in total. On-Site vs. Remote Support Most of the tasks outlined in this document can be actioned remotely, other than hardware configuration tasks, where we require IT engineer on-site support. For a Medicus implementation this would be: \n 1 days on-site the week before go-live to configure and test hardware e.g. scanners. \n 1-2 days floor-walking during go-live week for any final configuration and on the day troubleshooting. \n Note: if the practice is multi-site then we require 1 IT engineer per site for floorwalking. Server Requirements Because Medicus is a web-based application it does not have any on-site server requirements. All connections to the Medicus servers are made using HTTPS on port 443. Medicus Desktop App Installation The Medicus system is a web-based application, however, there is a small installation requirement which is the Medicus Desktop App. The Medicus Desktop App is required to enable the physical panic button functionality and to enable the integration with GP Order Comms systems such as tQuest and ICE. The app needs to be installed on all machines at the practice. This can usually be done remotely and then pushed to all practice devices. Here is detailed guidance and installation instructions for downloading the Medicus Desktop App: How to Install the Windows Desktop App as a Local IT Administrator Once live, if there is an update required, we will inform the CSU of this in good time. To update the Medicus Desktop App you should uninstall the old version using the uninstall instructions (included int he guide linked above) and then install the new version. We have designed the app to minimise the need for future updates to minimise the maintenance burden that arises from deploying updates. Desktop Shortcut To allow users ease of access to Medicus, we request that a desktop shortcut to england.medicus.health is added to the desktop of all practice devices. Please include the Medicus logo on the shortcut for clarity. Scanner Configuration Medicus is an end-to-end solution for document management which includes receiving documents via MESH, NHS Mail and scanned post. For paper documents received in the post that need to be coded, actioned and filed, Medicus requires the scanner to be configured to scan directly into the Medicus Web Application. Here is a detailed article on configuring your practice scanner to Medicus: Configuring your Practice Scanners . Minimum Technical Requirements In order for your scanners to be able to send documents directly to the Medicus Document workflow, the scanners must: \n Be able to connect to a network - through either Ethernet or Wi-Fi \n Support SFTP or WebDAV (HTTPS) as a scan destination \n Scanners that do not meet these requirements (for example, USB-only models or those that only support scan-to-PC or scan-to-email) are not compatible with this workflow. It is possible to manually upload documents to Medicus from a computer, which is suitable for ad-hoc use but not ideal for an end-to-end document workflow. Recommended Scanner Models This Epson model offers the best balance of reliability, ease of setup, and protocol support. \n \n Model \n Connectivity \n Price (ex. VAT) \n Recommendation \n \n \n Epson DS-790WN \n Ethernet and Wi-Fi \n £525 \n Most reliable option. Ideal for practices that want fast scanning and wired stability. \n \n The Epson ES-580W could be a lower-cost alternative, however, it will only work if your practice has strong Wi-Fi. If your practice does not have strong Wi-Fi, ensure it has the ability to connect to the network through an Ethernet Connection. The Epson ES-580W can mostly be configured from the device screen, while the DS-790WN has similar setup options. Some network and credential details will need to be entered during configuration using the scanner's touchscreen interface. Step-by-step guides on how to configure some specific scanner models are available here: \n How to Configure an Epson ES-580W Scanner \n How to Configure a Brother ADS-4700W Scanner \n If you're configuring another make / model of scanner, then please consult the manufacturing guide for detailed configuration guidance. Can I Use a Different Scanner? Yes but only if the scanner: \n Is network-enabled \n Supports SFTP or WebDAV \n Allows manual configuration of hostname, port, path, and credentials \n If you're considering another brand please ensure to check the manufacturer documentation. Important Notes \n Most non-Epson models support SFTP only (not WebDAV). \n Setup can be more involved - often requiring use of a vendor-specific web interface or software tool. \n Make sure that you perform an end-to-end test with a multi-page document (with no patient identifiable information) to ensure that the document is successfully scanned, uploaded, and can be accessed within Medicus. \n We do not support scan-to-email or scan-to-shared-drive (SMB) as part of the direct Medicus document workflow. Networking Scanners \n Scanners using SFTP connect to sftp.england.medicus.health on port 22. The IP addresses associated with this domain name will change over time but are currently 3.9.52.129 , 13.40.58.131 and 52.56.135.100 . The IP addresses will always be within the AWS eu-west-2 IP address range. \n Scanners using WebDAV connect over HTTPS to {tenant-id}.api.england.medicus.health on port 443. The IP addresses associated with this domain name will change over time but are currently 3.9.148.234 and 18.130.198.14 . The IP addresses will always be within the AWS eu-west-2 IP address range. \n Printer Configuration Printers are routinely used in practices for a variety of use cases: \n Printed FP10s or other prescriptions \n Printing of lab request forms and specimen labels \n Printing a manual referral form for a patient e.g. private referral \n Each of the above use cases may require printing to a specific template form, and often practices have set up their printers whereby e.g. FP10s in drawer 1 and Lab forms in drawer 2. As a web based solution, there is no configuration in Medicus to target a specific drawer for a specific use case. We recommend IT support to run a small number of tests on printing lab forms, labels and FP10 scripts to ensure the paper is aligned correctly, and the printers continue working as expected. Small configuration tweaks for realignment may be required, but this is on the desktop itself rather than within the Medicus system. Medicus Call-in Board The Medicus Call-In Board is an optional component that displays messages for patients in the waiting area at the practice to call them in for consultations. It can also display a YouTube video playlist. Requirements The call-in board software is a web app like the main Medicus web app and has the same basic operating system, browser and networking requirements. \n For ease of management we recommend using a PC to run the call-in board, attached to one or more large display screens. You can use any model of PC, including small and micro form-factor machines such as from the Dell Optiplex Micro PC or the Lenovo ThinkCentre ranges. \n The PC hardware should meet the Windows 11 minimum specifications ( https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/windows-11-specifications ). It should also have audio and video outputs compatible with the display screens to be used (see below). \n We recommend at least 8Gb of RAM to guarantee good performance. \n As with the Medicus web app, the PC will need to be connected to your local network and have access to the internet. From a network firewall perspective, the PC must have access to the same Medicus servers / domain names as machines running the Medicus web app. In addition, the youtube.com and www.youtube.com domain names must be accessible if the YouTube video playlist functionality is to be used. \n While you can use a wireless network connection, we recommend a wired connection for best possible reliability. \n Display Screens \n Any sufficiently large monitor or television meeting the following requirements can be used: \n Minimum resolution 1920×1080 (Full HD) \n Built-in speakers \n External video input connection matching the call-in board PC Typically HDMI or DisplayPort (DP) \n \n External audio input connection This can be combined with video input if using HDMI \n \n For ease of connection we recommend using an HDMI connection so that the audio and video connection can be combined into a single HDMI cable. \n If you wish to have multiple display screens in the same waiting area then we recommend using an HDMI splitter to ensure that all the screens stay synchronised, rather than using multiple call-in board PCs. \n Medicus Check-in Kiosk The Medicus Check-in Kiosk is an optional component that allows patients to check-in for their appointment on a touch screen device, instead of having to go to reception. Requirements The kiosk user interface is designed to run in any supported web browser on a tablet or other device such as a desktop that has a touchscreen. The device must have reliable internet connectivity and should be receiving automatic security updates. Display Screens iPads Any iPad model that meets the following specifications is supported: Runs a version of iPadOS that receives security support For supported versions of iPadOS see https://endoflife.date/ipados and https://support.apple.com/en-gb/guide/ipad/ipad213a25b2/ipados   Android Tablets Any Android tablet that meets the following specifications is supported: \n Runs a version of Android OS that receives security support \n 4Gb RAM or greater \n For supported versions of Android OS see https://endoflife.date/android   Other Devices Any other device that meets the following specifications is supported: \n Runs a supported web browser \n Runs an operating system that receives security support \n 4Gb RAM or greater \n Physical Panic Buttons Medicus has a virtual panic button built into the system. Medicus also offers the addition of a physical panic button for practices to use. The physical panic button is an Arduino Leonardo-compatible microcontroller that connects over USB as a virtual (CDC) serial / COM port. It is also powered over USB. It runs microcode written by Medicus. As part of the setup, please ensure the practice has available USB ports in each clinical room and by the reception to accomodate the physical panic button devices. If there are not enough USB ports then you may need to procure USB adapters. Removing EPS Pop-ups By default, the NHS Credential Management software has two “annoying pop ups” when signing prescriptions: There is a way to remove these by adding the following settings to the Windows Registry: Path: Computer\\HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\NHS Digital\\CredentialManagement Add these 3 registry keys to disable the pop-ups: \n ShowSigningLoadingSplash (Type = REG_SZ, Data = False) \n SigningConfirmationMsg (Type = REG_SZ, Data = False) \n SigningSuccessMsg (Type = REG_SZ, Data = False) \n Notes from previous implementations: \n On occasion, the Credential Management files were not located under Policies. The IT Support moved the files to the Policy folder to exactly match the above set up. This then allowed the changes to apply correctly. \n Note that on some CSU setups the registry keys for NHS Credential Management software may be instead located under Computer\\HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\Software\\WOW6432Node\\NHS Digital\\CredentialManagement. \n This was located by searching for “CredentialManagement” on the registry of one of the GP practice computers to see where the NHS Credential Management software put its registry keys. \n CIS2 Smartcards Please ensure that all practice devices have the latest version of credential manager installed so users are able to pair their NHS Smartcard to Medicus. The following RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) Activity Codes are required to perform specific NHS API functions within Medicus: Most existing Smartcard users will already have the required RBAC Activity Codes linked to their Smartcard. In these cases, no changes to RBAC permissions are typically required.  Access to individual Medicus modules is managed separately from NHS RBAC permissions. Module-level access is controlled within Medicus in the Staff & User Management module."}, {"id": 21661012525725, "title": "Creating Ad Hoc Reports Using the Report Builder", "section": "Reporting", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21661012525725", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose The patient report builder is intended to support ad hoc reports where there isn't currently an out of the box report or dashboard in the system. This user guide will show you how to how to use to patient report builder. Navigating to the reporting module To navigate to the patient report builder, select 'Modules' from the left hand side navigation bar to open up the modules menu, then select 'Reporting & Data Returns'. Once in the Reporting module, select 'Patient Report Builder'. Creating a New Report Select 'Create report'. This will open up the 'Generate New Report' form.  First, select your report focus. Medicus supports 3 focuses: \n Patients \n Activity \n Specific NHS numbers/ GY Numbers - e.g. if you wanted to copy a list of NHS/ GY numbers from an excel document to run a report against. \n Next, choose your patient population. Here you can set: \n Age \n Clinical sex \n Current registration type \n Named GP \n   Then select 'Add' under the 'Report Criteria' section to specify your report criteria. Here you can choose from: \n Issued medication \n Not issued medication \n Record contains code \n Record contains code with value - this enables searching for target specific values for observations e.g. BMI>=30 or QRisk>=10 \n Record does not contain code \n When searching using codes, you can choose to search for a specific code or for a code in a refset. You can choose many report criteria. Each criteria is AND, for example \"Prescribed Amoxicillin\" + \"Does not have code Medication Review\" this means all patients who have been prescribed Amoxicillin AND does not have the code Medication Review. You can also select a date range and choose whether to only search for codes / medications that have been added or issued at the practice. For date range you can select: \n No date limit  \n Relative range e.g. last 4 weeks, last 5 years  \n Fixed range  \n   Once you've set the criteria, you can choose which columns you want the report to include. Here you can include contact information, named GP, registration type etc.  When you have set up all the criteria and columns needed click 'Run report'. You can save these reports in Medicus to re-run at any time and copy reports if you need to retain the same base population while adding new search terms. You can also export patient reports to csv files using the Export drop down.  Bulk Actions Once you've completed your ad hoc report you can complete any bulk actions on the list of patients in the report. \n Bulk add a SNOMED CT code to the patient record \n Add a future action / recall \n Add immunisation \n Send a bulk communication"}, {"id": 31098124389789, "title": "How to Create and Manage Communication Templates", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/31098124389789", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose Communication templates are a great way to save time and ensure that your messages are as concise and consistent as possible. You can use communication templates when sending an individual message or a bulk communication.  Creating and managing letter templates is available to users with the roles Clinical Management, Operational Management and IT Support.  Creating a communication template \n Firstly go to Modules > Communication > Templates. \n \n Select Create template or New template \n \n 3.  Give your communication template a name and then select Create Template.       If you want specific templates to appear at the top, simply put a 0 at the beginning of the template name      eg. 0 - Smear test invitation 4. Once you have created the template, you can create a version. To do this, select Create Version and then give the template a version number (eg. V1). 4. Once you've created the version, you can add content to the template by selecting Add Content. 5. When adding content to the template, you can firstly add a code. This code will be added to the patient's record whenever the template is sent to the patient. You can then enter text into the template. You can also insert system merge fields by typing \"{{\" and selecting the merge field from the drop-down (You can choose from 'Patient Name' and 'Sender Name'). To add a booking link, click Add booking link and fill out the details of the appointment type you want patients to book in to.  6. Once you're done, select Save Changes, then click Back to template. To make the template ready to use, select Set to Active  The template will then be ready to use for all users at the practice.   Editing a Communication Template \n Go to the templates list and select the template you'd like to edit (Modules > Communication > Templates). \n \n To make a edits to the template, select New Version and give the template a new version number. \n 3. Select Back to template and then select the new version.  4. Click on the current content to make edits, then Save Changes. 5. To make the new version active, select Set to current version. Archiving a Communication Template To archive a communication template, select the template from the template list and then select Archive template. Confirm that you wan to archive the template and then it will be removed from the template list."}, {"id": 33575891925021, "title": "How to view MESH mailbox documents in Medicus", "section": "Data Sharing Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/33575891925021", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Administrator"], "body": "This article explains where to find your MESH (Message Exchange for Social Care and Health) mailbox credentials and where to find the documents for action in Medicus.  Viewing your MESH mailbox credentials in Medicus You can view your MESH mailbox credentials in Medicus in the Data Sharing module.  \n Go to Modules in the left-hand menu \n Select Third Party Data Sharing \n Scroll down to the MESH section \n Select the Mailbox Credentials tab \n Review your MESH mailbox credentials \n Under the credentials section in Messages, you can also see a list of i nbound and outbound MESH messages. This is a technical view of MESH traffic and is not where you manage or action documents. Where to find MESH documents in Medicus To view documents that have been received via MESH: \n Go to Modules \n Select Workflow \n In Workflow, select Inbound items > Documents \n Review the list of inbound document tasks \n All documents received via MESH are processed and shown here, along with documents that have been scanned or received by email, as inbound document tasks.  This article explains in more detail how we process inbound documents and match them to patients.  This article guides staff through the various actions they can take on an inbound document task."}, {"id": 26675533867421, "title": "How to Configure a Brother ADS-4700W Scanner", "section": "Document Scanners", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/26675533867421", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose  When configuring your practice scanners, you first need to determine whether they support the SFTP (Secure File Transfer Protocol) or WebDAV (HTTPS) network protocol. This user guide provides detailed steps on how to configure a Brother ADS-4700W scanner, which is an example of a common scanner model which utilises SFTP. Configuration steps Step 1 First, you need to set up a SFTP profile. \n Connect the scanner to the same network as the computer you will use to configure it. \n Follow the instructions here to set up a ‘Scan to SFTP’ Profile from your computer: Set up a Scan to SFTP Profile | ADS‑3100 | ADS‑3300W | ADS‑4100 | ADS‑4500W \n \n When setting up the profile: \n Enter the scanner credentials provided in Medicus into the corresponding options in the SFTP profile - including uploading the Server public key provided. \n Configure the following options: \n \n \n \n Settings \n \n Colour \n B&W 300 dpi \n \n \n File type \n PDF multi-page \n \n \n Skip blank page \n On \n \n \n Document separation \n Off \n \n \n 2-sided scan \n On \n \n \n Continuous scan \n Off \n \n \n Port number \n 22 \n \n   Step 2 Next, you need to set up a shortcut for the SFTP profile. \n On the scanner, navigate to ‘FTP/SFTP’ - which can be found on page 2/3 of the scanner’s homepage. \n You should see your SFTP profile displayed - in the top right-hand corner click ‘Save as Shortcut' and confirm this action. \n Set a name for your shortcut (e.g Medicus) and then check the box to set as a One Touch Shortcut. This option can now be accessed via the Shortcuts button on the scanner’s homepage. \n Your scanner is now set up - please scan a test document (i.e. a document with no patient identifying information) to ensure that, once scanned, it successfully appears in Medicus for processing.   Note: If the connection times out trying to connect to the Medicus SFTP server, you may need to set the scanner’s DNS server IP address manually. Go to Network -> TCP/IP (Wireless) -> Advanced Set the DNS Server Method to STATIC Enter your network's DNS Servers IP addresses"}, {"id": 16428498041245, "title": "How to Reset your Two Factor Authentication", "section": "Login & Account Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16428498041245", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose If you need to reset your authenticator app, the steps outlined in this guide will show you how to do this. Navigating to your account settings Navigate to your account settings by: \n Select your name in the bottom left corner of the screen \n Select 'My Account' from the settings \n Resetting your 2FA \n Remove your old 2FA code from your authenticator app so you can create a new 2FA code.  \n On the 'Login and Security' screen click the 'reset 2FA' button \n \n This will open a new window with a QR code, scan the QR code with your authenticator app to create a new entry for your Medicus 2FA code.  \n   4. Once you've scanned the code click Next. A pop up window will open and request the 6 digit token from your authenticator app.    Enter the 6 digit token then click Verify & reset. You should now have reset your 2FA access and can use it to login to your Medicus account along with your username and password. You do not need to enter the code from your app as a recovery code."}, {"id": 18264214044957, "title": "Redacting from Patient Online Access & Marking Confidential from Third Parties", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18264214044957", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n There may be some information in the patient's record that you may not want the patient to see online, for example on the NHSapp, or share with third parties, like the shared care record, because this visibility could place the patient at risk of harm if disclosed. This user guide will show you how to how to redact care record elements from patient online access and mark confidential from third parties. \n Redacting from patient online access and marking confidential \n When completing any actions on the care record which will be saved on the patient's journal, for example, a note, appointment or consultation, you'll notice two fields on the forms: \n \n Redact from patient online access \n Mark confidential from third parties \n \n These checkboxes will default as unticked, but you can check these boxes if appropriate."}, {"id": 20585685078941, "title": "The Patient Banner", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20585685078941", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n When interacting with a patient, the patient banner at the top of the record not only mitigates clinical safety risks relating to mis-identification, but also enables a more personal interaction with the patient. This user guide will show you how to view and interpret the patient banner. \n Viewing the patient banner \n The banner is displayed at the top of the patient's record. To expand the banner to see additional details, you can click the arrow in the top left hand corner of the banner. \n \n This expands the banner if you need to view additional information about the patient. \n \n Identification \n To help you ensure you have the correct patient the banner displays the following information at all times: \n \n Patient name \n Preferred name (if known) \n DOB and age \n NHS number \n Pronouns (if known) \n Home Address (Click on the address from the patient banner will open Google Maps) \n Temporary address (if one is set) \n Temporary phone number (if one is set) \n Next of kin  \n \n The patient's gender, address and contact information is also displayed upon expanding the banner. \n Safeguarding risks, reasonable adjustments & legal information \n In addition to identifying information, the patient banner is used to make you aware of any safeguarding risks, reasonable adjustments or legal information so you can be aware during patient interactions. \n Displayed information includes: \n \n Safeguarding risks - including coded SNOMED CT risk flags and CP-IS child protection alerts, \n Reasonable adjustments - this is a legal duty to ensure the patient's equality needs are taken into account, \n Legal information - legal obligations the practice needs to be aware of e.g. lasting power of attorney. \n \n Risk flags (which are added via care record note) are displayed as an amber warning on the patient banner. If a patient has more than one risk flag associated to them, the number of flags is displayed in brackets. \n \n To find more information on the risk flags, select the link to view additional information. \n Here you can see the code behind the risk flag and at what date this was added to the patient record. \n \n Select 'View more' to view additional details."}, {"id": 31210841132317, "title": "Merge Duplicate Patient Records", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/31210841132317", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose  This feature lets you merge duplicate patient records in Medicus that refer to the same person. To use Patient Merges you need the user role Clinical Management or Operational Management.  Merge Patient Records Starting a patient merge To create a new patient merge, go to Modules > Patient Registration > Patient Merges. On this page you will see a list of historical patient merges, including their status. Select Merge Patient and review the merge instructions. Selecting patients to merge If you are merging an inactive patient we recommend opening their record and filling out the Restricted Record Access reason before starting the patient merge.  Once you hit Continue, a modal will open which allows you to search for the patient records to include in the merge. Select the first patient record to include in the merge.   It doesn't matter which patient record is selected first, as you will choose which patient record should be kept at a later stage. Once you have selected the first patient record, select the second patient record to include in the merge. If there are more than two duplicate records, you will only be able to select one patient record at this stage. You can merge the remaining patient record by completing the same steps after merging the first two records. Choose which patient record to keep Once the second patient is selected, the records of both patients will be displayed side by side so that you can compare them.  You can click on the drop-down to navigate to other tabs within the patient record. Once you have chosen which patient record to keep, select either Keep patient A or Keep patient B. The content of the record that you choose not to keep will be merged into the record that you choose to keep.  Confirm the merge Once you have selected the patient record to keep, you will be shown which patient record will be kept and which patient record will be deleted. Once have confirmed the selected patient record to keep, select Confirm and continue. If you want to to change you selection, select Back. Once you select Confirm and Continue, you will need to confirm that you understand the merge cannot be undone by typing \"I understand that this action cannot be undone\".  Once you have done this, select Merge Patients.  After successfully confirming the patient merge, the Patient Merge Next Steps modal will be displayed which will inform you of any steps you need to take eg. Contacting PCSE or PDS. The instructions in the modal will vary depending on the type of patient merge. You will then be able to see the status of a patient merge on the Patient Merge page. FAQ Who can perform a patient merge? Only users who have the permission Perform NHS Restricted Patient Actions will be able to perform a patient merge. This will be users with the user roles Clinical Management or Operational Management.   How many patient records can be merged? Two patient records can be merged at a time. If you have more than two patient records which need merging, you can merge the first two records and then subsequently, merge further records.   Can I merge a deceased patient record into another patient record? No, it is not possible to merge a patient record if one or both of the records are marked as deceased.   Can a patient merge be reversed? Patient merges cannot be reversed. Please make sure to thoroughly check that the correct patient records have been selected before confirming that you want to proceed with the patient merge."}, {"id": 32385807299357, "title": "Child Protection Alerts", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32385807299357", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose The Child Protection-Information Sharing (CP-IS) programme supports secure information sharing between Local Authorities and healthcare settings for any child or young person who: \n Is a 'Looked After child' (LAC)  \n Has a ‘Child Protection Plan’ (CPP)  \n CP-IS also shares information for any unborn baby with an 'Unborn Child Protection Plan (UCPP), linked to the pregnant patient’s record. This article explains how these alerts work in Medicus.  Child Protection Alerts in Medicus Along with other safeguarding information, CP-IS alerts are displayed in the patient banner in Medicus to highlight the information to those viewing the patient record.  Medicus retrieves the Child Protection alerts from CP-IS via API, as opposed to from codes added to the record. The types of Child Protection alerts we display are: \n Child Protection Plan (CPP) \n Looked After Child (LAC) \n Unborn Child Protection Plan (UCPP) \n Hovering over the badge in the patient banner will show additional information including the local authority and the plan start and end date (if known). You can click on the badge to view more information.  CP-IS alerts remain visible on the record after the end date. CPP’s and LAC’s are displayed for 364 days after the end date. UCPP’s are displayed for 28 days after the end date.  Setting up notifications for CP-IS traces  You can set up CP-IS trace notifications in Modules > Patient Information Maintenance > CP-IS > Configuration. Here you can specify who the email notifications should be sent to. The email will include a link to the Positive Trace report. On the Positive Traces tab you also can view a list of all past alerts."}, {"id": 17119784087581, "title": "How to Export a Patient Record", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17119784087581", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose For times when you need to export an entire patient record, for example in the event of a Subject Access Request, you can easily do this in Medicus. This user guide outlines the steps required to export a patient record, for both printing and downloading. Exporting the patient record To export a patient record, select the Actions > Print/Export Record  in the top right corner of the patient  Care Record. You'll be presented with a pop out form with some options as to how to export the patient record and what elements of the patient record to include. The options are: \n Basic Clinical Summary \n Repeat Medication List \n Immunisation History \n Investigation Results \n Consultations \n Administrative and contact details \n Full Patient Record \n   For confidentiality, you can choose to: \n Remove records redacted from patient online access \n Remove records marked as confidential from third parties \n   You can also set a date range if you want to limit the data exported.   Once you have chosen, you can choose to either  Print  or  Download.   If choosing to download the full patient record, the file will download as a zip file. You can then open the zip file to access the PDF document. \n Patient record format When viewing the exported record, it should be viewable in the following example formats. Exported administrative details: Exported prescription: Exported consultation report document:"}, {"id": 17621234359965, "title": "Managing a Patient's Consent Preferences", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17621234359965", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator", "ANP", "Nurse"], "body": "Purpose \n Different patients may express different preferences on receiving communications or sharing data to various parties. This user guide will show you how to view and update a patient's consent preferences in Medicus.  \n Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. \n Consent to Publish Summary Care Record (SCR) \n Medicus does not permit the entry of SCR Consent SNOMED CT codes into a consultation or directly to the patient care record as an ad-hoc Care Record Note. A patient’s consent for SCR sharing must be updated from the administrative record in the 'Data Sharing' tab. \n Note:  you'll need to be logged in with your NHS Smartcard to edit a patient's SCR consent. \n Select the 'Consent to publish SCR' field to open up a form on the right hand side of the screen. \n \n Select the pencil icon to edit the settings. \n \n You'll be presented with the following three options when editing a patient's SCR: \n \n Express consent for medication, allergies and adverse reactions only. \n Express consent for medication, allergies, adverse reactions, AND additional information. \n Express dissent (opted out) - Patient does not want a Summary Care Record. \n \n You'll be prompted to enter a reason for changing SCR consent before saving this action. \n \n Once you've saved changes, this will be updated in the administrative record. \n \n You can also view a log of consent history from the 'Manage Summary Care Record' slide over screen. \n \n Type 1 Opt-Out Status \n A patient may express a Type 1 Opt-Out if they have a preference to prevent information being shared outside the GP practice, e.g. to NHS England, for purposes other than direct care. \n You can view and edit a patient's Type 1 Opt-Out status easily from the administrative record. \n From the 'Data Sharing' tab, select the 'Type 1 opt out status' field. This will open up a slide over screen on the right hand side to edit the status. \n \n Once changed, select the 'Save changes' button.  \n \n The opt out status will now be updated on the patient record. \n National Data Opt-Out (NDOP) \n A patient may express an NDOP if they'd like to prevent data from being used for research and planning purposes at the national level e.g. with the University of Oxford. \n The NDOP cannot be changed in Medicus, but it set by patients in the \"Your NHS Data Matters\" Website . \n This information will then be passed through to Medicus and stored in the background of the system."}, {"id": 16593309476637, "title": "Managing a Patient's Language Preferences", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16593309476637", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose English may not always be a patient's first language, and they may require an interpreter. This information is stored and can be updated within a patient's administrative record so you can be aware of this whilst managing a patient's care. This guide outlines how to view and update language preference settings within the patient record. Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. Managing preferred languages Within the patient's administrative record you can view a patient's preferred language, and whether or not the patient requires an interpreter. To edit these settings, simply click on any of the fields to open up a form to complete. This will be a dropdown list to select the preferred language from, and a checkbox to add whether or not the patient requires an interpreter. Click the Save button to update the settings."}, {"id": 16572368742301, "title": "How to Manage a Patient's Associated Contacts", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16572368742301", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose In Medicus, there is the option to add in key contacts for a patient within the administrative record. This can be useful information for you to see, and also gives you the option to copy contacts into correspondence to a patient. This user guide will show you how to manage patient contacts in Medicus. Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. Viewing, editing and removing existing contacts Existing patient contacts can be seen under the 'Contacts' section in the personal details tab of the administrative record. This will show the name of the contact, with the relationships in brackets. If you need to edit or remove an existing contact, simply click on the contact you would like to edit. This will bring up more details of the contact on the right hand side of the screen. If you'd like to edit the patient contact select the 'Edit' button and if you'd like to delete the patient contact select the 'Remove' button. If editing, you'll be brought to an 'Edit Contact' screen where you can edit the relationship and permissions to copy in patient correspondence. Once updated, you can save changes to update the contact. Adding a new contact To add a new contact, select the Add a contact link on the top right corner of the contacts box. You will be presented with three options: \n \n Add another patient -  add another patient active in Medicus as a contact. \n \n Add a contact from another patient record -  add another patient active in Medicus already listed as a contact in another patient record. \n \n Add a brand new contact -  add a patient contact who is not an active patient in Medicus. \n The guidance below covers how to add a patient contact for each of the three available options. Add another patient Selecting this option opens up the patient finder to select another active patient in Medicus to add as a patient contact. Once you select a patient from the patient finder, you will be brought to a Add Patient Contact form. The contact's demographic details will be displayed so you can double check you have selected the correct patient before completing the form. Once you've completed the information, select the Add button.  The contact will now appear in the patient's contacts list within the administrative record. Add a contact from another patient record This option is if you would like to add a patient contact that is already active on another patient record. For example, if a mother of two is recorded as a patient contact for one child, you could navigate to the second child and add the mother as a patient contact using this method. Selecting this option will open up the patient finder. Once you have selected the patient record that you would like to copy the contact from, you'll be taken to a pop-up to choose which associated contact to add. Once you have selected the contact you would like to add you will be prompted to complete additional information on the relationship. Once you've completed the information, select the Add button.  The contact will now appear in the patient's contacts list within the administrative record. Add a brand new contact The final option is to add a brand new contact who is not currently an active patient in Medicus. Selecting this option will present you with a contact form to complete, with additional demographic details that are not already stored in the system. Once you've completed the information, select the Save button.  The contact will now appear in the patient's contacts list within the administrative record. Listed as a contact for On the patient's record, as well as viewing what contacts a patient has, you will also be able to see if a patient is listed as a contact for anyone else in Medicus. If a patient is not listed as a contact for anyone in Medicus, this box will not be visible within the patient administrative record."}, {"id": 16601471793309, "title": "Managing a Patient's Pharmacy Nominations", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16601471793309", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose A patient may need to change their nominated pharmacy for a number of reasons. For example, they may move house and would like their prescriptions to be sent closer to home, or they may want their nominated pharmacy to be near their place of work. You can edit a patient's nominated pharmacy in Medicus in two ways: \n From the patient's administrative record. \n Whilst issuing a prescription. \n This guide will show you how to do this for both of the above methods. Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. Updating pharmacy nominations from the patient record The easiest way to update a patient's EPS pharmacy nominations is from the patient record. Here you can add or change a patient's: \n Community pharmacy \n Appliance dispenser \n Dispensing doctor \n From the Administrative Record Firstly, you can do this by going to  Administrative Record > Personal Details > EPS Pharmacy Nominations.   Select the option you would like to remove or change and you'll be brought to a pop out form to complete.   \n From the Medication Regimen You can edit the EPS Pharmacy Nomination from the Medication Regimen. To do this with the patient record open >  Care Record > Medication Regimen.     Select the option you would like to remove or change and you'll be brought to a pop out form to complete.   When issuing a prescription You can also change the patient's pharmacy nominations when issuing a prescription. To do this, simply click  Change  under the current nominated pharmacy.   From here, you can either: \n Change the EPS pharmacy nomination on their record by selecting Change \n \n Search for a one-off pharmacy  \n Select that the patient wishes to collect from any pharmacy using an EPS token"}, {"id": 16572056873373, "title": "How to Manage a Patient's Contact Information", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16572056873373", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose It's important to keep a patient's contact details up to date, to ensure correspondence by SMS and email are sent to the correct person. This guide will show you how to view and update a patient's contact information. Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. Contact information Viewing and editing existing contact information Under the Contact Information section on the personal details tab of the patient's administrative record, you can view existing contact information for a patient. To edit or amend existing contact information, simply select the information you would like to change. This will open up a form where you can either edit or delete the phone number or email. Once you've made changes, click the Save changes button. Adding new contact information To add new contact information, select the 'Add' button and choose from two options from the dropdown: \n Telephone number \n Email address \n This will open up a form for you to complete the contact information details. Once completed, select 'Save'. The details will now show on the patient's administrative record. Note:  If a temporary phone number is set for a patient then it will be visible on the patient banner. Preferred number for text messages If a patient has multiple mobile numbers in their contact details, SMS communications will only be sent to the phone number which last had Preferred telephone number for SMS selected. SMS communications will only go out to this one mobile number rather than multiple. If no preferred number for SMS has been set then SMS communications will be sent to the last mobile number added to the patients contact information. PDS synchronisation tasks Medicus will auto-update the patient's record based on any PDS changes to ensure the two are in syncronisation. However, if one of the following fields are changed then a task is created to inform you of the change and take any action if required: \n Address \n Phone number \n Email Address \n DOB \n Gender"}, {"id": 16566146089373, "title": "How to View and Manage a Patient's Addresses", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16566146089373", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This guide provides instructions on how to view, update, delete or add new address types to a patient's record. Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. Address types There are four address types within Medicus that you can save for a patient: \n \n Home address - this is the main address for the patient. Many patient's will only have a home address. \n \n Work address  - this is the address for a patient's place of work. \n \n Other address  - if a patient has another place of correspondence other than home and work, it can be recorded under 'other'. \n \n Temporary address  - temporary addresses can be recorded in Medicus, for example, for student accommodation. \n Adding a new address To add a new address, select the Add Address link on the top right of the address box. This will open up a form for you to select the address type and then enter the address details. Select the 'Save' button to save the address. When adding a temporary address, you'll also be prompted to add the temporary address type from a dropdown list. This mirrors the temporary address types within PDS. You'll also be asked for the date in which the temporary address will be in use until. Note:  If a temporary address is set for a patient then it will be visible on the patient banner. Viewing, updating or deleting an existing address You can view and update an existing address by selecting the address field. This opens up a viewing screen on the right hand side. Select the Edit button if you would like to update the address. You will then be taken to a screen where you can update the address. Once updated select the 'Save changes' button to save the updated address. If you'd like to delete an address no longer in use, you can select the Delete button. Patients who live at the same address A quick way to view if another patient is registered to the same address is to view the Also at this address field when viewing the home address. Note that for a patient to show within this section, they must be actively registered with Medicus and the address type must be a home address. PDS synchronisation tasks Medicus will auto-update the patient's record based on any PDS changes to ensure the two are in syncronisation. However, if one of the following fields are changed then a task is created to inform you of the change and take any action if required: \n Address \n Phone number \n Email Address \n DOB \n Gender"}, {"id": 16554037740957, "title": "How to Update a Patient's Name and Demographic Details", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16554037740957", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose You may need to update a patient's demographic details at some point. This guide will show you how to update a patient's name or demographic details in Medicus from the patient's administrative record. Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. Name and demographics Once in the patient's administrative record, you can update any field under the Name & Demographics section by simply selecting the one you want to edit. This will open a form for you to complete and save changes. The only field you cannot update from this section is the patient's NHS number as this is a read only field within PDS. Former name There is also an option in the top right corner of the Name & Demographics section to add a patient's former name. Here are some examples of situations where you may want to add a former name to a patient: \n A patient has recently married and changed their last name, therefore you may want to add their previous surname as a former name. \n A patient is transgender and has changed their official name, therefore you may want to add their previous name as a former name. \n Preferred pronouns Some patients may have a preferred pronoun. To help staff address patients using the correct pronoun, you can edit preferred pronoun within Medicus. Once updated, this will appear in the patient banner so this information is clearly visible to a staff user to help them address the patient using their preferred pronouns. PDS synchronisation tasks Medicus will auto-update the patient's record based on any PDS changes to ensure the two are in syncronisation. However, if one of the following fields are changed then a task is created to inform you of the change and take any action if required: \n Address \n Phone number \n Email Address \n DOB \n Gender"}, {"id": 16549946520093, "title": "Viewing a Patient's Administrative Record", "section": "Patient Records", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16549946520093", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose The patient's administrative record contains all of the none clinical information related to a patient. This includes contact information, demographic details, registration, data sharing consent and communication preferences. This guide will show you how to view information on a patient's administrative record. Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. Viewing the administrative record Patient Banner When a patient record is selected, the patient banner prominently shows which patient record is in use. Therefore, it's a great way to double check you are in the correct record before performing any actions. To view additional demographic and contact information, select the arrow within the banner on the left hand side to extend the patient banner. You can do this whilst on any tab on either the clinical or administrative record. Personal Details Within the patient details tab you can view and edit: \n A patient's name \n Demographics details \n Contact information \n Preferred language \n Communication preferences  \n Pharmacy nominations \n Registration Within the registration tab you can: \n View and/or update current registration details \n Start the deduction process \n View previous registrations \n View a patient's PDS link \n Data Sharing The Data Sharing tab allows you to: \n Edit a patient's Data Sharing Consents \n Setup and edit Patient Online Access \n Tasks  The Tasks tab will show all tasks related to the patient.  Online Access  The Online Access tab allows you to grant the patient online access to their patient record. Booking Links The Booking Links tab shows all booking links generated for a patient. It will show when the link was created, the appointment service and type, the reason for the appointment and whether an appointment was booked via the link. Clicking onto an appointment will show further information, like who sent the booking link to the patient. Internal Conversations The Internal Conversations tab will show any internal conversations linked to the patient. Yellow Cards The Yellow Cards tab on the administrative record details any yellow cards submitted to MHRA for that patient."}, {"id": 32754393617181, "title": "How to mark a patient as deceased - Guernsey Practices", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32754393617181", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose When a patient has passed away, you will need to mark the patient as deceased in their medical record. This article will show you how to mark a patient as deceased in Medicus in a non-NHS organisation. Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. Marking a patient as deceased  From the patient's administrative record, scroll to the bottom of the Personal Details tab and you will see the option to Record Patient's Death. You will then be asked to confirm that you definitely want to mark this patient as deceased. To confirm, select Mark as Deceased. This will add the Deceased code to the patient's medical record."}, {"id": 17660437214237, "title": "Managing Practice Closure Periods", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17660437214237", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose Organisation closure periods allow you to record dates and times that the whole practice or specific sites will be closed. If a staff member then tries to schedule any activities during a closure period they will be presented with a warning message informing them of this. This user guide will show you how to record and manage practice closure periods in Medicus. Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. Once in the scheduling module, select 'Configuration' on the left hand side navigation bar.   Select 'Closure Periods' to navigate to the closure periods tab. Recording a closure period Navigate to the closure periods tab and then click Add closure in the top right.  This will open up the 'Record Closure Period' form to enter the following details about the closure period. Information you'll need: \n Start and end date / time. \n Site - if the closure period is only at a specific site, record it here. If the closure period if for the whole organisation, you can leave this blank. \n \n Reason - enter the closure period reason as free text. \n If there are any appointments already scheduled during the closure period you'll be warned of this on the 'Record Closure Period' form. Editing a closure period To edit an existing closure period, simply select the closure period you'd like to edit from the calendar to open up the 'Edit Closure Period' form. Update any fields you'd like to update and then select 'Save changes'. Deleting a closure period To delete a closure period, select 'Delete' from the 'Edit Closure Period' form. Practice closure warning When scheduling staff activities from the staff schedule page, if you try scheduling during an organisation closure period then you'll see a warning message displayed. If only a specific site is closed, then the warning message will only be displayed if you select that specific site whilst scheduling a staff appointment diary."}, {"id": 32751999869469, "title": "Managing custom registration types", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32751999869469", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose You may want to register patients under a custom registration type to differentiate them from the default registration types of Permanent, Temporary Resident or Immediate Necessary Treatment. This help article will go through the steps to create and manage custom registration types. Creating a custom registration type To create a custom registration type, go to Modules > Patient Registration > Registration Types. You will see the Medicus Registration Types which are the default types and cannot be edited. You will also see any existing Custom Registration Types. To create a new registration type, select Add Registration Type. You can then give the registration type a name. You can also give the registration type a default registration period. If you do give it a default registration period, the registration will automatically end after this time period. If no default registration period is given, the registration will stay active until manually ended. To save the new registration type, select Add registration type.   Edit or archive a custom registration type To edit or archive a custom registration type, select it from the list. To edit the registration type, select the pencil icon in the top right hand corner. You will then be able to edit the name and the default registration period. You can archive the registration type by selecting Archive."}, {"id": 32753200585245, "title": "Resolving failed communication tasks", "section": "Patient Communications", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32753200585245", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose When sending messages to patients, the message can sometimes fail to send. This can happen for a few reasons, for example, the patient's mobile was not able to receive the message or the mobile number was invalid. If a message fails to send to a patient, a failed communication task will be created so that the message can be resent or the task can be resolved. This guide walks through how to manage and complete these tasks.  Resolving a failed communication task To find any failed communication tasks, go to Modules > Workflow > Configuration and System Issues > Failed Communications. Here you will see a list of any failed communications. Select a task from the list and you will see further information about the message that failed to send.   From here, you can either: \n Leave a comment on the task under Task Comments \n \n Schedule the task for later by selecting More Actions > Schedule for later. \n \n Resend the communication by selecting Next Steps > Resend Communication \n \n Do nothing and resolve task by selecting Next Steps > Do Nothing and Resolve Task"}, {"id": 32232320888733, "title": "Authenticating User Accounts with ICE or tQuest", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32232320888733", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose When a new member of staff is added to Medicus, their account will need to be linked to their ICE or tQuest account in order to order investigations through Medicus.   Link user account to their ICE or tQuest account \n Once a user's account has been set up in Medicus, their account can be linked to their ICE or tQuest account. To do this, go to Modules > Investigation Results > Service Providers \n \n \n Select the service provider that you want to add account details for. \n \n \n \n From the user list, select the user you would like to add account details for. \n \n \n Here you can now enter the user's account details for ICE or tQuest. Once saved, their Medicus account will be linked to ICE or tQuest and they will be able to order investigations through Medicus."}, {"id": 18513503853469, "title": "Recording an Observation", "section": "Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18513503853469", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose Recording observations is vital to support diagnosis, monitoring and aid patient care. This user guide will show you how to record an observation in Medicus and how to view observations on the patient record. Recording an observation There are two ways to record an observation in Medicus: \n From a consultation \n From the care record \n Recording an observation from a consultation To record an observation from a consultation, select Observation from the More actions menu, or use '/' to select Observation from the quick action shortcut. You could also code some observations to open up the form e.g. '.bp' to record blood pressure. Recording an observation from the care record You can also record an observation directly from the care record. To do this, select Observation from the Actions menu from a patient's care record. Completing the record observation form Once you've selected to record an observation, you'll be taken to the record observation form. The first thing you'll need to enter is the type of observation you'd like to record. This will search for SNOMED CT observation codes. Any previously recorded observations for the selected observation type will be displayed. Once you've selected the code you're looking for, select Save. Selecting an observation type will tailor the record observation form to the required fields for that observation type. For example Blood Pressure:   Note:  for any observation codes that Medicus does not have required fields information for, the form will show all possible fields. As the clinician, you can complete the fields that are required for the observation you are taking. If an observation is inputted which is considered as too high, a warning will be displayed so that the input can be corrected. Finalising the observation form Once you've completed all the required fields on the form, select Save . This will save the observation against the care record which will be visible on the patient journal."}, {"id": 31734188621341, "title": "Receiving and Actioning Patient Clinical Requests", "section": "Patient Portal and Online requests", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/31734188621341", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose The Medicus Online Consultations functionality can be useful for clinical triage requests that patients send through the patient portal. This user guide will show you how patients submit clinical requests from the portal, and how you can action them. How patients submit a clinical request from the patient portal The link to the patient portal will most likely be made available on your practice website where patients can either send in clinical requests, admin queries or request their repeat prescriptions. The times at which patients can send in clinical requests is controlled by the practice so patients can only submit these at times that a clinician is available to review them. Selecting I have a medical request will take them through to the clinical request form. Before they complete the form, they must enter their name, DOB and postcode so Medicus can match the form to a registered patient. If we can't match the details to a patient record we will direct the patient to try again or contact the practice directly.  Note: We require the patient to have either a mobile phone number or email address saved in their record for them to be able to submit a request. If they don't, we will display a message saying \"It is not possible to submit your request online because we do not have a valid email address or mobile number on record for this patient. Please contact the surgery instead.\" When we have been able to match the details submitted to a patient record, the following information is entered by the patient and submitted: Actioning a Patient Request task Requests come into the system as a Patient Request task and will appear in either the medical, admin or prescription request task queue depending on the option the patient selected. Tasks are assigned to the default team, which is typically staffed by clinical members who can review and triage the requests according to your local processes. The task layout is the same as other task types in Medicus, with the task details on the left hand side and the patient record on the right. Details of the patient request form can be seen under the Initial Request section of the task details. From the task, you can respond to the request as required. From the Codes and Actions field, you can: \n Type free text \n Add any clinical coding by typing a \".\" to code \n Complete any required actions by typing a \"/\" to open up the quick actions menu - for example, send another message to the patient, prescribe a medication or issue a fit note. \n   If you would like patients to be able to reply when sending a message, when in the New Communication modal, select Allow Replies. This will allow the patient to respond to the conversation thread until the thread is marked as resolved.   If you would like to redact the patient request from being visible via online access, you can do this within the task by selecting Redacted from patient online access."}, {"id": 21652547816605, "title": "Receiving and Actioning Patient Clinical Requests", "section": "Patient Requests - Online Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21652547816605", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose The Medicus Online Consultations functionality can be useful for clinical triage requests that patients send through the patient portal. This user guide will show you how patients submit clinical requests from the portal, and how you can action them. How patients submit a clinical request from the patient portal The link to the patient portal will most likely be made available on your practice website where patients can either send in clinical requests, admin queries or request their repeat prescriptions. The times at which patients can send in clinical requests is controlled by the practice so patients can only submit these at times that a clinician is available to review them. Selecting I have a medical request will take them through to the clinical request form. Before they complete the form, they must enter their name, DOB and postcode so Medicus can match the form to a registered patient. If we can't match the details to a patient record we will direct the patient to try again or contact the practice directly.  Note: We require the patient to have either a mobile phone number or email address saved in their record for them to be able to submit a request. If they don't, we will display a message saying \"It is not possible to submit your request online because we do not have a valid email address or mobile number on record for this patient. Please contact the surgery instead.\" When we have been able to match the details submitted to a patient record, the following information is entered by the patient and submitted: Actioning a Patient Request task Requests come into the system as a Patient Request task and will appear in either the medical, admin or prescription request task queue depending on the option the patient selected. Tasks are assigned to the default team, which is typically staffed by clinical members who can review and triage the requests according to your local processes. The task layout is the same as other task types in Medicus, with the task details on the left hand side and the patient record on the right. Details of the patient request form can be seen under the Initial Request section of the task details. From the task, you can respond to the request as required. From the Codes and Actions field, you can: \n Type free text \n Add any clinical coding by typing a \".\" to code \n Complete any required actions by typing a \"/\" to open up the quick actions menu - for example, send another message to the patient, prescribe a medication or issue a fit note. \n   If you would like patients to be able to reply when sending a message, when in the New Communication modal, select Allow Replies. This will allow the patient to respond to the conversation thread until the thread is marked as resolved.   If you would like to redact the patient request from being visible via online access, you can do this within the task by selecting Redacted from patient online access."}, {"id": 31734105772189, "title": "Receiving and Actioning Patient Admin Requests", "section": "Patient Requests - Online Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/31734105772189", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose The Medicus Online Consultations functionality can be useful for online admin requests that patients send through the patient portal. For example, a patient may need to chase test results or request a sick note. This user guide will show you how patients submit admin requests from the portal, and how you can action them. How patients send admin requests from the patient portal The link to the patient portal will most likely be made available on your practice website where patients can either send in clinical requests, admin queries or request their repeat prescriptions. Selecting I have an admin query will take them through to the admin request form. Before they complete the form, they must enter their name, DOB and postcode so Medicus can match the form to a registered patient. The patient is asked to describe their request before submitting. Actioning admin request tasks These requests that can be matched to a patient come into the system as a admin request task. They are assigned to the default team, which is typically staffed by admin members who can review and respond to the requests appropriately. The task layout is the same as other task types in Medicus, with the task details on the left hand side and the patient record on the right. Details of the patient request form can be seen under the Initial Request section of the task details. From the task, you can respond to the request as required. From the Codes and Actions field, you can: \n Type free text \n Add any clinical coding by typing a \".\" to code \n Complete any required actions by typing a \"/\" to open up the quick actions menu - for example, send another message to the patient, prescribe a medication or issue a fit note. \n If you would like patients to be able to reply when sending a message, when in the New Communication modal, select Allow Replies. This will allow the patient to respond to the conversation thread until the thread is marked as resolved. If you would like to redact the patient request from being visible via online access, you can do this within the task by selecting Redacted from patient online access."}, {"id": 21653504403869, "title": "Receiving and Actioning Patient Admin Requests", "section": "Patient Portal and Online requests", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21653504403869", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose The Medicus Online Consultations functionality can be useful for online admin requests that patients send through the patient portal. For example, a patient may need to chase test results or request a sick note. This user guide will show you how patients submit admin requests from the portal, and how you can action them. How patients send admin requests from the patient portal The link to the patient portal will most likely be made available on your practice website where patients can either send in clinical requests, admin queries or request their repeat prescriptions. Selecting I have an admin query will take them through to the admin request form. Before they complete the form, they must enter their name, DOB and postcode so Medicus can match the form to a registered patient. The patient is asked to describe their request before submitting. Actioning admin request tasks These requests that can be matched to a patient come into the system as a admin request task. They are assigned to the default team, which is typically staffed by admin members who can review and respond to the requests appropriately. The task layout is the same as other task types in Medicus, with the task details on the left hand side and the patient record on the right. Details of the patient request form can be seen under the Initial Request section of the task details. From the task, you can respond to the request as required. From the Codes and Actions field, you can: \n Type free text \n Add any clinical coding by typing a \".\" to code \n Complete any required actions by typing a \"/\" to open up the quick actions menu - for example, send another message to the patient, prescribe a medication or issue a fit note. \n If you would like patients to be able to reply when sending a message, when in the New Communication modal, select Allow Replies. This will allow the patient to respond to the conversation thread until the thread is marked as resolved. If you would like to redact the patient request from being visible via online access, you can do this within the task by selecting Redacted from patient online access."}, {"id": 32242854275741, "title": "Future Action Rules", "section": "Long Term Condition Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32242854275741", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article explains the Future Action Rules feature in Medicus. Future Action Rules, when switched on, automatically insert Future Actions into a patient’s record so that it is clear from the Clinical Summary page what needs to be done for that patient.  Turning on a Future Action Rule To view Future Actions Rules start by navigating to the Population Health Management module. From here you can view the catalogue of rules, this will show any rules not currently enabled for your practice.  Rules that correspond to QOF indicators include the indicator in the name of the rule. For example, there is a Future Action Rule “Asthma: Annual review (AST007)” this corresponds to the QOF requirement AST007. To view the description for the rule, click the name and a slideover will open.  Rules are not turned on by default but if you do want future actions to be created automatically for this indicator, click Enable rule .  The rule runs once a day (overnight) and future actions are automatically inserted into the record of patients that match the rule and are cancelled for those that no longer match the rule.  Disabling a Future Action Rule  From the list of enabled rules, select the rule you want to disable and a slideover will open. Click Disable rule to stop the automatic creation of future actions. When disabling a future action rule, all future actions created by that rule will be cancelled.  Viewing a Future Action  The Future Action that has been created will then show as Incomplete on the Future Action/Recall dashboard as well as on the patient’s clinical summary page. You can see whether a future action has been added by an individual or the system in the View Future Action/Recall slideover."}, {"id": 16699587069597, "title": "How to Manually Register a Permanent Patient", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16699587069597", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This user guide will take you through the steps to register a new permanent patient in Medicus. This involves searching for a patient on the PDS and requesting the previous GP practice for the patient's medical record. Manually creating a new permanent registration To register a new patient, navigate to the Patient Administration module from the modules menu in the left hand side navigation bar. You'll then be taken to the patient list. To register a new patient, select the New registration button in the top right hand corner of the page. You'll be taken to a pop-out prompting you to select the registration type. Select Permanent. NHS Personal Demographic Service (PDS) Note : you must be logged in with your Smartcard to search for patients on the PDS. To register a permanent patient, you are required to search for patient on the PDS. There are two ways to search for a patient: \n Using their NHS number. \n By entering other details, including DOB and last name. \n If you don't know a patient's NHS number there are four search type options: \n \n Default (incl. wildcard search) -  Allows the use of \"wildcards\" e.g. Kat* instead of Kathryn or Katherine. \n \n Historic data (incl. wildcard search) -  Same as the default search but uses patient previous names to try and return more records. \n \n Fuzzy name search -  Uses techniques to find patients using a looser search criteria e.g. by checking common homophones such as Smith vs Smythe. \n \n Exact matches only -  Only returns patients that match the search criteria exactly. \n Select the Search button once you've entered in the patient details to yield the search results. Medicus will then search on the PDS to find a matching record. Select the patient record to be taken to some additional information about the patient. Here, you can check that this is the correct patient you would like to register. If a patient is not currently registered at the practice, there will be messaging displayed at the top of the form (see screenshot above), and you will be able to proceed with the registration. If a patient already has an active registration, you will be made aware of this (see screenshot below) and will be unable to proceed with the registration. Acceptance types The information collected in the next step are NHAIS requirements that are sent to Primary Care Support England (PCSE). The information requirements differ based on the acceptance type of the patient. There are 5 different acceptance types which are outlined in the section below. Transfer in Transfer in is for patients who are currently or have been registered with another NHS England GP practice. It is the most common acceptance type and the default acceptance type in Medicus. The form for Transfer In looks like this: Some details on the form will be pre-populated, for example previous home address and previous GP practice, if the information is stored on PDS already. Birth This is for patients who are under 1 year old, were born in England, has an NHS number and have not registered with an NHS England GP practice yet. The form for Birth looks like: First acceptance First acceptance is for patients who are over 1 year old, was born in England, has an NHS number and has not registered with an NHS England GP practice yet. The form for First acceptance looks like: Immigrant This is for patients who do not have an NHS number and who were born outside of England or where the patient does have an NHS number but is returning back to England after living abroad for more than 3 months. The form for Immigrant looks like: Ex-services This acceptance type is for patients who are leaving the Defence Medical Service and entering the NHS again. The form for Ex-services looks like: Submitting the registration If you need to add notes to the registration to send to PCSE, you can select Other under GP Notes. A free text will then appear where you can add any further detail required. Once you've completed the patient registration form, select the Complete & send to PCSE button. This will prompt Medicus to do a number of things: \n Send an NHAIS acceptance to Primacy Care Support England. \n Create a patient record for the new patient with the registration date starting from today. The registration status will initially be displayed as as Acceptance being sent to Health Authority until NHAIS acceptance is confirmed. \n \n Medicus tells PDS than the patient is now registered with the new GP (this is required for the GP2GP transfer to be successful). \n The patient's medical record is also requested via GP2GP from the previous GP practice. \n Medicus creates a new task in Medicus to complete the patient registration. \n Registration Tasks Complete Patient Registration Task To avoid having to complete too many actions up front whilst ensuring the registration activities are not dropped, a task will be created to complete the registration. Within the task you can complete the following actions: \n View the current status of the GP2GP record transfer from the previous GP practice. \n Review and update the patient’s contact details. \n Review and update patient contacts. \n Review and update the patient’s EPS pharmacy nominations. \n Review and update the patient’s data sharing consents. \n Setup the patient and/or patient contacts for patient online access e.g. NHSapp. \n Once you've completed the task and you're happy everything has been completed for the registration, select the 'Complete task' button. Registration Response Tasks Once PCSE has reviewed and responded to submitted new permanent registrations, you can view and acknowledge the status of the registration. This includes acceptances, rejections, amendments and deductions.  Review new Patient Medication Tasks Any imported repeat or current medications will be de-activated on import and need to be reviewed and if appropriate re-authorised before prescribing can take place by a clinical staff member. Resolve Degraded Codes Tasks During the integration, the patient’s GP2GP EHR or extract into Medicus we will encounter some codes that we don’t support. For each of these, we need to insert a 'code degrade' that will later be resolved by either a user of Medicus or automatically. Medicus will automatically create tasks for any code degrades requiring practice staff intervention and actioning. For clinical safety reasons the ability to prescribe and issue medication is suspended until all medication and allergy degrade tasks have been dealt with."}, {"id": 20886395988893, "title": "Actioning a Permanent Registration Request from the NHS Website", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20886395988893", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose If your practice has enabled patients to register through the NHS website ( Register with a GP surgery - NHS England Digital ) then this will be the quickest way for you to register new permanent patients. This user guide will show you how to view and action permanent registration requests in Medicus. Viewing and Actioning a Permanent Registration Request Task Permanent Registration Requests will appear on your homepage if they are assigned to you or a team you're in. Note:  You must be logged in with your NHS Smartcard to perform this action. Note: If the patient who has registered does not live in the catchment area that you have defined in the NHS Register with a GP portal, the following warning message will be displayed at the top of the task - ' This patient lives outside of the catchment area that you have defined in the NHS Register with a GP surgery portal'. Once in the task, the first step is to compare the information in the patient details box with the matching PDS results. The information in the patient details section is taken from the form that the patient completes online. Medicus will take this information and search to match the patient on PDS. If the results returned via the PDS search don't match the patient details, you can click on the linked request to see more information the patient added to the form. You can find the patient's phone number here if you need to contact them. If you're happy that the PDS search has matched the patient correctly, you can then scroll down to review the registration details form. All of the required fields should be pre-populated, but you can manually edit or add anything you'd like. Once you're happy with the information in the request form, select Register patient . Registering a patient without an NHS number If the patient does not have an NHS number, then select Register without NHS number . This will open up the registration details form. You'll only be able to register this patient as a first acceptance or immigrant registration type. Accepting a Permanent Registration Request Once you've selected Register Patient the following things happen in the system: \n A new patient record is created. \n The task is completed and can be found under the Request Approved filter in the task list. \n An NHAIS acceptance message is sent via MESH. \n An GP2GP EHR request is sent to the previous GP practice (if there is one). \n A Complete Permanent Registration Task is completed. \n Other Registration Tasks Complete Patient Registration Task To avoid having to complete too many actions up front whilst ensuring the registration activities are not dropped, a task will be created to complete the registration. Within the task you can complete the following actions: \n View the current status of the GP2GP record transfer from the previous GP practice. \n Review and update the patient’s contact details. \n Review and update patient contacts. \n Review and update the patient’s EPS pharmacy nominations. \n Review and update the patient’s data sharing consents. \n Setup the patient and/or patient contacts for patient online access e.g. NHSapp. \n Once you've completed the task and you're happy everything has been completed for the registration, select the 'Complete task' button. Registration Response Tasks Once PCSE has reviewed and responded to submitted new permanent registrations, you can view and acknowledge the status of the registration. This includes acceptances, rejections, amendments and deductions.  Review new Patient Medication Tasks Any imported repeat or current medications will be de-activated on import and need to be reviewed and if appropriate re-authorised before prescribing can take place by a clinical staff member. Resolve Degraded Codes Tasks During the integration, the patient’s GP2GP EHR or extract into Medicus we will encounter some codes that we don’t support. For each of these, we need to insert a 'code degrade' that will later be resolved by either a user of Medicus or automatically. Medicus will automatically create tasks for any code degrades requiring practice staff intervention and actioning. For clinical safety reasons the ability to prescribe and issue medication is suspended until all medication and allergy degrade tasks have been dealt with."}, {"id": 32139767576861, "title": "Patient Booking links", "section": "Patient Communications", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32139767576861", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article walks you through how to send booking links to patients and view their past booking links. It also shows the patient view when they have received a link and the steps to book an appointment.  Sending a booking link  To send a booking link in Medicus you add the link to a patient communication. You can send a communication to a patient from their care record using the Actions button in the top right > Communication. You can also send a communication from a task in the Codes & Actions section or from a consultation by using / to open the actions menu and selecting Consultation. This will open the New Communication form. Type the content of your message in the message box at the top and then click Add booking link. A modal will open where you can add the details of the type of appointment you want the patient to book in for. Select the appointment service and type or the procedure you want them to book into.  Here you can also select a specific practitioner for the patient to book in with. Set the reason for the appointment and click Add link. The booking link will then automatically be added to the message content. Once the link has been added to the message you'll need to fill out the rest of the communication details. Here you can choose whether to send the message as sensitive (requiring the patient to enter their DOB to view the message), when to send the message and which channel you want to use to send the message (text message or email).  When you're done, click Send now to send the message including the booking link to the patient.  Booking links do not expire until they have been used. You can see all of the booking links that have been sent to a patient in their Administrative Record > Booking links. This list includes links that have been created but not sent to the patient. Booking an appointment from a link  Your patient will receive their communication along with the booking link, this example shows a booking link sent via email.  To access the booking link the patient needs to fill out their first name, last name, postcode and DOB. Then they'll see all available appointments for the service and type you specified in the booking link. They can also filter to a specific gender practitioner. From here the patient can select an appointment slot that suits them and book. They'll see a confirmation screen and receive a confirmation message with a cancellation link. The appointment will be automatically booked into your appointment book with the reason you set when creating the booking link."}, {"id": 32139771337501, "title": "Patient Booking links", "section": "Patient Requests - Online Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32139771337501", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article walks you through how to send booking links to patients and view their past booking links. It also shows the patient view when they have received a link and the steps to book an appointment.  Sending a booking link  To send a booking link in Medicus you add the link to a patient communication. You can send a communication to a patient from their care record using the Actions button in the top right > Communication. You can also send a communication from a task in the Codes & Actions section or from a consultation by using / to open the actions menu and selecting Consultation. This will open the New Communication form. Type the content of your message in the message box at the top and then click Add booking link. A modal will open where you can add the details of the type of appointment you want the patient to book in for. Select the appointment service and type or the procedure you want them to book into.  Here you can also select a specific practitioner for the patient to book in with. Set the reason for the appointment and click Add link. The booking link will then automatically be added to the message content. Once the link has been added to the message you'll need to fill out the rest of the communication details. Here you can choose whether to send the message as sensitive (requiring the patient to enter their DOB to view the message), when to send the message and which channel you want to use to send the message (text message or email).  When you're done, click Send now to send the message including the booking link to the patient.  Booking links do not expire until they have been used. You can see all of the booking links that have been sent to a patient in their Administrative Record > Booking links. This list includes links that have been created but not sent to the patient. Booking an appointment from a link  Your patient will receive their communication along with the booking link, this example shows a booking link sent via email.  To access the booking link the patient needs to fill out their first name, last name, postcode and DOB. Then they'll see all available appointments for the service and type you specified in the booking link. They can also filter to a specific gender practitioner. From here the patient can select an appointment slot that suits them and book. They'll see a confirmation screen and receive a confirmation message with a cancellation link. The appointment will be automatically booked into your appointment book with the reason you set when creating the booking link."}, {"id": 20588866271645, "title": "Managing a Patient's Communication Preferences", "section": "Patient Communications", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20588866271645", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Different patient's may prefer different methods of receiving communication about their care, therefore you can edit a patient's communication preference so information they receive is always sent via their preferred channel. This user guide will show you how to manage a patient's communication preference. \n\n Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. \n Managing Communication Preferences \n Once in the 'Personal Details' tab of the Administrative Record, scroll down to the 'Communication Preferences' box. Here you can amend: \n \n Preferred channel -  Medicus will default to email as the preferred channel if an email address is stored for the patient and no preferred channel is selected to save on practice SMS costs. \n \n Contact times - Free text box to store information about the patient's preferred contact times. \n \n Alternative letter format -  Here you can record whether the patient needs adjustments to their letter format such as braille, audio or larger text. \n \n Consent to receive text messages - If a patient dissents to receiving text messages you can record this here to prevent any SMS messages being sent to this patient. \n \n \n \n Selecting any of the fields will open up a pop-out form to edit and update any of communication preferences."}, {"id": 18731562544925, "title": "Comparing the Local and Spine Held Summary Care Record", "section": "Data Sharing Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18731562544925", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Pharmacist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n If you need to compare the local and spine held Summary Care Record (SCR) for a patient to check the data is in sync, you can do so from the administrative record. This user guide will show you how to compare the local and spine SCRs in Medicus. \n Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. \n Once in the administrative record, navigate to the 'Data Sharing' tab. \n \n Viewing a comparison between the local and spine held SCR \n To view a comparison between the local and spine SCR, select the 'Consent to publish SCR' field under the data sharing consents section. \n Note:  you need to be logged in with your Smartcard to perform this action in Medicus. \n \n This will open up the 'Manage Summary Care Record' screen on the right hand side. \n Select 'Compare local with Spine SCR' from the actions menu. \n \n This will open up the local SCR on the left hand side of the screen, and the spine SCR on the right. This enables you to complete a side by side comparison of the data."}, {"id": 18729957182365, "title": "Manually Updating the Summary Care Record", "section": "Data Sharing Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18729957182365", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Typically a patient's Summary Care Record (SCR) is updated automatically when the local record is updated. However, it's possible to manually update a patient's SCR from the administrative record if you need to. For example, if you need to complete some tests of the SCR functionality or if there's an error that means you need to complete a manual update. This user guide will show you how to manually update the SCR in Medicus.. \n Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. \n Once in the administrative record, navigate to the 'Data Sharing' tab. \n \n Manually updating the summary care record \n To manually update the SCR, select the 'Consent to publish SCR' field under the data sharing consents section. \n Note:  you need to be logged in with your Smartcard to perform this action in Medicus. \n \n This will open up the 'Manage Summary Care Record' screen on the right hand side. \n Select 'Send manual SCR update' from the actions menu. \n \n This will open up the 'Send Manual SCR Update' screen. \n Make sure you read the information box and if you wish to proceed select 'Add manual SCR update to queue'. \n \n This will manually add the record to the SCR update queue."}, {"id": 16746495260701, "title": "How to View and Update a Patient's Registration Details", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16746495260701", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose Once a patient is registered in Medicus, you can view and manage their registration details from their administrative record. This guide shows you how to do this in Medicus. Navigating to the administrative record There are two ways to navigate to the patient record within Medicus: \n Using the patient finder. \n By selecting a patient from the patient list, located in the Patient Administration module. \n Once you select the patient you'd like to view through one of the methods outlined above, select Administrative Record from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the administrative record. Registration details Select the Registration tab within the administrative record to view the patient's current registration details. Some of the fields are read only, like registration type, registration dates, PCSE registration status and the PDS linked NHS number. There are some registration details you can update from this page: \n A patients usual GP. \n Preferred location. \n Responsible health authority. \n Whether a patient lives in a care home or at school/university. \n Whether medication is dispensed by the practice - updating this setting will then update the patient's P3 dispensing doctor nomination. \n \n Manually removing an FP69 flag. \n You can also start a deduction request manually from this page."}, {"id": 16743012387485, "title": "How to Register a Patient for Immediate Necessary Treatment", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16743012387485", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose You may need to register a patient for Immediate Necessary Treatment, for example if they fall ill whilst away from home. This registration will be for a period of fourteen days. This guide will show you how to register a patient for Immediate Necessary Treatment in Medicus. Creating a new INT registration To register a new patient, navigate to the Patient Administration module from the modules menu in the left hand side navigation bar. You'll then be taken to the patient list. To register a new patient, select the New registration button in the top right hand corner of the page. You'll be taken to a pop-out prompting you to select the registration type. Select Immediate Necessary Treatment. NHS Personal Demographic Service (PDS) Note: you must be logged in with your Smartcard to search for patients on the PDS. To register a temporary patient, you are required to search for patient on the PDS. There are two ways to search for a patient: \n Using their NHS number. \n By entering other details, including DOB and last name. \n If you don't know a patient's NHS number there are four search type options: \n \n Default - Allows the use of \"wildcards\" e.g. Kat* instead of Kathryn or Katherine. \n \n Historic data - Same as the default search but uses patient previous names to try and return more records. \n \n Fuzzy name search -  Uses techniques to find patients using a looser search criteria e.g. by checking common homophones such as Smith vs Smythe. \n \n Exact matches only -  Only returns patients that match the search criteria exactly. \n Select the 'Search' button once you've entered in the patient details to yield the search results. The system will then search on the PDS to find a matching record. Select the patient record to be taken to some additional information about the patient. Here, you can check that this is the correct patient you would like to register. If a patient is not currently registered at the practice, there will be messaging displayed at the top of the form (see screenshot above), and you will be able to proceed with the registration. If a patient already has an active registration, Medicus will alert you of this, and will be unable to proceed with the registration. Once you've checked the patient details, click the 'Register patient' button. Registration details The INT patient registration will then be created and you'll be taken to the patient record. If you view the registration details within the administrative record, you'll see that the registration type is for immediate necessary treatment, and that their registration end date is set to end automatically in fourteen days time. Ending the registration If you'd like to end the registration manually before the fourteen day period has ended, you can do this by selecting the End registration button. You may want to do this if you'd like to convert the patient to a temporary or permanent patient as you'll need to end the current registration before beginning a new registration. You'll be presented with a pop-out confirming that you'd like to end the registration. Select the 'Yes, end registration' button. The patient will then be de-registered and will be inactive in Medicus."}, {"id": 16741525008285, "title": "How to Register a Temporary Patient", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16741525008285", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose There are a number of reasons why you may want to register a patient as temporary, for example, they may be a student who has moved home over the summer holidays. In England, a temporary patient is registered for a period of three months. This user guide will show you how to register a temporary patient in Medicus. Creating a new temporary registration To register a new patient, navigate to the Patient Administration module from the modules menu in the left hand side navigation bar. You'll then be taken to the patient list. To register a new patient, select the New registration button in the top right hand corner of the page. You'll be taken to a pop-out prompting you to select the registration type. Select Temporary resident .   NHS Personal Demographic Service (PDS) Note: you must be logged in with your Smartcard to search for patients on the PDS. To register a temporary patient, you are required to search for patient on the PDS. There are two ways to search for a patient: \n Using their NHS number. \n By entering other details, including DOB and last name. \n If you don't know a patient's NHS number there are four search type options: \n \n Default (incl. wildcard search) -  Allows the use of \"wildcards\" e.g. Kat* instead of Kathryn or Katherine. \n \n Historic data (incl. wildcard search) -  Same as the default search but uses patient previous names to try and return more records. \n \n Fuzzy name search -  Uses techniques to find patients using a looser search criteria e.g. by checking common homophones such as Smith vs Smythe. \n \n Exact matches only -  Only returns patients that match the search criteria exactly. \n Select the 'Search' button once you've entered in the patient details to yield the search results. Medicus will then search on the PDS to find a matching record. Select the patient record to be taken to some additional information about the patient. Here, you can check that this is the correct patient you would like to register. If a patient is not currently registered at the practice, there will be messaging displayed at the top of the form (see screenshot above), and you will be able to proceed with the registration. If a patient already has an active registration, Medicus will alert you of this, and will be unable to proceed with the registration. Once you've checked the patient details, click the 'Register patient' button. Registration details The temporary patient registration will then be created and you'll be taken to the patient record. If you view the registration details within the administrative record, you'll see that the registration type is temporary, and that their registration end date is set to end automatically in three months time. Ending the registration If you'd like to end the registration manually before the three month period has ended, you can do this by selecting the End registration button. You may want to do this if you'd like to convert the patient to a permanent patient as you'll need to end the temporary registration before re-registering the patient as permanent. You'll be presented with a pop-out confirming that you'd like to end the registration. Select the Yes, end registration button. The patient will then be de-registered and will be inactive in Medicus."}, {"id": 28199703955229, "title": "Viewing messages sent to patients", "section": "Patient Communications", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/28199703955229", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose This user guide shows you how to view the messages that have been sent to a patient via Medicus.    Opening the Communication Log When you have a patient open in Medicus, select the Audit tab. Once you've opened the Audit tab, select Communications  to view the patient's message history.  The communication log will show you the date and time the message was sent, the communication type, the delivery channel and the delivery status. To see more information, including the content of the message, click on to the message you need to see and a slide-over will open with the details of the message. Here you can see what (if anything) the message was coded as, who sent the message and the content of the message that was sent. To see the content of the message sent, click the link next to Delivered By and a new window will pop open that shows the content of the message."}, {"id": 16618050203037, "title": "Managing Prescriber Details for Clinical Staff", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16618050203037", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n When adding a prescribing staff member, it's important to record their prescriber type and professional registration codes. This guides outlines how to manage prescriber types and registration codes in Medicus. \n Recording the prescriber type \n There are two ways you can record the prescriber type for a staff member: \n \n When adding a new staff member, there is the field to add the prescriber type within the 'Add Staff Member' form. \n You can add or update prescriber details of an existing staff member from within the 'Staff Details' section. \n \n \n When adding or editing the prescriber type, you will select the prescriber type of the staff member from the dropdown menu. \n \n Adding professional registration codes  \n Depending on what type of staff member you select, you'll be required to add additional information around the staff member's professional registration codes before you're able to click the 'Save' button. \n For example, recording a prescriber type as 'Doctor' requires the GMC number and prescriber number."}, {"id": 16478898523677, "title": "Managing Staff Job Roles in Medicus", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16478898523677", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Job roles in Medicus are the same thing as job roles within your healthcare organisation. They are used to grant staff one or more user roles, which in turn grants the permissions and actions they can perform within Medicus. This guide outlines how to manage staff job roles in Medicus. \n Viewing job roles \n To manage job roles, select 'Staff Administration' from the Modules menu on the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n Select 'Job Roles' from the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n You can see a list of active job roles from this page. To view archived roles, you can select the 'Archived Roles' tab. \n To view details of a job role, select the job role you would like to see. \n This will open up details of the job role on the right hand side for your review. \n Creating a new job role \n To create a new job role, select the 'Create job role' button in the top right hand corner. \n \n You will be taken to a form to complete. Required fields are marked with an asterisk. \n Information to enter: \n \n Name - enter the name of the job role which will appear in Medicus. \n eMED3 fit note profession - select the job role which will appear on fit notes. This is only relevant for clinical roles. \n \n GP Connect role - select the job role that maps to GP connect. \n \n \n GPAD healthcare professional type - select the job role that maps to GPAD and will appear in the GPAD reporting. \n \n \n Default user roles - select what default user roles the typical user with this job role will be assigned. \n \n \n Once completed, select 'save'. The new job role will appear in the active job roles list, and will be available in the drop down list when adding a new staff user to Medicus. \n Editing an existing job role \n To edit an existing job role, select the job role that you would like to edit to open up the job role view.  \n Select the 'Edit' button. \n \n This will open up a form to edit the job role. Select the 'save changes' button once you've updated the desired fields. \n Archiving and unarchiving job roles \n Archiving a job role \n You can archive a job role by selecting the job role you'd like to archive from the active roles tab. \n Select the 'Archive role' button. \n \n Once you've archived a job role, you'll be able to see it in the 'Archived Roles' tab. \n Un-archiving a job role \n If you need to un-archive a job role, select the job role you'd like to un-archive from the archived roles tab. \n Select the 'Un-archive role' button. \n \n This will action the request, and the job role will be visible within the active roles tab."}, {"id": 16475329721373, "title": "Archiving a staff member", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16475329721373", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n In the event a staff member needs to be archived, for example if they are leaving the organisation and therefore should not have access to Medicus anymore, this guide will take you through the steps required to action this. \n Archiving a staff member \n To remove a staff member from your Medicus workplace, you'll first need to navigate to the 'Staff Administration' module from the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n This will take you to the staff list. \n \n From here, you can click on the staff member that you would like to archive which will take you to the staff profile. \n \n To archive the staff member, simply select the 'archive' button. \n \n Any active user roles for the staff member will be revoked when the user is archived. \n Closing out staff responsibilities \n Reassigning tasks \n When a staff member is archived it's important that: \n \n Any incomplete tasks assigned to the staff member are re-assigned. \n Any task types where the staff member is a default assignee are updated. \n \n In any of these scenarios, when you click the archive staff member button, a pop-up will appear to prompt you to reassign any outstanding tasks or default assignees. \n \n You will be unable to archive the staff member until you have completed the task reassignments. \n Handling future scheduled responsibilities \n If the staff member being archived is assigned any future staff requirements in the appointment diary, you will see these in a warning pop-up when archiving the user. \n You will still be able to go ahead and archive the user, but note that the scheduled staff assignment(s) will be removed from the diary. \n \n Usual GP \n When archiving staff members assigned as 'Doctor' user roles, the staff member may be the usual GP for certain patients registered to the practice. \n This will need to be changed to another GP before the staff member is archived. \n \n If the staff member is a usual GP for certain patients you will be prompted to change this and can choose a new usual GP from the dropdown menu before being able to press the 'Archive' button. \n Unarchiving a staff member \n After archiving a staff member, you can unarchive them by selecting the unarchive button. \n \n Once you have unarchived a staff member, their account will be reinstated and they will be able to login to Medicus. \n However, you will need to reinstate any user roles and permissions that were previously assigned to the user. \n You will also need to reassign them as the usual GP and the default assignee to any tasks if you'd like to reinstate these responsibilities upon unarchiving the user."}, {"id": 16473150488861, "title": "Adding or Removing User Role Permissions for a Staff Member", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16473150488861", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n In Medicus, permissions are granted by assigning the staff member one or more 'user roles'. This article outlines the steps required to add or remove user roles for an existing staff member, which will edit the permissions they have in the system. \n To view what permissions are granted under each user role see User Roles & Permissions. \n Navigating to edit permissions \n To add or remove user roles for a staff member, select 'Staff & User Management' from the Modules menu on the left hand side navigation bar. This will take you to the staff list. \n \n   \n   \n From here, you can click on the staff member that you would like to edit which will take you to their staff profile. \n From this page, you'll be able to add or remove user roles from the selected staff member. \n Adding a new user role to an existing staff member \n To add a new user role, select the ' Add user roles ' link from staff profile. \n \n Select the user role from the list you would like to assign to the staff member, and select 'Save'. \n \n The user role is now active and is visible on the staff member's user role list. \n \n The staff member will now have the permissions of this user role, and they will receive an email informing them that a new user role has been added to their account. \n Removing a user role from a staff member \n To remove a user role from a staff member, navigate to the Login & Security page of the staff member and select the user role you'd like to remove. \n Select 'End role' from the pop-up screen. \n \n You'll be presented with another pop-up screen to confirm you'd like to go ahead with removing the user role from the staff member. \n Select 'Yes, revoke user role'. \n \n The user role and associated permissions will now be removed for the user. The user role will still appear on the user role list, but with an end date. \n \n Revoking access \n The 'Revoke access' button on the staff profile page is available to revoke all user role permissions at once for a user. It's only required in the circumstances that the staff member will be archived."}, {"id": 16453804178973, "title": "How to Update the Details of an Existing Staff Member", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16453804178973", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n If the details of a staff member change, you can edit these from within the Staff Administration module of Medicus. This guide will provide instructions of the steps required to do this. \n Note:  if the email address of a staff member changes then follow this user guide instead.  (to link user guide on changing email address). \n Updating the details of a staff member \n To update the details of a staff member, navigate to the 'Staff Administration' module from the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n This will take you to the staff list. From here, you can click on the staff member that you would like to edit which will take you to the staff profile. \n \n \n From here, you can click on the field you would like to update. This will bring up a pop up screen to make any changes. Once updated, select 'save changes' to update the user profile. \n Note: for prescribing users you will be unable to edit the GMP PPD code from Medicus."}, {"id": 16451413925789, "title": "Resending a User Activation Link as an Administrator", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16451413925789", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n As account activation links are active for 30 days, but there may be instances where a new user may click the link too late and are therefore unable to set up their account.  As an administrator, you are able to resend the account activation link for a new user. This guide outlines the steps you need to take to action this. \n How to send a new activation link \n 1. From the modules menu on the side navigation bar select 'staff administration'. \n \n 2. From the staff list, locate and select the staff member that you would like to resend the activation code to. This will open up the staff details. \n 3. Select 'Login & Security' on the side navigation bar. \n 4. Select the 'Resent invitation link' button. \n \n 5. The user should then receive a new email with an active unique link for them to complete their account activation."}, {"id": 16321210114461, "title": "Managing Teams in Medicus", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16321210114461", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Using Teams in Medicus is a way to share workloads across your organisation and ensure tasks can be picked up by available staff members within a team, without having to rely on individual staff members. This guide outlines how to create a new team, and how to view, edit, archive and unarchive existing teams. \n Creating a new team \n To navigate to the Teams feature, select 'staff administration' from the modules menu, and then select 'Teams' on the side navigation bar. To create a new team, select the 'new team' button in the top right hand corner of the screen. \n \n This will open a pop-up form to create a new team. Enter the team name and press the save button. \n \n The new team will appear in the teams list. Note that the list is ordered alphabetically. Click on the team you've just created to open up a page which allows you to add staff members to the team. Once here, select one of the two 'add team members' buttons. \n \n Select staff members from the dropdown list and click add staff. \n \n These staff users are now members in this team and will appear under the 'Team Membership' section. \n \n Viewing and editing existing teams \n To view and edit an existing team within Medicus, simply navigate to the list of existing teams as per the instructions above and select the team you would like to view or edit from the list. \n From here, you can: \n \n Edit the team name by clicking on the name under the 'basic details' section, editing the name in the free text box and clicking save. \n Add a new team member by clicking the 'add team members' link. Search for a new staff user and select 'add staff'. \n Remove a staff user from a team by selecting the trash icon next to each team member. A pop-up confirmation message will appear. Select the 'yes, remove' button to proceed with the removal of a staff member. \n \n \n Completing any of the actions above will successfully edit the team. \n Archiving a team \n A team can be archived by selecting the 'archive team' button. \n \n Before a team can be archived, the following actions need to be completed: \n \n Any outstanding tasks assigned to the team need to be re-assigned. \n Any task types where the team is the default assignee need to be updated. \n \n A pop-up with any of these outstanding actions will appear, and you won't be able to archive the team until these have all been updated. The 'archive team' button will only be clickable once new staff and/or team members have been chosen from the dropdown boxes. \n \n Unarchiving a team \n Once a team has been archived, it is possible to unarchive it. You can do this by clicking on the 'archived teams' tab from the teams screen and then selecting the team you would like to unarchive. This action will restore any team memberships. However, this action won't  restore any default assignees on tasks."}, {"id": 16320172288285, "title": "Adding a New Staff Member", "section": "User Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16320172288285", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Clinical and operational management user roles can add new staff members to Medicus. This is controlled from within the Staff Administration Module. This guide outlines the steps required to set up a new staff member with a Medicus account. \n Steps to add a new staff member \n To navigate to the staff list, select 'staff administration' from the modules menu on the side navigation bar. You can then begin the process to add a new staff member by selecting the 'add staff member' button in the right hand corner. \n \n This will open the new staff member form where you can enter the details of the staff member, including the work email address they will use to log in. The fields marked with an asterisk are required. \n \n The staff member's job role must have already been setup within Medicus for it to appear in the drop down menu. \n It's also important here to ensure the correct user role(s) for the staff member is assigned, as this will set the role based access permissions within Medicus. These will populate automatically once the job role is selected, but can be manually adapted if required. \n Once you click 'save', an email will be sent from support@medicus.health to the staff member's work email address inviting them to join Medicus and set up their account."}, {"id": 31769942538013, "title": "How to Create and Manage Letter Templates", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/31769942538013", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose With this new function, you can create your own document templates, making it easy to quickly generate standard letters and personalise them for each patient/organisation. This helps save time, keep communications consistent, and reduce manual entry errors.  Creating and managing letter templates is available to the roles Clinical Management, Operational Management and IT Support.     Creating a New Letter Template \n \n Go to Modules → Consultations → Document templates . \n   \n \n Click “ New Template” . \n    3. Enter a template name , then click Save . \n The template will automatically open in draft mode , ready for editing. \n \n   Tip: Use clear, descriptive names (for example, Referral Letter – Dermatology ) to make templates easier to find later. \n   \n \n Once you have created the template, you can create a version. To do this, select Create Version and then give the template a version number (eg. V1).   Once you've created the version, you can add content to the template by selecting Add Content .   \n \n Select a Document Type (for example, Letter ).  \n   \n \n \n You can include header content by ticking any of the available options — Organisation Details , Patient Identification Details , and Document Title .  \n   \n \n \n Then, add your content and insert any required merge fields (such as Patient Name or Date of Birth ). These fields will automatically populate with information from the patient’s record. \n   \n \n To add a merge field and pull in information from the patient's record,  type {{ to see the list of pre-built variables you can include. To create a custom variable select “Add custom variable” and type what you would like the custom field to be called. \n   \n Click Save & preview once you’ve finished. Then click Set to Active.  \n   \n   \n Editing an Existing Template \n   \n 1. From the Templates list, search for or scroll to the template you’d like to update.   \n 2. Click on the template, then select New Version . The content from the original version will appear, allowing you to make any edits and publish the updated version. \n   \n 3. Make your updates and click Set to Current version. \n       Note: Any changes will apply to all users within your practice.    Using a Document Template \n Go to the patient’s record. \n Go to Actions > Document > From a Template , then search for and select the template you want to use. \n \n Review and adjust any patient-specific details before saving or printing the letter.   \n \n   Deleting a Template \n \n \n To archive a communication template, select the template from the template list and then select Archive template . \n   \n \n Confirm that you want to archive the template and then it will be removed from the template list. \n     Important: Deleted templates cannot be recovered, so please double-check before    deleting."}, {"id": 16321273553565, "title": "Automatic Task Assignment", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16321273553565", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose Automatic Task Assignment in Medicus ensures that incoming tasks are always routed to a responsible staff member or team. This is essential for clinical safety and prevents tasks from being left unassigned. You can configure default assignees for different task types, including inbound document tasks, so that each new task is automatically allocated to the appropriate team or user. This guide explains how to view and update Automatic Assignment Rules within the Workflow module. Navigating to the workflow setup All task assignment configuration is managed within the Workflow module. To navigate there from the homepage, select 'Workflow' from the modules menu in the left hand side navigation bar. Once in the Workflow module, scroll down the items list in the left hand side navigation menu and select 'Workflow setup'. This will take you to the 'Workflow set up' page which lands on the 'Task assignment' tab. Inbound Document assignee The Inbound document assignee in Medicus is used in instances where there is no assignee specified for a particular task type. For example, if theres a new task type introduced and no assignee has been assigned yet, those tasks will be assigned to the Inbound document assignee. The Inbound document assignee must be a single staff member, not a team. You can view the Inbound document assignee from the workflow setup page. If you'd like to change the Inbound document assignee, simply Select the pencil icon. This will open up a pop-out form to edit the Inbound document assignee. Select a staff member from the dropdown list and select the 'Save changes' button. Assigning assignees to tasks types Under the next section 'All Other Tasks', you can view and edit assignees for each task type. To update the assignee for a task type, simply select the Select the pencil icon. You will be taken to a configuration screen showing all available task types, each in its own configuration block. For each task type tick Assign all “{task type}” to enable an automatic rule. A dropdown will appear, allowing you to select either an individual staff member, or a team. Configure as many task types as needed.Ensure the All Other Tasks rule has an assignee selected (this is mandatory). Select Save changes. Assigning teams as assignees When assigning assignees to task types, it's recommended to assign a team as the default assignee rather than an individual staff member. This is to mitigate any risk of tasks not being picked up if they are assigned a single staff member who may be absent. Reassigning assignees prompts You may be prompted to reassign default assignees of task types when completing certain actions in Medicus, for example: \n When archiving a staff member who is an assignee of a task type. \n When archiving a staff member who is the last member of a team who is an assignee of a task type.  \n When archiving a team who is an assignee of a task type."}, {"id": 32083177603229, "title": "Submitting Requests on Behalf of Patients", "section": "Patient Portal and Online requests", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/32083177603229", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose Patients may raise clinical, admin or prescription requests through the patient portal, email, phone call or in person. This article shows you how to record different types of requests when you're required to submit these on behalf of patients. Medical Requests When patients have a health concern that requires review by a healthcare professional, you can raise a medical request on their behalf. Search for the patient within the Patient Finder > open their Care Record > click on the Actions button > click Patient request > select Medical request. Describe the patient's problem, confirm whether they have contacted a healthcare professional about this before and then select a team or staff member to take further action. Any urgent requests can be marked as 'high priority'. Admin Requests For non-clinical requests such as following up on test results, fit notes or booking vaccinations, you can submit this as an admin request by clicking the Actions button > Patient request > Admin Request. A short description and a named team/staff member are mandatory. Select the checkbox for 'high priority request' if it is urgent. Prescription Requests Patients can request any repeat prescription from the last 6 months, with a few exceptions that require closer clinical monitoring such as: \n Antibiotics \n Controlled substances (e.g. strong painkillers) \n You can submit these requests by clicking the Actions button > Patient request > Prescription request. Bulk prescription of all available medications is permitted by clicking 'Select all' and then assigning the request to a staff member to review and authorise: Searching for requests The patient's Clinical Summary immediately displays all 3 types of requests within the Tasks box, with high priority requests automatically shown at the top: Alternatively, you can find requests by clicking through Modules > Workflow > Patient Clinical Requests or Patient Admin Requests."}, {"id": 18523963544221, "title": "Creating and Managing a Future Action / Recall", "section": "Long Term Condition Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18523963544221", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This user guide will show you how to record, view and complete future actions / recalls in Medicus. Future actions / recalls overview Future actions or recalls are future activities planned for the patient. They should be recorded in Medicus for times when the planned activity is too far ahead for an appointment. Unlike tasks, future activities / recalls do not have a specific owner assigned until closer to the time that the action is due to be completed. An example of a future action / recall would be that a patient needs to come back for a blood test in 8 weeks time. Recording a future action / recall There are two ways to manually record a future action / recall in Medicus: \n From a consultation \n From the care record \n From a consultation To record a future action / recall from a consultation, select 'Future action/recall' from the 'More actions' menu, or use '/' to select 'Future action/recall' from the quick action shortcut. From the care record You can also record a procedure directly from the care record. To do this, select 'Future action/recall' from the 'Actions' menu from a patient's care record. Creating a future action Selecting to create a future action/recall opens up the 'Create Future Action/Recall form'. The 'Code' field utilises a SNOMED CT search. As you start to type the information, you'll be presented with a list of codes to choose from. You can either enter a specific day, month or date range for when the action is due. Backdating a future action / recall You'll notice on the form that some details are pre-populated like the record date and author under the 'Additional Details' section. Usually you won't need to edit these as a future action / recall is typically entered on the same day that the patient was last seen by the clinician who saw the patient. However there are certain situations where this might not be the case, for example, if a patient record is transitioning from paper notes to Medicus and an admin staff member is entering the data on behalf of the clinician. You can edit this information by selecting the 'Change' link. Future action / recall status Once a future action / recall is saved, a status is displayed next to it to let you and other users know the current status of the recall and if any action needs to be undertaken: \n Overdue - the recall is incomplete and is past the due date. \n Due - the recall is incomplete and is within the planned date range (if a custom date range was set) \n Planned - the recall is incomplete and the due date is in the future. \n Completed - the recall has been completed and marked as completed in Medicus. \n Cancelled -  the recall was cancelled in Medicus. \n Viewing future actions / recalls on the care record Once saved, future actions / recalls are visible on the care record from the patient journal and the patient clinical summary page. You can click on the entry on the journal to open up additional details about the future action / recall. You can also retrospectively edit the information from here if you need to. Viewing future actions / recalls for all patients You can view all future actions / recalls for all patients to help manage upcoming actions from across the organisation. This is located within the Patient Administration module which you can access from the left hand side navigation bar. Once you're in the Patient Administration module, select 'Future Actions/Recalls' to be taken to the full list. This list is ordered with the planned date as the latest, but you can reorder or filter the list as desired. Clicking on a particular line item opens up the 'View Future Action/Recall screen'.  The 'More actions' menu includes a number of actions such as cancelling or editing the recall. Completing a future action / recall  Once you've actioned a recall, selecting 'Mark as completed' updates the status to 'completed' in Medicus. Future actions can also be completed automatically when specific codes are added to the patient record. For example, if a patient has an outstanding future action that requires their blood pressure to be recorded as they are on the QOF register for Hypertension. If their blood pressure was taken in an appointment and recorded as an observation, the future action would be resolved automatically."}, {"id": 18071601120669, "title": "Applying a Template to the Staff Schedule", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18071601120669", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article walks through the steps to assign templates to staff members to build out your staff schedule.  Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. Once in the scheduling module, select 'Staff Schedule' on the left hand side navigation bar. Applying a template to the staff schedule When you have created your daily and weekly templates you can add them to the staff schedule and assign them to your team members.  Select the day and staff member that you want to add a template for. Start by clicking into the Monday space for the staff member you want to assign a template to and a pop up will open with options of what you can add to the schedule.  Here you can choose to Apply a schedule template or Apply a week template. \n Select Apply schedule template if you want to assign a single-day template. \n Select Apply week template if you want to assign a full-week template. \n When adding the template you'll be prompted to choose which template you're applying and when you want it to start from.  Click Continue to review and you'll see a preview of the template. From here you can check you have the correct template and then click Apply Template.  You will see that the sessions have been added to the staff schedule.  Copying the schedule forward Once you have added templates for all of your team, you can copy the week forward for multiple weeks. Click Copy schedule forward, then specify the number of weeks you want to extend the schedule for.  When you click Continue to review, Medicus will automatically highlight any staff absences or practice closure periods that occur within the time range you’re extending the schedule to. If a staff absence or closure period overlaps with the dates you’re copying the schedule forward for, Medicus will not create diaries for those times. Staff absence  Practice closure"}, {"id": 31742441155997, "title": "Receiving and Actioning Prescription Requests", "section": "Patient Requests (Online Consultations)", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/31742441155997", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Patients taking repeat medications are able to request more when needed. Medicus enables patients to make a repeat prescription request via: \n \n The patient portal. \n The NHS App. \n A staff member can raise a repeat prescription request from the patient record on behalf of the patient. \n \n This user guide shows you how to manage repeat prescription requests in Medicus. \n Note: Only patients who are registered at the practice will be able to submit prescription requests . \n Routine vs. non-routine requests \n Repeat prescription request tasks will appear on your homepage if assigned to you or can be found in the workflow module, under prescription tasks. \n \n The tasks are split into: \n \n Routine Requests - this includes repeat prescriptions which have issues left, for example a patient is requesting issue 4/6. \n \n Non-Routine Requests -  this would be for any prescription which requires a re-authorisation e.g. a repeat prescription where the patient has already had all issues or a variable repeat. \n \n \n Routine requests \n Each routine prescription request looks like the below screenshot: \n \n Simply review the medication in the task and select 'approve and issue' to proceed. \n If there are more than one medication in the list you can approve or reject individual items. \n Selecting 'reject' on an item will open up a 'reason' box where you'll be prompted to enter a rejection reason before proceeding. \n Note:  the rejection reason will not send to the patient in a communication so you'll need to inform the patient separately. \n \n Routine prescription requests can be reviewed and approved in bulk. \n To do this, select the 'bulk approve' button from the task list. \n \n Non-routine requests \n Non-routine requests cannot be approved in bulk as they require individual review and re-authorisation. \n \n If a non-routine request contains more than one medication, you'll need to review and re-authorise these separately. \n Note:  if a patient requests both a routine and non-routine prescription request, all medications will come through as a non-routine request task (rather than splitting the task) so all medication requests can be reviewed at the same time by the same clinician. \n Selecting 're-authorise' will open up the re-authorise prescription form for you to review and proceed."}, {"id": 17943287237661, "title": "Creating a Staff Schedule Template", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17943287237661", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose Scheduling templates speed up the process of assigning duties to the staff schedule, and allows you to build templates containing diary assignments, breaks and rota activities. Before a template can be applied to a staff member in the staff schedule, you'll need to build a new schedule template. This user guide will show you how to create a new schedule template in Medicus. Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. Building a New Schedule Template Once in the scheduling & appointments module, select 'Templates' from the left-hand side navigation bar and then the 'Schedule Templates' tab. To create a new template, select the 'Add template' button. This will open up a 'New Schedule Template' form. Give your template a name, start time and end time, and select 'Create template'. This will then create a new template for you to start adding activities to. The activities you can add to templates are: \n Appointment diary \n Break \n Other activity \n Note:  Meetings cannot be added to templates. This is because templates can only be applied to one staff member at a time, whereas meetings will typically have multiple attendees. Adding a Diary to the Template To add an appointment diary to the new template, select the 'Add' button to open up a dropdown list, and then select 'Appointment diary'. This will open up the 'Add Diary to Template' form. You can then choose the Appointment service, Appointment Type, whether it is a timed appointment or untimed appointment, the Site location and the Room allocation. You can also set the start and end time of the diary. If this is the first item added to the template, the start time will default to the start time of the template. Otherwise, the start time will default to the end of the item with the latest end time in the template. This is a similar form to the new appointment diary form, but without the need to specify the dates and staff members, as you'll do this when applying the template. Once you've completed the form, either cancel/save, or you can also add other options:   Other template options: Appointment Booking Rules:  Add in another appointment type into the template. Breaks:  Schedule in time for the clinician to take a break. Other activities: Eg. Tutorial or Admin Time. Completing the Template Once you've filled your template with activities from the template start time to end time, your template is complete and ready to be applied to the staff schedule.   Creating a Week Template Once you have created daily clinic templates as needed, you can add these to a week template. Under Templates, select Week Templates and then Add template and give it a name.  For each day that you want to populate, click Add schedule template and select the schedule template(s) you want to add for that day. You can add more than one template to the day (eg. for an AM and PM clinic template) as long as they don't overlap in times.  From here you can preview the template to see the timings for the week. You can also duplicate the template, if for example, you use a similar weekly pattern for another member of staff with only some changes."}, {"id": 18522898064157, "title": "Recording a Procedure", "section": "Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18522898064157", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Any procedures carried out by the organisation should be recorded in Medicus. This user guide shows you how to record a procedure against a patient record. \n Recording a procedure \n There are two ways to record a procedure in Medicus: \n \n From a consultation \n From the care record \n \n Recording a procedure from a consultation \n To record a procedure from a consultation, select 'Procedure' from the 'More actions' menu, or use '/' to select 'Procedure' from the quick action shortcut. \n \n Recording a procedure from the care record \n You can also record a procedure directly from the care record. To do this, select 'Procedure' from the 'Actions' menu from a patient's care record. \n \n Completing the record procedure form \n Selecting to record a procedure opens up the 'Record Procedure' form. \n The 'Procedure' and 'Body site' fields utilise a SNOMED CT search. As you start to type the information, you'll be presented with a list of codes to choose from to enter into these fields. \n \n Finalising the procedure form \n Once you've completed all the required fields on the form, select 'Save'. \n This will save the procedure against the care record which will be visible on the patient journal. \n \n You can click on the entry on the journal to open up additional details about the procedure. You can also retrospectively edit the information from here if you need to."}, {"id": 18519403315997, "title": "Recording Medication or Device Administration", "section": "Consultations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18519403315997", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Certain medications or devices may be administered by a clinician to a patient. This should then be recorded in Medicus against the patient record. This user guide will show you how to record the administration of medication or a device. \n Recording medication or device administration \n There are two ways to record medication or device administration in Medicus: \n \n From a consultation \n From the care record \n   \n \n Recording medication or device administration from a consultation \n To record medication or device administration from a consultation, select 'Drug/device administration' from the 'More actions' menu, or use '/' to select 'Drug/device administration' from the quick action shortcut. \n   \n \n   \n Recording medication or device administration from the care record \n You can also record medication or device administration directly from the care record. To do this, select 'Drug/device administration' from the 'Actions' menu from a patient's care record. \n \n   \n Completing the medication/device administration form \n Selecting Drug/device administration opens up the 'Record Drug/Device Administration' form. \n Medicus uses a coded lookup for the following fields on the form: \n \n Product (dm+d) \n \n Unit of measure (dm+d) \n \n Body site (SNOMED CT) \n \n Route (dm+d) \n \n \n As you begin typing the data, the list of available codes matching the information you've entered will appear that you can select from to populate the form. \n \n   \n Scanning product barcodes \n Instead of searching for a product, you can also select 'Scan product barcode' to scan the 'Data Matrix' barcode on the side of the drug/device packaging. \n Scanning the product barcode will then populate the 'Product Administered' field. Check that this is correct before completing the rest of the form. \n   \n Finalising the medication/device administration form \n Once you've completed all the required fields on the form, select 'Save'. \n This will save the medication/device administration against the care record which will be visible on the patient journal. \n \n   \n You can click on the entry on the journal to open up additional details about the medication/device administration. You can also retrospectively edit the information from here if you need to."}, {"id": 29762148075165, "title": "Website Banner For Online Requests", "section": "Patient Portal and Online requests", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/29762148075165", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Using the Banners You can use the banners below on your practice website like this:   Versions Darkest blue: Darker blue: Please get in touch if you need a high-resolution version or if you would like the wording slightly tweaking."}, {"id": 21622227446429, "title": "Receptionist Cheat Sheet - Booking Appointments", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21622227446429", "roles": ["HCA", "Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Booking an on the Day Appointment \n 1. Find the open slot that you want to book on today's Appointment Book and select 'Book'. \n \n 2. Ask for the patient's name or DOB and search for this in the patient finder. Select the patient you want to book the appointment for. \n \n 3. Check all the details are correct, add an appointment reason and book! You can select 'change' on things like appointment duration if you'd like to book a double appointment. \n \n Booking a Future Appointment \n 1. Select 'Find appointment' from the Appointment Book. \n \n 2. Ask for the patient's name or DOB and search for this in the patient finder. Select the patient you want to book the appointment for. \n \n 3. Ask what type of appointment they would like, and then select the correct appointment service from the list. \n \n 4. Use the available appointments finder to find a day which suits the patient which has available appointments. Select 'next' to toggle to the next week or select 'filters' if you would like to filter by a specific clinician. \n Once you've found a suitable date, select 'view available appointments'. \n \n 5. Select which appointment slot you would like to book on your selected day. \n \n 6. Check all the details are correct, add an appointment reason and book!  You can select 'change' on things like appointment duration if you'd like to book a double appointment."}, {"id": 21620618223389, "title": "Reception Cheat Sheet - Other Tips", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21620618223389", "roles": ["HCA", "Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Arriving a Patient \n 1. Open the patient finder and ask for the patient's name or DOB. \n \n 2. Type this in the search bar. Selecting the patient you'd like to arrive will open the patient record. \n \n 3. Check the appointment time is correct and select 'Click here' from the arrival information banner at the top of the record. \n \n   \n Changing the Appointment Type \n 1. Select the appointment slot that you'd like to change the appointment type for and select 'change appointment type' from the dropdown. \n \n Cancelling or Rescheduling an Appointment \n 1. Select the appointment you want to cancel or change from the Appointment Book. \n \n 2. Select 'more actions' and then either 'cancel or reschedule' from the view appointment screen. \n \n Changing from Face-to-Face to Phone \n 1. Select the appointment you want to cancel or change from the Appointment Book. \n \n 2. Select the pencil icon from the View Appointment Details screen. \n \n 3. Change the delivery mode from the dropdown list and save. \n \n Squeezing a Patient In \n 1. To squeeze a patient in to a full appointment diary, select the three dots on the appointment diary and select 'squeeze patient in'."}, {"id": 21514002588189, "title": "Squeezing a Patient in for an Appointment", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21514002588189", "roles": ["HCA", "Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n There may be an instance where a patient needs to be seen on the day as a priority, but all appointment slots have been filled. Therefore, Medicus allows the possibility to override the system and 'squeeze' the patient in. This user guide will show you how to squeeze a patient in for an appointment. \n Squeezing a patient in \n To squeeze a patient in, select the 3 dots on the appointment diary you would like to squeeze the patient into and select 'Squeeze patient in'. \n \n This will open up the patient finder for you to find and select the patient, before booking them into a time slot. Once booked, you'll notice an 'overlapping appointment' warning badge on the two appointments scheduled for the same time. \n \n Note:  you can only squeeze a patient in between two appointments that are already booked."}, {"id": 18278364207901, "title": "Moving a Patient Appointment", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18278364207901", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n You can easily move an appointment to a different time slot, diary or queue that is later on the same day. This avoids having to reschedule the appointment (where the original appointment is cancelled and a new one is booked), but allows you to simply move an appointment start time to later in the day. This user guide will show you how to move a patient appointment to a later time. \n Note:  you can only move the appointment to a time slot, diary or queue that is on the same day as the original appointment. If you would like to move the appointment to a different day then you will need to reschedule the appointment instead. \n Managing booked appointments Once an appointment is booked, the appointment can be managed from numerous places within Medicus: \n Directly from the appointment book \n From the patient appointments tab \n From the patient clinical summary page \n Clicking on an appointment will open up the 'View Appointment Details' screen on the right hand side of the page. From here, you'll be able to view and manage the appointment. \n Moving an appointment \n Selecting the 'More actions' menu at the bottom of the page offers a number of options to move the appointment: \n \n \n Move appointment -  this option allows you to move the appointment to a later time slot within the same appointment diary. \n \n Move appointment to another diary -  this option allows you to move the appointment to a later time slot within a different appointment diary. \n \n Move appointment to a queue -  this option allows you to move the appointment from an appointment diary to an appointment queue. \n \n Move appointment to diary -  this option allows you to move an appointment from a queue to a time slot in an appointment diary. \n \n \n Once you've selected an option from the above list you'll be taken to a pop-out screen showing you available appointments in a diary or queue. \n \n \n Once you've selected the appointment slot or queue that you'd like to move the patient appointment to, you'll be taken to a confirmation screen. \n Review the current and new appointment details to check they are correct before confirming. \n \n You'll also be prompted to send a booking confirmation to the patient. \n Once you're happy with the new details, select 'Confirm and move' to move the appointment."}, {"id": 18267220102173, "title": "Viewing Previously Cancelled and Rescheduled Appointments", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18267220102173", "roles": ["HCA", "Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n If you'd like to view a list of previously cancelled and rescheduled appointments in Medicus, follow the steps in this user guide. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n This will take you to the Appointment Book. \n Viewing cancelled and rescheduled appointments \n To view a list of previously cancelled or rescheduled appointments, select the 'Actions' menu in the top right hand corner of the page and then choose 'View cancelled appointments'. \n \n This will open up an audit of previously cancelled appointments in Medicus. \n The appointment cancelled most recently will be at the top, but you can sort the columns to amend the order by clicking on the column headers. \n \n Note: As rescheduled appointments, are a cancellation of the original appointment and a rebook of a new appointment, these are included in the table with a 'Rescheduled' status. \n If you'd like to view additional details about a cancelled appointment, select the row with the appointment on to open up the 'View Appointment Details' screen on the right hand side."}, {"id": 18266859195165, "title": "Marking an Appointment as Did Not Attend (DNA)", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18266859195165", "roles": ["HCA", "Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n If a patient does not attend their appointment, Medicus will automatically record them as Did Not Attend (DNA) at the end of the day. However, you can record this manually in the system as well. This user guide will show you how to mark an appointment as DNA. \n Managing booked appointments Once an appointment is booked, the appointment can be managed from numerous places within Medicus: \n Directly from the appointment book \n From the patient appointments tab \n From the patient clinical summary page \n Clicking on an appointment will open up the 'View Appointment Details' screen on the right hand side of the page. From here, you'll be able to view and manage the appointment. \n Marking an appointment as DNA \n To mark an appointment as DNA, select the 'More actions' menu at the bottom of the page, and choose the 'Patient did not attend' option. \n \n Appointments marked as DNA will display an amber DNA status in the appointment book. \n \n Note:  if a patient still hasn't arrived for their appointment, Medicus will automatically record them as DNA after 12 hours."}, {"id": 18266201366557, "title": "Rescheduling an Appointment", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18266201366557", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n The reschedule function allows you to amend the date and time of the appointment. This will cancel the original appointment, and rebook a new one in the system. This user guide will show you how to reschedule an appointment in Medicus. \n Managing booked appointments Once an appointment is booked, the appointment can be managed from numerous places within Medicus: \n Directly from the appointment book \n From the patient appointments tab \n From the patient clinical summary page \n Clicking on an appointment will open up the 'View Appointment Details' screen on the right hand side of the page. From here, you'll be able to view and manage the appointment. \n Rescheduling an appointment \n To reschedule an appointment, select the 'More actions' menu at the bottom of the screen and then the 'Reschedule' option. \n \n This will open up the 'Reschedule Appointment' appointment book that will display free appointment slots. \n You can toggle the date at the top to the day you would like to reschedule the appointment to. \n Select the appointment slot that you'd like to reschedule to. \n \n This will open up the 'Reschedule Appointment' form. \n The appointment details will be pre-populated with the details from the previous appointment, but you can change some of the details if required. \n \n Once you're happy with the appointment details, select 'Book' to finalise the appointment reschedule."}, {"id": 18265470221341, "title": "Cancelling an Appointment", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18265470221341", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n For various reasons, you may need to cancel an appointment. This user guide will show you how to cancel an appointment in Medicus. \n Managing booked appointments Once an appointment is booked, the appointment can be managed from numerous places within Medicus: \n Directly from the appointment book \n From the patient appointments tab \n From the patient clinical summary page \n Clicking on an appointment will open up the 'View Appointment Details' screen on the right hand side of the page. From here, you'll be able to view and manage the appointment. \n Cancelling an appointment \n To cancel an appointment, select the 'More actions' menu at the bottom of the screen and then the 'Cancel appointment' option. \n This will open up the 'Cancel Appointment' form. \n If you'd like to record a cancellation reason, enter this in the optional free text box. \n \n A cancellation message will be sent to the patient via their preferred channel."}, {"id": 18263400753949, "title": "Editing Booked Appointment Details", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18263400753949", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n You are able to edit details of booked appointments in Medicus, other than the start date & time or duration. ( If you need to change these details, you'd need to either reschedule or cancel the appointment and create a new one.) \n This user guide will show you how to edit appointment details of booked appointments in Medicus. \n Managing booked appointments Once an appointment is booked, the appointment can be managed from numerous places within Medicus: \n Directly from the appointment book \n From the patient appointments tab \n From the patient clinical summary page \n Clicking on an appointment will open up the 'View Appointment Details' screen on the right hand side of the page. From here, you'll be able to view and manage the appointment. \n Editing Appointment Details \n To edit details about the appointment, select the pencil icon from the 'View Appointment Details' screen. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Appointment' form.  \n Here you'll be able to update details of the appointment, other than the start date & time or duration. ( If you need to change these details, you'd either need to reschedule or cancel the appointment and create a new one.) \n Once you've updated the appointment details, select 'Save changes'."}, {"id": 18131577053597, "title": "Updating the Appointment Arrival Status", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18131577053597", "roles": ["HCA", "Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Appointments with a 'face-to-face' delivery mode enable you to manually set the appointment arrival status. This user guide will show you how to update the appointment arrival status. \n Quickly Arrive Patients \n From the Appointment Book \n You can arrive a patient in one click from the 'View Appointment Details' slideover. Just select the appointment you want to view from the appointment book and then select 'Click here to mark them as arrived'. \n \n From the Care Record \n If a patient has an appointment today then this will be displayed as a banner on their care record. You can click 'Click here' to arrive them in one click. \n \n Amending the Appointment Status \n To update the appointment arrival status, select the 'More actions' menu and then the 'Set arrival status' option. \n \n You'll be taken to the 'Set Arrival Status' form. \n Select the appointment status you'd like to use and select the 'Mark as' button to update the status. \n \n The arrival status options that are available depend on what the current arrival status is. \n You'll be able to manually change the appointment status to: \n \n Arrived \n Called in \n Remove status \n \n The appointment status will automatically change to Started, Seen, Rescheduled, Late or Did Not Attend based upon the actions taken within Medicus. For example, when a clinician starts a consultation, the status will update to 'Started' or if the appointment date / time is changed, the status will change to 'Rescheduled'. \n If the appointment status is Started, Seen, Rescheduled, Cancelled or Did Not Attend then you'll be unable to manually change the appointment status. \n Viewing the Appointment Status \n Once an appointment has an appointment status assigned, either manually or automatically, this is displayed on the appointment details within the appointment book."}, {"id": 18112034300445, "title": "Booking Patients in for Appointments", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18112034300445", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n There are numerous ways patients can be booked in for an appointment in Medicus. This user guide will take you through each of the different ways you can book patient appointments. \n Ways to book patients in for appointments in Medicus \n Patient appointments can be booked in Medicus: \n \n From the 'Appointment Book' tab from the homepage \n From a patient's care record \n From a consultation \n From a book appointment task \n \n Booking an on the day appointment from the appointment book \n To book an appointment from the Appointment Book, either from the homepage or the scheduling module, select 'Book appointment' from the appointment diary you would like to book a patient into. \n If you are booking into an untimed diary there will be a 'Book untimed appointment' button: \n \n If you are booking into a timed diary,  you'll need to select a specific time slot that you would like to book the patient into: \n \n This will then open up the Patient Finder. Once you've selected the patient you'll be taken to the 'Book Appointment' form. \n Booking a future appointment from the Appointment Book \n If you are booking a future appointment from the appointment book then select 'find appointment' to open up the free appointment finder. \n \n Booking an appointment from the Care Record \n To book a patient appointment from the Care Record, select the 'Actions' dropdown menu from the top right hand corner. Select 'Appointment' to proceed. \n \n This will open up two options: \n \n \n View appointment book - selecting this option will open up the Appointment Book where you can view appointment diaries with available appointments to book the patient into. \n \n Free appointment finder  - selecting this option will take you through the free appointment finder workflow. \n \n Booking an appointment from a consultation \n The option to book a patient appointment during a consultation is found at the bottom of the 'New consultation' form. \n \n This will open up two options: \n \n \n View appointment book - selecting this option will open up the Appointment Book where you can view appointment diaries with available appointments to book the patient into. \n \n Free appointment finder  - selecting this option will take you through the free appointment finder workflow. \n \n You can also create a book appointment task if you don't have time to book a follow up appointment during the consultation. \n Using the free appointment finder \n \n First, select the appointment service that you'd like to book the patient into. \n \n This will open up a list of dates that have available appointments. Select the date that you'd like to book the appointment on. \n \n   \n Available appointments on the date selected are listed, organised by clinician. \n If the diary is an untimed diary, appointment duration which will take place between the start and end time of the diary is shown. \n If the diary is timed then the available appointments are shown as timed appointment slots seen in the screenshot below. \n \n   \n Once you've selected an available appointment, you'll be taken to the 'Book appointment' form. \n Booking the appointment \n All routes to appointment booking take you to the 'New Appointment' form. \n \n Appointment details \n Some of the appointment details have been pre-populated in line with the appointment diary settings. You can override the delivery mode, duration or NHS slot category if required. \n Reason for appointment \n The following fields are optional when booking a patient appointment: \n \n \n Reason for appointment (e.g. cough) - this will be displayed on the booking in the Appointment Book and useful for other staff members to see. \n \n High priority checkbox (untimed appointments only) - if the appointment is marked high priority it is prioritised in the untimed appointment queue. \n \n Additional information - enter any additional information in this free text box that could be useful for other staff members, for example if the patient requires an interpreter. \n \n Redacted from online access checkbox - checking this box will hide the appointment from any patient's viewing appointment information online e.g. NHSapp. \n \n Booking confirmation \n The booking confirmation will default to sending the communication to the patient via their preferred channel for contact. However, you can amend this at the time of booking if you'd like. \n Note: If you choose to redact the appointment from patient online access, then you'll notice the booking confirmation options disappear. This is to prevent any appointment notifications being sent to the patient to mitigate the risk of others seeing the notifications. \n Booking appointments that extend past the appointment diary time \n When booking appointments into slots near the end of the appointment diary, it's possible for you to enter a duration that extends past the end time of the diary. This is to enable scenarios where the diary is full but you'd like to accomodate a later appointment. \n In this case, Medicus will automatically extend the time of the appointment diary. \n Note: If you choose to cancel or reschedule the appointment that extended the diary, the end time of the diary will remain at the extended time. You will need to manually amend this back to the original end time if you want the diary to return to it's original state."}, {"id": 18108165939613, "title": "Booking Patients into Appointment Queues", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18108165939613", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n The purpose of appointment queues is to manage shared lists of patients that need to be seen at some point during a given time period. This user guide will show you how book patients into an appointment queue. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n This will take you to the Appointment Book. \n Booking patients into an appointment queue \n Appointment queues set up will appear on the left hand side of the Appointment Book. \n To book a patient into the queue, select the 'Book appointment' link. \n \n This will open up the Patient Finder tool. \n \n Search for and select the patient you'd like to book into the appointment queue. \n This will open up the 'New Appointment' form. \n \n   \n Appointment details \n Some of the appointment details have been pre-populated in line with the appointment queue settings. You can override the delivery mode, duration or NHS slot category if required. \n Reason for appointment \n The following fields are optional when booking a patient into the queue: \n \n Reason for appointment (e.g. cough) - this will be displayed on the booking in the Appointment Book and useful for other staff members to see. \n High priority checkbox - if the appointment is marked high priority it is prioritised in the appointment queue. \n Additional information - enter any additional information in this free text box that could be useful for other staff members. \n Redact from patient online access checkbox - checking this box will hide the appointment from any patient online services e.g. NHSapp. \n \n Booking confirmation \n The mechanism to send a booking confirmation is the same when booking a patient into a queue as it is for booking a patient appointment. \n Finalising the appointment \n Once you've completed the form select 'Book'. The appointment will be created and will now be visible in the Appointment Book. \n \n If you checked the high priority box, you'll see the appointment is prioritised and is shown above any normal priority appointments."}, {"id": 18096585312285, "title": "Managing Appointment Queues", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18096585312285", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The purpose of appointment queues is to manage shared lists of patients that need to be seen at some point during a given time period. \n This user guide will show you how to: \n \n View appointment queues \n Close appointment queues to new patients \n Edit an appointment queue \n Cancel an appointment queue \n \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n This will take you to the appointment book where you can manage existing appointment queues. \n Viewing appointment queues \n Appointment queues are displayed on the left hand side of the Appointment Book. \n At the top of the appointment queue you'll see the following information: \n \n Appointment service \n Start and end time of the diary \n The delivery mode \n How many appointments are booked and the duration of those appointments added together \n How many appointments have not been seen yet \n \n Appointments are in the queue are ordered by: \n \n High priority - these are identified with a 'high priority' badge \n The time the appointment was created \n \n \n Closing a queue to new patients \n If you'd like to close the queue to new patients, select the three dots to open up a dropdown menu of actions and select 'Close queue to new patients'. \n \n This will close the queue so no new patient appointments can be booked. \n A banner will appear which reads 'Closed to new patients' so other staff members are aware. \n \n If you need to reopen the queue again you can do so via the same mechanism. \n Editing an appointment queue \n To edit an appointment queue, select the three dots to open up the options menu and click 'Edit queue'. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Appointment Queue' form. \n If there are patients already booked into the queue, you'll see the following warning banner: \n \n Cancelling an appointment queue \n To cancel an appointment queue, select the three dots to open up the dropdown menu and choose 'Cancel queue'. \n Note:  the cancellation option will only be shown if there are no patients booked into the queue. \n \n You'll be presented with a pop-out confirmation form asking if you'd like to proceed with the cancellation. \n \n Selecting 'Yes, cancel' will cancel the queue and it will no longer be visible in the Appointment Book."}, {"id": 18094537091997, "title": "Creating an Appointment Queue", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18094537091997", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The purpose of appointment queues is to manage shared lists of patients that need to be seen at some point during a given time period. This user guide will show you how to create an appointment queue in Medicus. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n This will take you to the appointment book view where you can setup an appointment queue. \n  Creating an Appointment Queue \n To create an appointment queue, select the 'Actions' button in the top right hand corner from the Appointment Book and select 'Add new appointment queue'. \n \n This will open up the 'New Appointment Queue' form. \n \n You'll be asked to enter basic details about the appointment queue such as: \n \n Appointment service, duration and delivery mode \n Start and end date / time \n Site - where the physical locations responsible for the queue is \n Default slot category \n \n You can also: \n \n Create the appointment queue on multiple days within the scheduled week \n Copy forward to multiple weeks (a maximum of 52 weeks) \n Set an appointment booking rule - for appointment queues these are limited to when internal booking openings only \n \n Note: GP Connect booking is not an option for appointment queues because GP Connect booking only supports booking appointments into fixed time slots. \n Once you've completed the form, select 'Continue to review'. \n This will bring up the 'Confirm Appointment Queues' screen. \n \n Check everything is correct. Once you're happy and ready to proceed select 'Confirm & create queues'. \n The appointment queues will be created in Medicus and will be visible from within the appointment book, ready to book patients into."}, {"id": 18084772966941, "title": "Appointment Book overview", "section": "Appointment Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18084772966941", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n The appointment book is the organisation-wide view of appointments on a given day to help your administrative team see a general overview of appointment availability and arrival statuses for that day. This user guide will take you through how to view and interpret the appointment book. \n Viewing the appointment book \n The Appointment Book is visible from your Medicus homepage. \n The appointment book displays all staff members who are assigned to an appointment diary that day, as well as any appointment queues that have been set up. \n \n You can search for specific patients in the appointment book or filter by appointment service, site, team and job role if you're searching for a particular patient or appointment. \n If no staff member is assigned then 'unassigned' will be shown instead of the staff name. \n Each appointment book will display the following details: \n \n The appointment service \n The diary start and end time \n The site and room \n How many appointments are booked and the duration of those appointments put together \n How much time is left unallocated \n Any appointment booking rules will be shown \n \n You'll be able to book patients into available slots directly from the appointment book. \n You'll also see any breaks, meetings or other activities in the appointment book. You'll be unable to book patients into appointments during these times as the staff member is busy. \n Untimed and mixed appointment diaries \n Untimed appointments do not show as timed slots in the appointment book as they do not have an assigned start and end time. \n Appointments in an untimed appointment diary are displayed in the order that they are booked. \n In a mixed appointment diary, untimed appointments are displayed below the timed appointment slots. \n Viewing booked appointments \n Booked appointments are shown as cards on the appointment books with the following information: \n \n Patients name (and preferred name) \n Appointment reason (or no reason given if this is not completed) \n Appointment duration \n Delivery mode \n Appointments arrival status \n If the appointment is high priority \n \n Clicking on a booked appointment will open the 'View appointment details' screen on the right hand side. \n \n Staff Usual Site within the Appointment Book \n When you open the appointment book, the 'Site filter' defaults to your usual surgery location if one is set. This helps you quickly view appointments for your main site. \n \n \n You can remove or change the Site filters anytime to see appointments at other locations. \n \n \n This default filter applies only in the appointment book. For booking future appointments, you can select any site as needed. \n \n \n \n To set or update your usual location, go to Modules > Staff & User Management, then select the staff member from the Staff List. \n From here, click on the arrow to the right of the 'Usual location' to open the 'Edit Usual Location' pop-up and select the required location from the drop-down menu. \n High Priority Appointments \n High-priority appointments will be marked with a 'High Priority' badge. In addition, there will be a 'High priority appointments' message shown at the top of the appointment diary. \n \n Appointment Type Colours \n Practices can choose to add colours to help distinguish different appointment types. These colours appear as a vertical line on the left side of the appointment in the booking system. \n \n To add or change the colour of an appointment type, go to Modules > Scheduling & Appointments > Appointment Services. From the list, select the relevant service to open the View Appointment Service pop-up. From there, choose the appointment type you want to edit and click the arrow to the right.  \n \n This opens the 'View Appointment Type' window, from here select the pencil icon to edit and select the required colour from the drop-down menu in the 'Edit Appointment Type' pop-up. Alternatively, you can select a colour when creating the appointment type. \n Slot Reservations \n We allow users to reserve appointment slots that they intend to book so that they don’t get booked while they are providing the patient/appointment details. These are reserved and labelled 'booking in progress' for 5 minutes or until the booking is completed. \n \n These reservations can be manually removed by right-clicking the reserved slot and selecting 'Remove slot reservation '. \n \n Hiding 'Completed' Appointments in the Appointment Book \n Users can choose to hide completed appointments in the appointment book using the \"Hide completed appointments\" filter. When enabled, the system hides: \n \n \n Unbooked slots that have ended \n \n \n Breaks or rota activities that have ended \n \n \n Appointments marked as Seen or Did Not Attend (Appointments marked Cancelled or Rescheduled are always hidden) \n \n \n Diaries at capacity  \n When a diary is at capacity, you'll see a warning message informing you of this."}, {"id": 21038187205149, "title": "Medicus Chat", "section": "Medicus Overview, Navigation & Tasks", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21038187205149", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n The Medicus Chat is an instant messenger tool that supports direct messages and group conversations. The tool can be used to: \n \n Facilitate discussions between clinicians about a patient. \n Facilitate a discussion between one or many staff members. \n Facilitate a discussion between whole teams. \n \n This user guide will show you how to utilise the Medicus Chat functionality. \n Note:  you should not use the Medicus chat for clinically urgent communications. For this, you should use the panic button. \n Overview \n There are two main message types in Medicus chat: \n \n \n Direct message -  a direct message is a one-to-one chat with another staff member. \n \n Conversation -  a conversation around a particular topic which can be archived at a later date. Conversations can also be used to facilitate discussion between a group of people or a team. \n \n The Medicus chat can be found in the left hand side navigation bar. This is where you can start a new direct message or conversation from. \n \n Any unread messages appear on the homepage navigation between your outstanding tasks. \n Depending on the message type, the unread messages will fall under different sections: \n \n Direct messages \n General conversations \n Patient conversations - these are conversations linked to a particular patient \n \n You'll also notice the chat icon has a green circle to indicate there are unread messages. \n \n To start a new message you can either click on the chat icon or use the hotkey Ctrl/cmd + shift + C. \n This will open up the Medicus chat pop out to either search for a staff member to send them a direct message, or start a new conversation. \n \n Direct Messaging \n To start a new direct message, search and select the staff member you'd like to message. \n \n You'll be taken to your conversation with this staff member. Any historical messages will be visible here. \n Type your message and press 'send'. \n \n The message will be visible in your chat and the other staff member will be notified that they have a new direct message. \n \n When you receive a reply, you'll be notified that you have an unread direct messages. Clicking on this will take you to your chat. New messages have a green circle in the top right hand corner. \n \n If you need to edit a message after it has already been sent, you can select 'Edit' to update the content. \n You can also delete previously send messages through the same mechanism. \n Conversations \n Conversations can be accessed in the same way that direct messages are. \n To start a new conversation, select 'New conversation'. \n \n This will take you to the 'New Conversation' form where you'll need to enter a title and select the participants to include. \n You can also add or remove participants in a conversation by selecting 'Click here' at the bottom of the page. \n \n Conversations can then be archived from the actions menu. \n Linking a conversation to a patient \n If you want to have a conversation about a specific patient, you can check the box that says 'The conversation is about a specific patient'. \n \n Selecting 'Choose patient' will bring up the patient finder for you to choose the patient from. \n A link to any conversations about a specific patient can be found in the 'Audit' page on the patient's care record."}, {"id": 20558997075613, "title": "Managing an Individual Task", "section": "Medicus Overview, Navigation & Tasks", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20558997075613", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n Anything which requires a piece of work or an action to be completed should have a task associated to it which is assigned to a staff member or team. There are many tasks types in Medicus. For times where a task doesn't fit into any of the specialist task types you can raise a 'miscellaneous task'. This user guide will take you through the general look and feel of tasks in Medicus, and the common actions you can do from a task. The guide will use a miscellaneous task as an example. \n General layout of a task in Medicus \n All tasks in Medicus adopt a split screen view to avoid you having to navigate away from the task whilst looking for information you might need to complete it.  \n On the left hand side you have the task details, and on the right hand side Medicus shows the patient record. \n \n You can select from the dropdown to view different sections of the patient's care record whilst in the task. \n \n Adding a comment \n Comments are a useful tool when a task requires action from multiple assignees. You can use task comments to enter what action you have taken so far, and request input from others before reassigning. \n \n Changing the task assignee \n Often tasks will need to be actioned by multiple people before completing. Therefore, you can reassign a task to another individual or a team. Prior to changing the task assignee, you can add a comment with what action you've completed, and what you'd like them to do (see 'adding a comment' section above). \n To change the task assignee, select the current assignee from the 'Task 'Details' section. \n \n This will open up the 'Change Task Assignee' box where you can select a new assignee and then 'Change'. \n \n If you're working from a task list, then you'll be taken onto the next task once reassigned. \n The new assignee will now see the task on their tasks or team tasks on their homepage to complete. \n More task actions \n At the bottom of the task under 'more actions' you can either: \n 1. Schedule for later - this is a useful function if a task is not urgent so you'd like to remove the task from your task list for now, and a set a date for it to resurface later, for example the following week. \n When you use Schedule for later, which you can find by clicking More actions on the task, you choose a date when you want the task to reappear in the main list.   Tasks that are scheduled for later won't be displayed by default on the main task list, but you can always turn on the filter for \"Scheduled for later\" to see them.  \n 2. Discard the task - you can discard a task if it is no longer required to be completed. \n \n Completing a task \n Only once all actions associated to the task have been closed, should you complete the task. \n To do this, simply select 'Complete task'. \n \n The task will now be visible under your 'completed' task lists. \n If you complete a task by mistake, or need to reopen a task you can select the 'reopen' button on a completed task."}, {"id": 17215844570013, "title": "Creating a New Prescription", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17215844570013", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n This guide will show you how to create a new prescription for a patient, and will provide guidance to assist you in completing a new prescription form in Medicus. \n Creating a new prescription \n There are two ways to create a new prescription in Medicus: \n \n From a patient's care record. \n From a consultation. \n \n Creating a new prescription from a patient's care record \n To create a new prescription from the care record, select the 'Actions' dropdown menu in the right hand corner of the patient record. Select 'Prescription' from the list. \n \n This will open up the create new prescription form. \n Creating a new prescription from a consultation \n To create a new prescription whilst completing a new consultation form you can either: \n 1. Select 'Prescription' from the 'More actions' dropdown list. \n \n 2. Use / as a shortcut to open up the actions menu and select 'Prescription'. \n \n This will open up the create new prescription form. \n Completing the new prescription form \n The create prescription form is split into two halves: \n \n The left hand side is where will enter required information to issue the prescription \n The right hand side displays information to aid you whilst completing the form, for example any allergies or safety alerts. \n \n The following subsections of this user guide will provide guidance and context on how to complete and submit the new prescription form. \n Product search \n You must enter the product you are prescribing before you can complete the rest of the form. This is so Medicus can then tailor the form as per the prescription selected. \n The product search uses dm+d Primary Care Prescribable Product Search. \n \n Once you select the product you'd like to prescribe from the list, more fields on the form will appear for you to complete. \n Selecting the linked product name under 'Product Information' leads to the BNFC website for that product so you can reference additional information as required. \n \n Checks and alerts \n Once you've chosen the product to prescribe, Medicus will run a series of safety checks against the selected product and the patient's care record to inform you of any alerts. The following checks are performed: \n \n \n Sensitivity checks - if the product being prescribed contains anything that may cause the patient to have a reaction. \n \n Age, sex and condition checks - any contraindications, precautions or warnings directly related to the product and the patient. \n \n Pharmacological equivalence checks - the drug is checked against a list of other drugs the patient is already taking to identify whether duplicate products, ingredients or products in the same therapeutic class are being prescribed. \n \n Interaction checks  - if there are any possible side effects when two medicinal products are concurrently prescribed. \n \n High risk messages  - if the product is considered high risk. \n \n Note:  some medications, such as Methotrexate and Sodium Valproate, have special prescriber warnings to provide additional advice to prescribers. \n Indication \n To link the prescription to an existing problem tied to the patient's record, select from the dropdown list. \n Or, select 'Add new' if the prescription is related to a new problem and you'd like to add it. \n \n To add a new problem, you can search for a new problem code in the box. \n If you'd like to switch back to the dropdown to select an existing problem, select 'Link to existing problem'. \n \n Dosage \n Selecting certain product will amend the dosage suggestions you can choose for the prescription. \n You can also select 'Enter free text' if you don't want to use one of the suggested doses. \n \n Supply \n Under the supply section of the form, the first thing you'll need to choose is the type of prescription. There are 4 types to choose from: \n \n \n Acute -  a one-off prescription, for example, a patient is prescribed a short course of antibiotics for an infection. \n \n \n Repeat - a prescription for multiple issues, for example a 28 day supply each month, but the GP must sign off each repeat prescription request. \n \n \n Variable repeat -  a prescription that is included on the repeat medication list, but are not issued on a regular cadence, for example a patient with mild asthma may only require a new inhaler every few months. \n \n \n Repeat dispensing - multiple issues that are signed off by the prescriber at once and sent to the nominated pharmacy. \n \n \n Selecting 'repeat' or 'repeat dispensing' on the form will add an additional required field of 'number of issues'. You will also need to choose the authorisation method:  Issue until medication review date  or  Fixed Number of Issues. \n A maximum of 12 months supply can be prescribed on a repeat dispensing prescription, and the number of issues is limited to a maximum of 99. \n The unit of measure will be pre-populated depending on what medication you have selected to prescribe. \n If you have selected a pre-defined dosage and entered the expected days supply, the issue quantity will be calculated and populated automatically. \n \n The following prescriber endorsements can be added to prescriptions in Medicus: \n \n ACBS Indicator \n AF \n SLS \n CC \n FS \n \n Contraceptive (CC) and STI (FS) prescriber endorsements are included on the form constantly. However, ACBS, AF and SLS appear conditionally, depending on what medication has been selected. \n The 'additional instructions for dispenser' box is an optional free text box in case the pharmacist should take any additional action or provide advice in relation to the prescribed medication. \n Authorisation \n \n \n Start date - this is pre-populated with today's date but can be manually edited if required. \n \n Review date  (repeat or repeat dispensing only) -  this field is optional, but can be used to indicate if the medication should be reviewed on a specific date. For example, if the you as the prescriber would like to monitor how the patient is getting on in their first few weeks on the medication. \n \n Authorised by practitioner - this is pre-populated based on what user has created the prescription but can be manually edited if required. \n You can also check boxes the hide from patient facing services or third parties if required. \n \n Once you've completed the form, you can either create another prescription or issue now. \n Make sure you check all the information you've entered is correct and taken care to review any allergies, safety alerts and product information displayed on the right hand side of the form before issuing. \n Issuing the Prescription \n Once you've completed the form, select 'Issue now'. There are four ways to issue a prescription in Medicus: \n \n Via EPS \n FP10 form \n Handwritten script \n Private handwritten script \n Private printed script \n \n The 'Issue Medication' form defaults to the EPS method. \n Note:  you must be logged in with your NHS Smartcard to issue a prescription via EPS. \n To amend the method of issuing the prescription, select the pencil icon on the 'Issue Medication' form. \n \n This will open up a 'Change Issue Method' form where you can choose your preferred method. \n \n   \n Review the details of the prescription and once you're happy, select 'Issue' to complete the prescription. \n   \n EPS prescriptions will send to a patient's nominated pharmacy, but you can send the prescription to a one-off pharmacy if requested. \n   \n For EPS prescriptions, a message will be sent by default to the patient to inform them that their prescription has been sent to their nominated pharmacy. You can also add additional text if you need to."}, {"id": 20559816156829, "title": "Actioning Inbound Documents", "section": "Document Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20559816156829", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n Once a document has been processed and matched to a patient, it needs to be actioned and coded before filing against the patient record. This user guide will show you how to review and complete an inbound document task and file the document against a patient's record. \n Documents for Action task \n Task Overview \n The layout of a 'Document for Action' task is similar to other task types in Medicus but the document is surfaced on the left hand side of the page, the task details are to the right. \n You can review the patient banner against the document to check that the document has been matched correctly before moving onto other document actions. \n \n You can find another part of the patient's record if needed by selecting the section of the record from the drop down list. \n \n As per any other task type in Medicus, you can reassign the document task to another individual or team if you've completed what action you needed and it's ready to pass the task onto someone else before the document is filed. \n \n The document details should have been auto-populated whilst the document was processing. Here you can check these have been populated correctly and edit if necessary. \n \n Codes & actions \n In the codes & actions box you can: \n \n Type free text \n Add any clinical coding by typing a \".\" to code \n Complete any required actions by typing a \"/\" to open up the quick actions menu \n \n \n You can double click a code to add any additional free text behind it if you need to. \n \n The quick actions menu is similar to the actions menu found during a patient consultation or the actions menu in the care record. Shown below is an example of raising an appointment request task directly from a document task. \n \n \n Task comments \n Like all other task types in Medicus, you may find it useful to add internal comments outlining what actions you have taken so future assignees can be clear on what's happened and what they need to do. \n \n Adding/linking problems \n Under the  Linked Problems tab, you can link an existing or create a new problem. To do this, select the pencil icon in the top right hand corner.  \n \n To link an existing problem, select one from the drop-down list. You can select multiple problems to link. \n \n   \n To add a new problem, select  Create new problem.  You can then add a new problem code and then  Save Changes. \n \n Redacting documents \n Under the data sharing tab you can either redact the document from patient online access or restrict from sharing the document with third parties. \n \n Filing the document \n Only once all actions have been completed on the task from all assignees should you select 'file document'. \n \n Once the document is filed it is then saved to the patient's health record. \n Note: \n Please note that there is a known issue where Docman is unable to export annotations from documents. Please check Docman for any annotations when viewing documents that have been imported into Medicus. This gap in the data export from Docman is expected to be resolved by OneAdvanced later in 2025."}, {"id": 31174694727581, "title": "How to Hide a Consultation Template", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/31174694727581", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose  Depending on the packages you are subscribed to, you may have similar consultation templates from different subscriptions. You can easily hide specific consultation templates so you only have your chosen consultation templates as available to use.   Hide a consultation template \n Firstly, go to Modules > Subscriptions. \n \n From the Content Package list, select the package you'd like to hide a consultation template from. \n  3. Select the template you'd like to hide from the list. 4. Select Hide from use and then confirm you'd like to hide the consultation template. The template will now no longer be available when choosing a consultation template. Unhide a consultation template To make a consultation available to use again, simply select the consultation template from the list and  select Unhide template. The template will now be available to choose when selecting a consultation template."}, {"id": 20549627726493, "title": "Patient Deregistration", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20549627726493", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n When a patient is registered at a different practice the deregistration process in Medicus ensures that future care responsibilities for the patient are resolved, and the patient's care record is transferred to the new practice. This user guide will take you through the patient deregistration process. \n GP2GP Transfer \n When a patient is registered at a different GP practice, their health record is typically transferred to the new practice by a GP2GP transfer. This should happen automatically once the GP deduction request has been received from NHAIS. The status of the GP2GP transfer can be seen in the patient deregistration task which is created upon receiving a deduction request. \n Patient Deregistration Task \n The patient deregistration tasks exists to ensure that all actions required to fully deduce a patient have been completed. The task is assigned to whomever is assigned as the default task assignee. \n The task will prompt the completion of certain actions such as: \n \n Any open tasks related to this patient \n Any upcoming appointments which need to be cancelled \n Any incomplete recalls or future actions for long term conditions \n Any active repeat dispensing prescriptions \n \n The status of the GP2GP transfer will also be visible. \n \n Resolving the deregistration task \n Patient deregistration tasks should not typically require any manual actions to complete and close the task. \n Once the NHAIS deduction has been received, the GP2GP transfer completed and there are no outstanding actions related to the patient the task auto-resolves in the system. \n The task can also be manually resolved if an NHAIS deduction has been received by selecting 'Mark as completed'. For example, if a GP2GP transfer will not happen because a patient is marked as sensitive in the PDS the task will not auto-resolve and requires the task assignee to complete this. \n Resolving issues during the deregistration process \n Handling failures in outbound GP2GP record transfers \n If there are any issues with the transfer of the patient's health record to the new practice then as an NHS requirement you'll need to print the record and send it to the new GP practice. \n A 'Send Printed Record' task will be created and assigned to the relevant assignee. From here you can print the failed documents, and send them onto the new practice. Once actioned you select 'complete task'. \n If a GP2GP transfer has failed you can attempt to re-send the failed transfer. From the 'Patient Administration' module select 'GP2GP transfers' then 'Outbound transfers'.  \n Once you've located the outbound transfer that failed you can click to open the details, from here click Actions then Resend failed transfer. \n Handling newly received reports or documents \n If there is a scenario where a patient record transfer has already taken place but an inbound report or document is received, for example an investigation report or clinical letter, then you'll see a warning message on the file document or review results tasks. \n You'll need to take appropriate action to share this information with the new practice, for example sending the document in the post. \n Manually requesting a deduction \n In the event of a patient leaving the catchment area of the country, then you can manually request a deduction from the registration tab on their administrative record. \n \n This will open up the 'Request Patient Deduction' where you'll be prompted to enter the reason, date and any additional notes before sending the deduction request. \n \n Note:  A deduction request will also be sent to NHAIS upon recording a patient death. \n   \n Patient de-registrations report \n You can see a report of all patient de-registrations in the last 12 months in the patient de-registration report. You can find this by going to Modules > Patient Registration > Patient Deregistrations."}, {"id": 21550953722269, "title": "Processing Inbound Documents", "section": "Document Management", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21550953722269", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n Inbound documents can be received to the practice either through the post, by email or into the MESH mailbox. Despite the method the document was received, they are still processed in Medicus in the same way. This user guide will take you through how documents are processed in Medicus. \n Scanning documents into Medicus \n Documents received in the post need to be scanned into Medicus. Your practice scanners will be configured in Medicus during implementation. Documents should be scanned into Medicus one by one, which you may choose to do at the start of the day before allowing the documents to start auto-processing in the system. \n Auto-processing of documents \n Once in the system, Medicus will scan the contents of the document and will attempt to match the document to a registered patient and populate some of the document details, such as document type, clinical speciality and authoring organisation and department. \n Initially the document will be in the 'Unmatched Document' task list with a banner displaying that Medicus is currently processing the document. If Medicus successfully matches the document to a patient it will move into the 'Document for Action' folder ready for review, actioning and filing. \n \n Unmatched documents \n If a document is not matched successfully to a patient it will remain in the 'Unmatched Document' task list. \n \n   \n From here you can either manually match the document to a patient ,  mark as awaiting patient registration or  discard the document if it does not require filing. \n \n Note: \n Please note that there is a known issue where Docman is unable to export annotations from documents. Please check Docman for any annotations when viewing documents that have been imported into Medicus. This gap in the data export from Docman is expected to be resolved by OneAdvanced later in 2025."}, {"id": 20588951048989, "title": "Viewing a Patient's Immunisation History", "section": "Vaccinations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20588951048989", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose  This article will guide you through how to access, interpret, and manage a patient's immunisation history. Please note, it does not cover the 'Childhood Immunisation Schedules', which are detailed in a separate article. Navigating the Care Record To view a patient’s immunisation history, open their Care Record and navigate to the Immunisations tab. At a glance, the Immunisation History page displays: \n The type of immunisation (e.g. First MMR (measles, mumps and rubella) vaccination) \n The date the immunisation was given \n The patient's age on the date of immunisation \n Exploring Individual Immunisations Each entry can be selected which opens the 'View Immunisation' tab to see additional information.  Editing Individual Immunisations From the 'View Immunisation' tab, you can view and edit all immunisation details. To make changes, simply click on the pencil icons.  Clicking a pencil icon opens the 'End Point of Care Immunisation' pop-up. All immunisation details can be edited, except for the 'Administration Status' and 'Administering Organisation', which are not editable.  Clicking the pencil icon next to 'Linked Problems' opens the 'Update Linked Problems' form, where you can link multiple active or inactive patient problems to the immunisation result using the dropdown menu. Having made the necessary changes, select 'Save' for this change to be visible within the Patient's Immunisation History tab.  Note: The audit details will show who made each amendment and when it was made. Marking Immunisation entry as incorrect  If an immunisation has been recorded incorrectly (e.g. on the wrong patient's Care Record), you can 'Mark as Incorrect' from within the 'End Point of Care Immunisation'.  Having selected 'Mark as incorrect' you will be prompted to either: \n Mark as incorrect only \n Remove from record \n You must give a reason in order to save this change.  Marking an entry as incorrect will strike it through, but it remains visible in the immunisation record and can be undone. Removing it from the record deletes it from the Immunisation history and Journal.  Exporting immunisation history  You can print or download the patients immunisation history from the bottom of the immunisations tab. This will print or download the full immunisation history.     You can also do this by going to Actions > Print/Export Record where you can choose a timeframe to download the immunisation history for."}, {"id": 20146984454429, "title": "Receiving and Actioning Prescription Requests", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20146984454429", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Dispenser", "Pharmacy Technician", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Patients taking repeat medications are able to request more when needed. Medicus enables patients to make a repeat prescription request via: \n \n The patient portal. \n The NHS App. \n A staff member can raise a repeat prescription request from the patient record on behalf of the patient. \n \n This user guide shows you how to manage repeat prescription requests in Medicus. \n Note: Only patients who are registered at the practice will be able to submit prescription requests . \n Routine vs. non-routine requests \n Repeat prescription request tasks will appear on your homepage if assigned to you or can be found in the workflow module, under prescription tasks. \n \n The tasks are split into: \n \n Routine Requests - this includes repeat prescriptions which have issues left, for example a patient is requesting issue 4/6. \n \n Non-Routine Requests -  this would be for any prescription which requires a re-authorisation e.g. a repeat prescription where the patient has already had all issues or a variable repeat. \n \n \n Routine requests \n Each routine prescription request looks like the below screenshot: \n \n Simply review the medication in the task and select 'approve and issue' to proceed. \n If there are more than one medication in the list you can approve or reject individual items. \n Selecting 'reject' on an item will open up a 'reason' box where you'll be prompted to enter a rejection reason before proceeding. \n Note:  the rejection reason will not send to the patient in a communication so you'll need to inform the patient separately. \n \n Routine prescription requests can be reviewed and approved in bulk. \n To do this, select the 'bulk approve' button from the task list. \n \n Non-routine requests \n Non-routine requests cannot be approved in bulk as they require individual review and re-authorisation. \n \n If a non-routine request contains more than one medication, you'll need to review and re-authorise these separately. \n Note:  if a patient requests both a routine and non-routine prescription request, all medications will come through as a non-routine request task (rather than splitting the task) so all medication requests can be reviewed at the same time by the same clinician. \n Selecting 're-authorise' will open up the re-authorise prescription form for you to review and proceed."}, {"id": 29541933433117, "title": "Referral Letter Tasks", "section": "Referrals", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/29541933433117", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This article will guide you through creating, managing, and completing referral letter tasks in Medicus. It covers where to find these tasks and how to attach the necessary documents/information, and finalising the referral. Overview Referral letter tasks are designed for cases where a referral letter is needed but not completed during a consultation. For clinical safety reasons, we believe that any work like this that requires action should be captured in a task to reduce the risk of forgetting/missing it. Creating Referral Letter Tasks Referral letter tasks are created when you make a referral but don't upload a referral letter or if you save a referral letter in draft, as a reminder to finalise it later. The default assignee for the task will be the person who created the referral but you can choose to send it to another person or team at this stage.    Managing Referral Letter Tasks Viewing your Referral letter tasks When a Referral Letter Task is assigned to you, it will be visible under My Tasks on your homepage as well as in the Referral letter tasks list. Actioning a Referral Letter Task From the Referral letter task, you can: \n Change the date and priority  \n Re-assign the task to another staff member \n Upload referral attachments \n Add comments to the task \n Complete the task / Schedule for later / Discard the task  \n Adding Attachments  \n To add attachments you can: \n \n Drag and drop attachments from your computer into the box \n Browse documents on your local computer \n Add referral templates \n Attach sections from the patient’s record \n \n From the task, click \"Add attachment\". \n This opens a modal where you can choose how you want to add an attachment.  \n You can drag and drop files directly into the 'Attachments' box or select 'Browse from your computer' to choose the relevant file(s). Selecting the 'Use template' button opens the 'Referral Letter Templates (A-Z)' where you can search for the specific service referral letter templates to fill out and attach. Selecting a template will open the form in a split-screen view, with editable fields on the left and a real-time preview on the right. As you enter the required details, the preview will update. Once finished, you can choose to 'Cancel', 'Save & complete later', or 'Save final version'. You can also choose a  Medicus default referral template. These templates can be used for any referral service where you don’t have a more specific template. Click 'Add to referral' when you are happy with this or 'Cancel' to get rid of it. Selecting 'Attach from record' enables you to attach the patient's clinical summary, documents or investigation results. Once you’ve added all relevant attachments, click 'Save' to return to the 'Referral Letter' screen. If you choose 'Cancel' instead, you’ll also be taken back to the same screen without saving any attachments.  Completing a task Completing a task is slightly different for manual referrals and e-Referrals.  For manual referrals the task looks like the one below: If we have an email address linked to the service, the button will show \"Complete task and send via email\". If not, you'll see \"Complete task and print\" instead.  An e-Referral looks like this: To complete an e-Referral you need to select \"Complete task and send to e-RS\"."}, {"id": 30564474943005, "title": "Setting up Surgery Connect for Telephony", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/30564474943005", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This is a step by step guide to outline the process for setting up Surgery Connect as your telephony provider in Medicus and how to make an outbound call or receive inbound call alerts that are automatically matched to patient records. Configuring Surgery Connect as a Telephony Provider To setup Surgery Connect as a telephony provider in Medicus you will first need to navigate to the communication settings within Medicus.  \n From the Modules list, select Communication. \n \n \n Select Telephony on the left hand side. \n \n \n \n Select Link Provider and then enter your Surgery Connect API key (you need to obtain this from X-On) \n \n \n \n Click Save and you will see that Surgery Connect has been configured for telephony. \n 5. The only thing left to do is provide X-On with your \"webhook URL\" which is how Surgery Connect tells Medicus that a new inbound call is coming through and that it needs to find any matching patients for the phone number. \n The webhook URL is displayed if you click on the telephony provider \n \n Making an Outbound Call from Medicus \n You will be able to make an outbound call by clicking on a phone number anywhere in the medical record. \n If you have set up telephony within Medicus, phone numbers will show as clickable, like below. \n You will then see a pop-up asking you to confirm you would like the make a call to the number."}, {"id": 17957186849053, "title": "Fixing Schedule Templates with Data Quality Issues", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17957186849053", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n A schedule template could have data quality issues for a number of reasons, such as: \n \n A diary in the template is tied to an archived appointment service. \n A diary in the template is tied to an archived site or room. \n An item in the template is tied to an archived rota activity. \n \n This user guide will show you how to identify and resolve schedule template data quality issues. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Configuration' from the left hand side navigation bar and then the 'Schedule Templates' tab. \n \n Here you'll see a list of active schedule templates. \n Identifying data quality issues \n If any active templates have data quality issues, a warning message will display next to the template informing you of this. \n \n Click into the schedule template to find out more details. \n A banner for each data quality issue will be displayed at the top of the page informing you of what the data quality issue is, and a link to resolve the issue. \n \n Resolving data quality issues \n To resolve a data quality issue, simply select the 'click here' link on the banner. \n \n This will open up the edit item form, and the field which is causing the data quality issue will be blank and ready for you to resolve. \n \n Once you've selected a new field, select 'Save changes' and the data quality issue is now resolved."}, {"id": 17956724933917, "title": "Archiving a Staff Schedule Template", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17956724933917", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n This user guide will show you how to archive an existing staff schedule template. \n\n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Configuration' from the left hand side navigation bar and then the 'Schedule Templates' tab. \n \n Archiving an existing schedule template \n To archive an existing template, simply select the template that you'd like to archive. \n \n This will open up the template details and schedule. \n Scroll to the bottom and select the 'Archive' button. \n \n This will open out of a pop-up form for you to confirm that you'd like to proceed. Select 'Yes, archive'. \n \n The status of the template will now be set as 'Archived' and you'll no longer be able to apply this template to the staff schedule."}, {"id": 17945277683229, "title": "Editing a Staff Schedule Template", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17945277683229", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n This user guide will show you how to edit existing schedule templates in Medicus. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Configuration' from the left hand side navigation bar and then the 'Schedule Templates' tab. \n \n Editing an existing schedule template \n To edit an existing template, simply select the template that you'd like to edit. \n \n This will open up the template details and schedule. \n Editing the template details \n To edit template details, for example, the name or start / end time, simply select the field you would like to edit. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Template Details' form. \n \n Once you've edited the details you'd like to change, select 'Save changes.' \n Editing items on a template \n To edit an item on a template, select the item you would like to edit. \n This will open up edit item form. The example below is the 'Edit Diary Template' form. \n \n Update the field(s) that you'd like to update and save. \n Removing items on a template \n If you'd like to remove an item from a template, select the 'Remove from template' button on the edit item form. \n \n You'll be presented with a pop out form to confirm you'd like to proceed with this. \n Adding items to an existing template \n If you'd like to add a new item to an existing template, select the 'Add' button to open up the drop down list, then select the new item you'd like to add."}, {"id": 17967150057501, "title": "Bulk Creating an Appointment Diary", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17967150057501", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n To save time, Medicus allows you to create appointment diaries in bulk. This is useful for when multiple staff members need to be assigned to same appointment diary schedules on the same day. This user guide will show you how to bulk create appointment diaries. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Staff Schedule' on the left hand side navigation bar. \n Bulk creating appointment diaries \n From the staff schedule, select the 'Bulk add diaries' button. \n \n This will open up the 'Bulk Add Appointment Diaries' form. The 'Basic Details' and 'Copy Forward' sections of the form are the same as when creating a new standard appointment diary. \n However, the staff and room requirements look slightly differently. \n As you'll be creating diaries in bulk, you'll need to specify how many diaries you'd like to create, and how many staff members are required to be assigned per diary. \n \n Once specified, you can assign the staff member, site and room for each diary. \n Similarly to the standard appointment diary form, the only required field is the site. Room allocation is optional. The staff member can be left blank and assigned at a later date. \n Once you've completed the form you will need to review and check each diary before Medicus creates the diaries. \n Note:  if you assign a staff member to an appointment diary when they are already assigned to other duties, you'll be notified of this via a warning message. \n \n When you get to the last diary, you'll see the 'Confirm and create X diaries' button. \n \n Once you're happy with the appointment diaries and you've confirmed, they will be created in Medicus, ready to book patients into."}, {"id": 17993346858397, "title": "Creating and Managing Other Staff Activities", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17993346858397", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Other activities are used to assign staff members to specific duties or activities that are not directly related to the delivery of appointments. For example, this may be 'Clinical Admin Time' or 'Fridge Checks'. This removes any need to create 'fake appointments' to block the staff member out. This user guide will show you how to create, view, edit and delete other activities from the staff schedule. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Staff Schedule' on the left hand side navigation bar. \n Adding an 'Other activity' to the staff schedule \n To add an other activity, select the date and staff member you'd like to schedule the activity for from the Staff Schedule. \n You'll be presented with a list of activities to choose from. Select other activity from the list. \n \n This will open up the 'Add Other Activity' form for you to complete. \n \n Required fields are: \n \n Staff \n Activity ( Note: this needs to be pre-configured as a rota activity in the scheduling module. Read more about how to configure new rota activities here ). \n \n Start date/time and end date/time \n \n Once you've completed the form, select 'Save.' \n \n The activity will now appear in the staff schedule. \n Viewing an other activity \n To view details about the activity, select the blue block in the staff schedule to open up the 'View Activity' screen on the right hand side. \n \n Editing an other activity \n To edit a break, select the pencil icon in the top right hand corner of the 'View Activity' screen. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Activity' screen. \n \n Edit details of the activity and select 'Save changes'. \n Deleting an other activity \n To delete an activity, select 'Delete' from the 'Edit Activity' screen. \n \n You'll be prompted to confirm you'd like to proceed. \n \n Selecting 'Yes, delete' will remove the activity from the Staff Schedule."}, {"id": 20588935226269, "title": "Recording a Vaccination", "section": "Vaccinations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20588935226269", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose  This article shows you how to record a vaccination for an individual or for a group of patients in Medicus. This covers point of care vaccinations as well as recording vaccinations that were delivered in another care setting (eg. in a school).  Recording an immunisation for an individual patient  There are two routes to record an immunisation for an individual patient in Medicus.  \n From the patient care record \n Within a consultation (from an appointment)  \n Recording an immunisation from the care record  To record an immunisation directly from the patient record go to the ‘Actions' button on the top right of the patient's record and select Immunisation.    \n Recording an immunisation from a consultation (in an appointment)  \n If you're delivering the immunisation in the course of an appointment you can record the immunisation from the consultation. Start typing '/Immunisations' for the option to appear.      Once you have selected the Immunisation action you will see the below window: From here you have three options that will allow you to record an immunisation: \n Record an immunisation defined by patient group - allows you to select from pre defined vaccine cohorts. \n Manually enter a point of care immunisation - allows you to complete the form manually for a point of care immunisation. \n \n Record immunisation history - allows you to record an immunisation administered elsewhere. \n   \n \n Recording an Immunisation from a patient group Selecting the arrow to the right of the 'Patient group' free text box triggers a drop-down menu of patient groups. This list aligns with the national immunisation schedules and guidelines, ensuring that vaccinations are recorded according to the appropriate patient categories.   When you select a patient group from the drop-down, the immunisations available for that Patient group are displayed:   Selecting a routine immunisation will open the ‘Record Point of Care Immunisation’ form. Choosing the appropriate patient group and vaccine will automatically populate those fields on the form. Complete the remaining required fields, then click ‘Record immunisation’ to save Manually entering a Point of Care Immunisation  Selecting ‘Manually enter a point of care immunisation’ directly opens the ‘Record Point of Care Immunisation’ pop-up. From there, complete the form by filling in all required fields, then click ‘Record immunisation’ to save.   Manually recording immunisation history If you need to record an immunisation given to a patient elsewhere, you can choose the 'Record Immunisation History'. This will open a similar form to 'Point of Care Immunisation' where you can record where they had the immunisation and who it was administered by. Once saved, these records will be visible on the patient's journal as well as the 'Immunisations' section.   Batch recording immunisation history You can easily batch record immunisation history for a list of patients from a report. To do so, select the report from the 'Report Builder' list (Modules > Reporting and Data Returns > Report Builder). ( Read more about how to create ad-hoc reports for a list of patient identifiers here ). Then select 'Bulk Actions' > 'Add Immunisation'   This will open up the 'Bulk Add Immunisation' form to record the immunisation given. You be asked to confirm that you are happy to proceed to bulk insert an immunisation for all patients on the list and that you understand the implications of bulk inserting immunisation records."}, {"id": 29541742879389, "title": "Childhood Immunisation Schedules", "section": "Vaccinations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/29541742879389", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose  This page will show you how to view and interpret the Childhood Immunisation Schedule in Medicus. You’ll learn how to quickly identify which vaccines a child or young adult has received, which are outstanding, and how to use this information to support safe, timely, and informed immunisation decisions.   Overview The Childhood Immunisation Schedule in Medicus shows the latest UK vaccine timetable for patients under 25. Since immunisation schedules are updated frequently and differ by country, the schedule is regularly updated to reflect national guideline changes, monitoring official sources to keep it current.   Navigating the Care Record In Medicus, the Childhood Immunisation Schedule is located in the ‘Immunisations’ tab, positioned above the immunisation history within the patient’s Care Record. The schedule is presented as a simple table with seven rows, each representing a specific age or age range aligned to routine UK immunisation milestones. For each row, the following details are shown: \n Date: The recorded date of the immunisation, or ‘Unknown’ if not available. \n Age: The patient’s age at the time of immunisation, with a note if the date is an estimate. \n Immunisation: The vaccine given, if recorded; otherwise, this field is blank. \n The layout provides a clear overview, allowing users to quickly determine if a child is up to date with the recommended schedule. Viewing Individual Immunisations Each row is clickable, opening a detailed view of the corresponding immunisation entry (See example below) Editing Individual Immunisations From the 'View Immunisation' field, you can update the immunisation details by selecting the pencil icons and manually editing the relevant fields, then choosing 'Save changes'. All fields can be edited except for 'Administration Status' and 'Administering organisation'. You can also 'Mark as Incorrect'. Having selected 'Mark as incorrect', you will be prompted to either: \n Mark as incorrect only \n Remove from record \n You must give a reason in order to save this change.  Marking an entry as incorrect will strike it through, but it will remain visible in the immunisation record and can be reversed if needed. Removing an entry, however, permanently deletes it from the record with no trace. To do this, you must tick the box 'I confirm that I would like to remove this entry from the patient's record' before selecting 'Save'. Note: All childhood immunisations can also be viewed within the patient's journal."}, {"id": 16749404503069, "title": "Submitting a Yellow Card in Medicus", "section": "Care Record", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16749404503069", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) collects reports of suspected adverse drug reactions (ADRs) via the Yellow Card Scheme. Yellow Cards can be submitted electronically to the MHRA from Medicus, and are then stored in the care record. This user guide will show you how to create a Yellow Card task, submit a Yellow Card and view previously submitted Yellow Cards in Medicus. \n Creating and actioning a Yellow Card task \n Sometimes you may realise that a Yellow Card needs to be submitted whilst in the middle of other clinical actions. Therefore, you can simply create a Yellow Card task for you or another staff member / team to complete later. \n   \n You can create a Yellow Card task when: \n \n Creating a new allergy from the patient record. \n Discontinuing a medication due to a contraindication or other clinical reason. \n \n   \n Creating a Yellow Card task when adding an allergy \n Whilst creating a new allergy from a patient's care record, you'll see a checkbox to 'Create Yellow Card task'. \n If the new allergy requires a Yellow Card submission to the MHRA but you don't have time to submit a Yellow Card there and then, simply check this box to open up some additional fields to create the task. \n   \n \n   \n You'll be prompted to enter in some details about the task, assign it to a team or staff member and set the priority. \n Once you save the allergy, the task will be created in Medicus ready to be actioned. \n   \n   \n Creating a Yellow Card task when discontinuing a medication \n Whilst discontinuing a medication from a patient's care record, if the reason for the discontinuation is due to a contraindication or another clinical reason, a Yellow Card may need to be created. If it does, you can create a Yellow Card task to avoid having the action this there and then. \n   \n To do this, simply check the 'Create Yellow Card task' checkbox in the form. Note that the option to create a Yellow Card task will only be available if 'Clinical Contraindication' or 'Other clinical reason' is selected as the discontinue reason. \n   \n \n   \n You'll be prompted to enter in some details about the task, assign it to a team or staff member and set the priority. \n Once you complete the discontinuation, the task will be created in Medicus ready to be actioned. \n   \n Completing the Yellow Card form \n Actioning a Yellow Card task, or creating a Yellow Card directly from a patient's care record will open up the Yellow Card form. Some of the form will be automatically populated to help make completing the form more efficient. For example: \n \n Entering a reaction start date will populate the age when the reaction started. \n The height and weight fields are pre-populated using the last recorded height and weight observation if one has been taken within the last twelve months. \n Problems and allergies are pre-populated and are a MHRA requirement for Yellow Card reporting. \n Medications and vaccines recorded within the last three months are pre-populated on the form. \n \n \n Once the form is completed, select the 'Submit to MHRA' button. \n   \n Viewing previously submitted Yellow Cards \n Previously submitted Yellow Cards can be viewed in a patient's administrative record, on the Yellow Cards tab. \n \n   \n Click on the Yellow Card you'd like to view to see more details."}, {"id": 17992067563165, "title": "Creating and Managing Staff Breaks", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17992067563165", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Breaks are used to block out staff members for dedicated break time. This user guide will show you how to create, view, edit and delete breaks within the Staff Schedule. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Staff Schedule' on the left hand side navigation bar. \n Creating a Break \n To create a new break, select the date and staff member you'd like to schedule the meeting for from the Staff Schedule. \n You'll be presented with a list of activities to choose from. Select break from the list. \n \n This will open up the 'Add Break' form for you to complete. \n \n Required fields are: \n \n Staff \n Start date/time and end date/time \n \n Once you've completed the form, select 'Save.' \n \n The break will now appear in the staff schedule. \n Viewing a Break \n To view details about the break, select the blue block in the staff schedule to open up the 'View Break' screen on the right hand side. \n \n Editing a Break \n To edit a break, select the pencil icon in the top right hand corner of the 'View Break' screen. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Break Assignment' screen. \n \n Edit details of the break and select 'Save changes'. \n Deleting a Break \n To delete a break, select 'Delete' from the 'Edit Break Assignment' screen. \n \n You'll be prompted to confirm you'd like to proceed. \n \n Selecting 'Yes, delete' will remove the break from the Staff Schedule."}, {"id": 17985627803165, "title": "Creating and Managing Staff Meetings", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17985627803165", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Meetings are used to block out staff members for a dedicated meeting. This user guide will show you how to create, view, edit and delete meetings in Medicus from the Staff Schedule. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Staff Schedule' on the left hand side navigation bar. \n Creating a Meeting \n To create a new meeting, select the date and staff member you'd like to schedule the meeting for from the Staff Schedule. \n You'll be presented with a list of activities to choose from. Select meeting from the list. \n \n This will open up the 'Add Meeting' form for you to complete. \n \n Required fields are: \n \n Meeting title \n Start date/time and end date/time \n Attendees \n NHS Slot category \n \n Once you've completed the form, select 'Save.' \n \n The meeting will now appear in the staff schedule of the attendees. \n Viewing a Meeting \n To view details of a meeting, simply select the meeting from the Staff Schedule to open up the 'View Meeting' screen on the right hand side. \n \n Editing a Meeting \n To edit a meeting, select the pencil icon from the 'View Meeting' screen. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Staff Meeting' form where you can update any of the fields. \n \n Once you've made changes, select 'Save'. \n Deleting a Meeting \n To delete a meeting, select 'Delete' from the 'Edit Staff Meeting' form."}, {"id": 17967352765469, "title": "Viewing, Editing and Cancelling an Existing Appointment Diary", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17967352765469", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n This user guide will show you how to view, edit and cancel existing appointment diaries in Medicus from the Staff Schedule. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Staff Schedule' on the left hand side navigation bar. \n Viewing an appointment diary \n At a glance, you'll be able to see the appointment service, time, site and how many patients are booked into the diary. \n To view additional details for an appointment diary, simply click on the diary you'd like to view from the staff schedule. \n \n This will open up the 'View Appointment Diary' side screen. \n \n Editing an appointment diary \n To edit an appointment diary, select the pencil icon in the top right corner of the 'View Appointment Diary' screen. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Appointment Diary' form. \n If there are patients booked into the appointment diary, you'll see a warning banner displayed on the form. \n \n Additionally, you'll be unable to edit the appointment diary start or end time if there are patients booked into appointments either before the new start time or after the new end time. \n You'll see the below message informing you to cancel or re-schedule them before completing this action. \n \n Once you've updated the fields you'd like to change, then select 'Save changes' to update the appointment diary. \n Cancelling an appointment diary \n To cancel an appointment diary, scroll to the bottom of the 'Edit Appointment Diary' and select the 'Cancel diary' button. \n \n You'll be presented with a pop-out form to confirm you'd like to proceed with this action. \n \n Once you select 'Yes, cancel' the appointment diary will be cancelled, and you won't be able to book patients into this diary any longer. \n Note:  you will be unable to cancel an appointment diary if there are patient appointments booked into the diary already. You will need to cancel or reschedule these appointments before cancelling the diary. The 'Cancel diary' button will be disabled on the form."}, {"id": 17958681950237, "title": "Creating an Appointment Diary", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17958681950237", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The purpose of appointment diaries is to manage the delivery of a clinical service by a practitioner in a single room for a period of time. Appointments within a diary can either be timed, untimed or a mix of both. This user guide will show you how to create a new appointment diary in Medicus. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Creating an appointment diary \n There are two ways to create a new appointment diary in Medicus: \n \n From the 'Appointment Book', select the 'Actions' button to open up a dropdown menu and then select 'Add new appointment diary'. \n From the 'Staff Schedule', click on the calendar where you would like to appointment diary to be scheduled. You'll be presented with a list of activities, where you can select 'Appointment diary'. \n \n \n This will open up the 'New Appointment Diary' form. If you chose option two of clicking on a day in the staff schedule calendar, this will be pre-populated in the form. \n \n Basic Details \n You'll be required to populate the following fields in order to proceed: \n \n The appointment service the diary is for e.g. GP consultations, blood pressure clinic etc. \n The date, start and end time of the appointment diary. \n Whether the appointments are either timed, untimed or a mix. \n \n If you'd like to create the appointment diary on multiple days over the next week, you can select this from the 'Also create this diary on' dropdown. \n Timed and Untimed Appointments \n An appointment diary can contain timed, untimed or a mix of both appointments. Selecting either timed or untimed appointments will open up additional fields on the form for you to complete. \n Note: An untimed appointment is an appointment that does not have a specified start or end time, only a duration. An untimed portion of an appointment diary may be useful for telephone triage consultations. \n When creating a timed appointments diary, you'll be presented with the following fields to complete: \n \n The site that the appointments will take place at. \n The room that the appointments will take place in (optional). \n \n Default delivery mode e.g. face-to-face, telephone, home visit or video. \n The appointment duration. \n Default NHS slot category (required for GPAD reporting). \n \n \n As you complete the form, you'll see the right hand side of the screen populate with the details you've entered. \n When creating an untimed appointments  diary, you'll be presented with the following fields to complete: \n \n The site that the appointments will take place at. \n The room that the appointments will take place in (optional). \n \n Default delivery mode e.g. face-to-face, telephone, home visit or video. \n The appointment duration. \n Default NHS slot category (required for GPAD reporting). \n Specify when internal booking opens. \n Whether patients can book online, and if this is checked, when the online booking opens. \n \n \n You'll notice the right hand side of the screen doesn't populate with the appointment slots in the same way as it does for timed appointments. This is because untimed appointments don't have a start and end time, so are not presented as timed slots. \n Appointment Booking Rules \n In Medicus, you can override properties of the diary for a specific amount of time. These are called appointment booking rules. \n Examples of some useful appointment booking rules: \n \n \n Default delivery mode override -  this will allow you to change the delivery mode of appointments for a period of time. For example, if you'd like to run a set of telephone appointments in the first part of the diary, followed by in-person appointments for the rest of the time. \n \n Usual appointment duration override - this will allow you to schedule some shorter or longer appointments for a period of time, compared to the usual duration. \n \n NHS National Slot Type category override -  this will allow you to override the NHS slot category override for a period of time. \n \n You can override more than one field within the same appointment booking rule, for example, you could edit both the default delivery mode and the NHS National Slot Type category for those appointments within the same timeframe.  \n Here you can see the right hand side of the screen shows the breakdown of appointments in the diary with a default delivery mode override applied to timed appointments. \n \n Note: It's possible to add more than one appointment booking rule to an appointment diary, however, they must not overlap in start or end time. \n Staff Requirements \n Each appointment diary may have different staff requirements. \n At the point of creating the new appointment diary, you must specify the number of required staff.  \n \n However, it's optional to assign which staff member(s) these are at this point. For example, you may have a service that's run every week but only assign staff members to the diary once the rota is published. \n \n If you choose to leave this blank and assign the staff member later, this will appear in the staff schedule as an unfulfilled requirement. \n The number '1' in the bottom right of the blue box indicates how many staff member are required to be assigned. \n \n When you're ready to assign a staff member, click on the blue box to edit the appointment diary and assign the relevant staff member. \n Note:  if you assign a staff member to the appointment diary when they are already assigned to other duties, you'll be notified of this via a warning message. \n If there are appointment diaries with unfulfilled staff requirements for the following day, then Medicus will create a task for the default assignee to assign staff members in time for the duties. \n Copy Forward \n The final part of the 'New Appointment Diary' form is the copy forward checkbox. \n This allows you to copy diaries forward for a maximum of 52 weeks. \n \n Completing the Appointment Diary \n Once you're happy with your completed form, select 'Continue to review' to be taken to a summary of the diaries that will be scheduled. \n \n Check you're happy before confirming the appointment diaries. The appointment diaries will then be created in Medicus, ready to book patients into."}, {"id": 17696614872733, "title": "Viewing the Staff Schedule", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17696614872733", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The staff schedule page is where you can view and allocate the staff in your practice to all of the different duties to be performed on a given week. This user guide covers how to access and view the staff schedule. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Select 'Staff schedule' from the left hand side navigation bar to be taken to the staff schedule. \n Staff activities \n Staff can be assigned to perform the following activities in Medicus which are then viewable on the staff schedule: \n \n \n Appointment diaries - managing the delivery of an appointment service by a practitioner(s) in a single room for a period of time. \n \n Meetings - blocks out time for staff members to attend internal meetings. \n \n Breaks - blocks out time for staff members for dedicated break time. \n \n Absences - blocks out time for staff members to take time off. \n \n Other activities (rota activities) - assigning staff members to other duties that are not directly related to the delivery of appointments, for example, admin time. \n \n There's no need to create 'fake appointments' for staff members to block time out, as each staff activity should fall into one of the categories available in Medicus. \n For guidance on creating and assigning staff to activities, refer to the specific user guides on the each of the activities outlined above. \n Staff schedule view \n The staff schedule view is designed so you can easily view what duties each staff member is assigned to each day in a given week. \n \n You can also change the view to 'Day view' by selecting the drop down in the top right hand corner as well as filter by specific teams or staff members. \n Drag and drop staff activities to assign to a different staff member \n The drag and drop feature is an easy way to reassign a staff activity to a different member of staff. \n For example, if a staff member is unexpectedly absent and their morning appointment diary is going to be covered by another staff member, you can easily drag and drop the appointment diary onto the covering staff member on the staff schedule view. \n Viewing conflicts in the staff schedule \n If a staff member has conflicting activities, the conflicting events will change to amber and a warning symbol is displayed in the top right hand corner. \n \n This is to catch your attention to ensure any conflicts are resolved."}, {"id": 17658371972381, "title": "Configuring Rota Activities", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17658371972381", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Rota activities are used to assign staff members to specific duties or activities that are not directly related to the delivery of appointments. Clinical admin time is a good example of a rota activity not related to patient appointments. This avoids the need to create 'fake appointments' in the system. \n This user guide will show you how to create new, edit and archive rota activities in Medicus. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Configuration' on the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n Select 'Rota Activities' to navigate to the rota activities tab. \n \n Creating a new rota activity \n To create a new rota activity select the 'New' dropdown button in the top right hand corner and then 'Rota activity'. \n \n This opens up the 'Create Rota Activity' form. \n You'll be prompted to specify an internal name for the rota activity and the NHS Slot Category. This is a requirement for GPAD reporting. \n \n Select 'save' to create the rota activity. \n Editing a rota activity \n To edit an existing rota activity, select the service you'd like to edit from the active activities list. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Rota Activity' form where you can edit the internal name and/or NHS slot category. \n \n Select 'Save changes' when completed. \n Archiving a rota activity \n Rota activities can be archived and unarchived. \n If a rota activity is archived it can no longer be chosen when assigning rota activities to staff members. \n To archive a rota activity, simply select the 'Archive' button from the 'Edit Rota Activity' form. \n \n This will open up a pop-out confirmation form.  \n Note: If you try archive a rota activity that is used on an active template, a warning message will alert you of this on the pop-out form. If you proceed with archiving a rota activity currently used on an active template then the template will flag in the system as requiring an update."}, {"id": 17655530154781, "title": "Configuring Appointment Services", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17655530154781", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n In order to create appointment availability, you must first setup one or many appointment services. The appointment services that you set up should mirror the services that you run in your GP practice and offer on your practice website. Some examples of appointment services are: \n \n GP Consultations \n Asthma Clinic \n Phone Triage \n Minor Surgery \n \n This user guide will show you how to add, view and archive appointment services in Medicus. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Configuration' on the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n You'll be taken to the 'Appointment Services' tab where you can see a list of active and archived services. \n Adding a New Appointment Service \n To add a new appointment service, select the 'New' dropdown button in the top right hand corner and select 'Appointment service'. \n \n This will open up the 'Create Appointment Service' form. Create an internally facing name for the appointment service that's recognisable to your internal teams. \n You can also add a patient facing name that patient's will see when booking appointments online. \n \n Select 'Save' once you've completed the form and the service will now be active, and you'll be able to schedule appointments against this appointment service. \n Editing an Existing Appointment Service \n To edit an existing appointment service, select the service you'd like to edit from the active services list. \n \n This will open up the 'Edit Appointment Service' form where you can edit the internal name and/or patient facing name of the service. \n \n Select 'Save changes' when completed. \n Archiving a Service \n Appointment services can be archived and unarchived. \n To Archive a service, simply select the 'Archive Service' button from the 'Edit Appointment Service' form. \n \n This will open up a pop-out confirmation form.  \n If there's no impact to any existing appointment diaries or queues, you will be informed of this. \n \n Once a service is archived you'll no longer be able to select the appointment service when setting up new appointment availability. \n Note: If you try archive an appointment service that is used on an active template, a warning message will alert you of this on the pop-out form. If you proceed with archiving a service currently used on an active template then the template will flag in the system as requiring an update."}, {"id": 17628860917021, "title": "Managing Sites & Rooms", "section": "Staff Scheduling", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/17628860917021", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n When scheduling staff activities and diaries, you are able to add details about what site, and which room activities will take place in. This user guide will show you how to add and configure sites and rooms in Medicus. \n Navigating to the scheduling module To navigate to the scheduling module, select 'Scheduling & Appointments' from the modules menu on the left-hand side navigation bar. \n Once in the scheduling module, select 'Sites & Rooms' from the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n Managing sites in Medicus \n Often GP practices may have more than one site. These can be added to Medicus and assigned to staff activities and diaries within the schedule. \n Adding a new site \n To add a new site, select the 'New site' button in the top right hand corner. This will open up a pop out form to complete details about the new site. \n \n Once you've completed the form, select 'Save'. \n The site will now be listed in the 'Active Sites' tab and can be assigned against staff scheduling diaries. \n Editing an existing site \n To edit an existing site, simply click on the active site you would like to edit. This will open up additional details about the site. \n Select the field that you would like to edit. \n \n Once updated, save the changes. \n Archiving a site \n To archive a site, select the 'Archive site' button at the bottom of the page. \n \n You'll be prompted to confirm that you'd like to proceed with this action. \n \n Once archived, the site will appear in the 'Archived sites' tab. \n Any rooms that belong to the site are also archived. \n If you archive a site which is used on an active template, you'll see messaging on this on the pop-out confirmation form, prompting you to update the template(s). \n If you proceed with archiving the site before editing the templates the site was active on, then those templates will flag in the system as requiring updates. \n Managing Rooms in Medicus \n Rooms sit within sites, and can be assigned to staff schedule activities and appointment diaries. \n Adding a new room \n To add a new room, click into the site that you'd like to add a room to and select the 'New room' button. \n \n This will open up the 'New room' form where you'll be prompted to enter the room name, and save. \n \n This room will now be visible in Medicus and can be assigned to staff schedule activities and diaries. \n Editing a room \n To edit an existing room, simply select the room you would like to edit, and then the field you would like to edit. \n This will open up a form for you to make any required changes. \n Archiving a room \n To archive a room, select the 'Archive room' button from within the room details page. \n \n This will open out a confirmation to proceed pop-up. \n \n If you archive a room which is used on an active template, you'll see messaging on this on the pop-out confirmation form, prompting you to update the template(s). \n If you proceed with archiving the room before editing the templates the room was active on, then those templates will flag in the system as requiring updates."}, {"id": 29238678681373, "title": "Vaccine Batch Management", "section": "Vaccinations", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/29238678681373", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Other Clinical", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose This user guide will show you everything you need to know about managing vaccine batches in Medicus.  Batch Management Batches are managed in a page in the 'Prescribing & Medicines Management' module called ‘Vaccine Batch Management’. To navigate to this page, select: Modules>Prescribing & Medicines Management>Vaccine Batch Management 'Prescribing & Medicines Management' contains a grid which lists all vaccine batches recorded in Medicus: The grid has the following properties: \n Product \n Batch number \n Expiry date \n Status (e.g. available or unavailable for use) \n Immunisations - Immunisations this batch can be used for (can be multiple) \n Created (Date/time and staff member) \n Adding a Vaccine Batch You can add a new vaccine batch by selecting 'New batch'.   This opens the ‘Add Vaccine Batch’ pop-up. The batch cannot be created until you fill in the required details: \n Product name- select from drop-down menu \n Batch number \n Expiry date \n Immunisations this batch can be used for (you can enter multiple immunisation types) selected from the drop-down menu  \n Once finished, the populated form looks like this.  Scanning the Barcode to Add a New Batch You can also fill out this form by simply using the 'Scan barcode' function to fill in the details automatically. Clicking this opens your camera to scan the barcode so you must enable your camera settings in order to use this function.  Unexpired Vaccine Batches To view an unexpired vaccine batch, click on the batch itself from the 'Vaccine Batch Management' page. Batches that aren't expired are marked as 'Available for use'. Expired Vaccine Batches To view an expired vaccine batch, click on the batch itself from the Vaccine Batch Management page. The availability status of expired batches is simply 'expired'. Editing a Vaccine Batch To edit a vaccine batch you need to click the pencil icon at the top right hand corner within the vaccine batch details. This will open up the 'Edit Vaccine Batch Details' menu. Here you will have the opportunity to change the 'batch number', 'expiry date' or 'immunisations this batch can be used for' sections.  You cannot change the product itself, meaning, if the product is incorrect you will need to delete the batch and restart the process. Marking a Batch as 'Unavailable for Use' To mark a batch as 'unavailable for use' select the 'Mark as unavailable for use' button from within the vaccine batch details. This triggers the 'Mark Batch Unavailable For Use' pop up. You will then be given the option to give a reason for making the batch unavailable (e.g. Batch Recall). Marking a Batch as 'Available for Use' To then return it to being available again, you simply select 'Mark as available for use' from within the vaccine batch details.  This opens up the 'Mark As Available For Use' box. Once you mark the batch as 'available for use' the batch again becomes available and the 'reason marked unavailable' disappears.  Deleting a Vaccine Batch Selecting the 'Delete Batch' button triggers the 'Delete Batch' confirmation dialogue. Once 'yes, delete' is selected the batch is removed from the database and you will not be able to recover it.           ."}, {"id": 16350717902365, "title": "How to setup GOV.UK Notify as your SMS provider", "section": "System Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16350717902365", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n This is a step by step guide to outline the process for setting up GOV.UK Notify as your SMS provider in Medicus. This guide will cover: \n \n How to create a new GOV.UK Notify account \n How to configure your GOV.UK Notify account in Medicus \n How to amend the settings within your GOV.UK Notify account \n \n Setting up a GOV.UK Notify Account \n Medicus has been designed to integrate with GOV.UK Notify to enable patients to receive SMS communications from Medicus as your clinical system provider. \n If your practice does not already have a GOV.UK Notify account, you will need to create one. To do this: \n \n Visit GOV.UK Notify and select ‘create an account’. \n An email address from a public sector organisation is required to sign up (e.g. your GP practice / NHS email). \n Follow the steps to register your practice and set up your account login. \n \n If your practice has an existing GOV.UK Notify account \n If your practice already has a GOV.UK Notify account, simply log into your existing account, and follow the steps below to configure your Notify account within Medicus. \n Configuring GOV.UK Notify in Medicus \n To setup GOV.UK Notify in Medicus you will first need to navigate to the SMS configuration settings within Medicus. You will also require access to your GOV.UK Notify account to retrieve the required API key and Template ID. \n 1. From the ‘Modules’ list, select ‘Communication’ \n 2. From the side navigation bar on the left select ‘Configuration. You will be taken to the following page: \n \n 3. Select SMS to open up the change provider form: \n \n 4. Ensure that ‘GOV.UK Notify’ is selected as the provider \n 5. Next, login to your GOV.UK Notify account. \n 6. To create a new API key for Medicus, navigate to ‘API integration’ and then ‘create an API key’. \n \n 7. Create a new API key in ‘live’ with a naming convention so it’s clear this API key is used for Medicus. \n \n 8. Once created, select ‘copy API key to clipboard’ and add this to the API key credentials section in Medicus. Note: it’s important to copy the API key to clipboard before exiting this page, as you will be unable to go back and retrieve the API key after creation. \n 9. Next, to retrieve the Template ID, navigate to ‘templates’ within GOV.UK Notify and either create a new SMS template or retrieve the Template ID from an existing SMS template. \n \n 10. Select ‘save changes’ in Medicus to complete the setup. \n 11. Medicus will perform validation checks to ensure the API key and Template ID are validated within GOV.UK Notify. If the tests fail, you will see the following messaging within Medicus: \n \n 12. If saved successfully, the updated SMS provider credentials will now be displayed within Medicus. \n Configuring your GOV.UK Notify Account Settings \n You can configure the settings within your your Notify account to ensure the system is working as expected and inline with your practice agreed policies. \n Login to your GOV.UK Notify account and navigate to the “settings” tab, here you can change and manage any settings related to your account. \n \n Managing Text Message Settings \n For example, if your practice does not have systems in place to monitor bi-directional messaging with patients, then it is important to ensure that ‘receive text messages’ within the text message settings is turned off. \n This removes the ability for patients to respond to SMS messages they receive from Medicus, and therefore mitigates the risk of patients sending communications to the practice which are unable to received. \n Ensuring patients are unable to respond to text messages."}, {"id": 18591781362845, "title": "Summary Care Record Configuration", "section": "Data Sharing Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18591781362845", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Management users assigned the correct user permissions have the ability to toggle the view Summary Care Record and send Summary Care Record (SCR) updates settings on/off within Medicus. By default, Medicus will have the SCR updates switched off. The setting will be switched on as part of the implementation process at an agreed date during go-live. This user guide will show you how to locate and edit the SCR configuration settings. \n Navigating to the Data Sharing module \n To navigate to the SCR configuration settings, select 'Data Sharing' from the modules menu from the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n Once in the data sharing module, select 'Configuration' under the Summary Care Record section of the menu. \n \n You'll then be taken to the Summary Care Record configuration page. \n Summary Care Record configuration \n There are two settings you can edit from the Summary Care Record page: \n \n View Summary Care Record - when this is switched on you will be able to view a patient's Summary Care Record in Medicus. \n \n Send Summary Care Record updates - when this is switched on this will allow all GP summary updates to be sent from the practice to a patient's Summary Care Records. \n \n \n View Summary Care Record configuration \n To amend the 'View Summary Care Record' settings, select the 'View Summary Care Record' field. \n \n This will open up the 'View Summary Care Record Setting' pop-out form. \n Select whether you would like to switch this setting on or off and then select 'Save changes'. \n \n Send Summary Care Record updates configuration \n To amend the 'Send SCR updates' setting, select the 'Send SCR updates' field. \n \n This will open up the 'Send SCR Updates Setting' pop-out form. \n Select whether you would like to switch this setting on or off and then select 'Save changes'. \n \n Selecting 'off' will display a checkbox under the information message which allows you to send a bulk update for all patients with the messaging that the practice is no longer contributing to SCR updates."}, {"id": 18731000478877, "title": "Bulk Summary Care Record Updates", "section": "Data Sharing Configuration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18731000478877", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n It's possible to manually complete bulk updates of Summary Care Records (SCR) for all patients registered at the practice. This user guide shows you how to start, view and manage bulk SCR updates. \n Navigating to the Data Sharing module \n To navigate to the Data Sharing module, select 'Data Sharing' from the modules menu in the left hand side navigation menu. \n \n Once in the Data Sharing module, select 'Bulk Updates' under the Summary Care Record section. \n This will take you to the 'Bulk SCR Updates' page which displays a list of all the bulk SCR updates that have been started. \n \n Starting a new bulk update \n Note:  you must be logged in with your Smartcard to complete bulk SCR updates. \n To start a new bulk update select the 'Start bulk update' button. \n \n This will open up the 'Start Bulk SCR Update' pop-out form. You can set a start date and time to run the update from and then select 'Start bulk update'. \n \n This will start the bulk upload and it will be visible as a line item in the 'Bulk SCR Updates' page. \n Viewing details about a bulk update \n Clicking on a line item in the list opens up additional details about the update. \n \n Selecting the 'Summary Care Records' tab lists each patient record in the update queue. \n \n Pausing / resuming bulk updates \n It's possible to pause and resume bulk updates after you've started them. \n To do this, select either the 'pause' or 'resume' button on the 'View Bulk SCR Update Job' page. \n \n Failed uploads \n If any patient records fail within the bulk SCR update they will show as a 'failed'. If there are any failed uploads you'll be able to retry the upload by selecting the 'Retry all failed uploads' button."}, {"id": 21183198713501, "title": "Viewing Practice-Wide Unfulfilled Investigation Request Items", "section": "Reporting", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21183198713501", "roles": ["ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The purpose of the unreconciled investigation requests report is to have a centralised list of all investigation requests that are still awaiting results so they can be followed up accordingly. This user guide will show you how to view and interpret practice-wide unfulfilled investigation request items. \n Viewing the unreconciled investigation requests report \n To navigate to the report, select the 'Investigation Requesting & Results' module from the menu in the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n Next, select 'Unreconciled Investigation Requests' to open up the report. \n \n From here, you can view a list of investigation requests which are still awaiting results. The list is ordered by date requested, which the most recent date first. You can filter the list by a specified date range, requesting practitioner and performing organisation. \n Clicking on a line item will open up additional details about the investigation request."}, {"id": 26650699480477, "title": "How to Configure an Epson ES-580W Scanner", "section": "Document Scanners", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/26650699480477", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose  \n When configuring your practice scanners, you first need to determine whether they support the SFTP (Secure File Transfer Protocol) or WebDAV (HTTPS) network protocol. This user guide provides detailed steps on how to configure an Epson ES-580W scanner, which is an example of a common scanner model which utilises WebDAV (HTTPS). \n Configuration steps \n Step 1 \n First, you need to configure your scanner settings. \n \n On the homepage of the scanner interface, select ‘Settings’. \n Select ‘User Settings’, then select ‘Scan to Network Folder/FTP’. \n Configure the following settings: \n \n \n \n \n \n Settings \n \n \n \n \n Image type \n \n \n Black & White (B&W) \n \n \n \n \n File format \n \n \n PDF (Multi Page) \n \n \n \n \n Resolution \n \n \n 300 dpi \n \n \n \n \n 2-sided \n \n \n 2-sided \n \n \n \n \n Text enhancement \n \n \n On \n \n \n \n \n Skip blank pages \n \n \n On \n \n \n \n \n   \n Step 2 \n Next, you need to create a Contact on your scanner. \n \n On the homepage of the scanner interface, select ‘Network Folder/FTP’. \n Select ‘Contacts’. \n Select the ‘Add Contact’ icon which is to the right of the search bar at the top of the screen. \n \n   \n Step 3 \n Enter the credentials provided in Medicus into the corresponding fields in the contact. \n Note: Do not include spaces when entering the password on the scanner. \n Select ‘OK’ to register the contact. \n   \n Step 4 \n Next, you need to create a Preset on your scanner. \n \n Select ‘Presets’ on the bottom left of the home screen. \n Select one of the ‘+’ icons to add a new preset. \n Select ‘Scan to Network Folder/FTP’. \n Select the name of the contact you created in the previous steps and then select ‘Register’ on the right-hand side of the screen. \n \n   \n Step 5 \n Enter the Medicus credentials and specify the settings for the Preset. \n \n \n \n Credentials \n \n \n Name \n Medicus \n \n \n Quick send setting \n On \n \n \n \n Select ‘OK’ to create your Preset. \n   \n Step 6 \n Finally, add your Preset to the scanner’s home screen. \n \n On the Presets screen, click the arrow next to the name of your newly created preset. Scroll down and select ‘Add or Remove Icon on Home’ and then select ‘Yes’ to confirm this action. \n This preset will now be available as a ‘one touch’ button to send a scanned document to Medicus. You can change the order of the icons on the Home screen in Settings if desired. \n \n Your scanner is now set up - please scan a test document (i.e. a document with no patient identifying information) to ensure that, once scanned, it successfully appears in Medicus for processing. \n   \n Troubleshooting common issues \n \n If you receive an error \"File Name Already In Use\", you may need to ensure the communication mode is set to HTTPS (and not HTTP)."}, {"id": 26683417529501, "title": "Configuring your Practice Scanners", "section": "Document Scanners", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/26683417529501", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n During the implementation of Medicus, we work with a named IT Support contact to configure your practice scanners. This user guide takes you through the steps to configure a scanner in Medicus. \n Navigating to the Workflow module \n Scanner configuration settings are found within the workflow module of Medicus. \n To navigate to the workflow module, select 'Workflow' from the modules menu on the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n Adding a scanner to Medicus \n Once in the workflow module, select 'Workflow Setup' from the bottom of the list on the left hand side navigation bar. \n Then, navigate to the 'Document Scanners' tab. \n \n To add a new scanner, select the 'Add scanner' link. \n You'll be prompted to provide a scanner name for internal reference and to select the network protocol, which will either be SFTP (Secure File Transfer Protocol) or WebDAV (HTTPS). \n \n Depending on the network protocol, you'll be provided with a set of information required to configure your scanner. \n Medicus provides step-by-step guidance on how to configure some specific scanner models: \n \n Epson ES-580W \n Brother ADS-4500W \n \n To configure a different scanner model please consult the manufacturer’s user guidance and enter the credentials provided."}, {"id": 21541456381981, "title": "How to Install the Windows Desktop App as a Local IT Administrator", "section": "Implementation Guides for IT Teams", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/21541456381981", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The Medicus desktop app is required to enable the Panic Button functionality and to enable the integration with your GP Order Comms systems such as tQuest and ICE. This user guide will show you how to install the Windows desktop app as a local IT administrator. \n Installing the Windows desktop app \n The Medicus desktop app is compatible with Windows versions 10 and 11. \n Before installing the Medicus desktop app on a machine for the first time, install the .NET Desktop Runtime 8.0.6 or higher. Download the installer from the following location: \n Download .NET 8.0 (Linux, macOS, and Windows) \n The .NET Desktop Runtime installer requires administrator rights to execute. \n Install the Medicus desktop app using the provided MSIX installer package: \n \n Download the ZIP file: https://england.medicus.health/downloads/Medicus_Desktop_App.zip \n \n Extract Medicus_Desktop_App.zip to a folder on your computer. \n Open the .msix installer file included in the extracted folder to install. \n \n This package installs the desktop app for the currently logged in user only. It is code signed by Medicus Health and administrator rights are not required for installation. \n Once installed the desktop app starts automatically every time the user logs in. It runs in the system tray, displaying the Medicus logo. It has no other immediately accessible user interface, as all functionality is initiated via the Medicus web app. No further configuration is required once installed, as this is carried out automatically when users log in to the Medicus web app. \n The Medicus Desktop App running in the Windows 11 system tray \n If you need to support machines that are shared between users, you must ensure that all users will have access to the app. Safety-critical features in Medicus such as the panic button assume that all logged-in users have the Medicus desktop app running at all times. \n In these situations we recommend that the desktop app is deployed to your machines as a line-of-business app using an endpoint management solution that supports MSIX packages, such as Microsoft Intune. This will allow you to centrally install and update the desktop app for all your users and machines. \n If you are unable to use an endpoint management solution then it is possible to manually install or update the desktop app on a machine using the following steps: \n \n Log in to the machine using an account with administrator privileges. \n Copy the MSIX installer package file to the machine. \n Open Windows PowerShell in “Run as Administrator” mode. \n Enter the following command replacing C:\\Users\\Example\\Downloads with the path of the folder that contains the installer package file: \n \n Add-AppProvisionedPackage -Online -PackagePath \"C:\\Users\\Example\\Downloads\\medicus.msix\" -SkipLicense \n Uninstalling the Windows Desktop App \n If you cannot use an endpoint management solution to uninstall the Medicus desktop app, you can manually uninstall the app on a machine using the uninstallation script included in the ZIP file. \n \n \n Download the ZIP File: https://england.medicus.health/downloads/Medicus_Desktop_App.zip \n \n \n Extract the ZIP File: Extract Medicus_Desktop_App.zip to a folder on your computer. \n \n Log in to the machine using an account with administrator privileges. \n \n Open Windows PowerShell in “Run as Administrator” mode. \n \n Set PowerShell Execution Policy Temporarily (if needed):\n \n To run the uninstallation script, you may need to allow script execution temporarily. Run: \n \n \n \n Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope Process -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -Force \n 6. Navigate to the folder where you extracted the ZIP file. 7.  Run the following command to execute the uninstallation script: \n .\\Uninstall_Medicus_Desktop_App.ps1 \n Note: In some environments, the Medicus entry in the Programs menu may persist after running the uninstall script. If this occurs, reboot the machine to complete the uninstall process."}, {"id": 18362576234653, "title": "GP Appointment Data (GPAD) Reporting", "section": "Reporting", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18362576234653", "roles": ["Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Medicus automatically generates a weekly data extract for the General Practice Appointments Data (GPAD) dashboard for NHS England GP practices. More information on the GPAD dashboard can be found here on the NHSE website. \n This user guide will provide information on GPAD reporting in Medicus and show you how you can review the GPAD data exports. \n Submitting the GPAD report \n Medicus automatically submits the GPAD data every Tuesday, which is sent to NHSE via MESH. There's nothing for the practice to do other than ensure the NHS slot type is recorded correctly. \n Slot types are recorded against appointments, meetings and other rota activities to ensure the GPAD export reports on both patient appointments and work conducted outside of appointments. \n The report will also take into account an Ad Hoc consultations held in Medicus to ensure work undertaken by the GP practice is not underreported. \n Reviewing the GPAD data exports \n Previously generated GPAD reports can be viewed and downloaded from the Reporting module within Medicus. \n From the Modules menu, select 'Reporting'. \n \n Once in the Reporting module, select 'GP Appointment Data (GPAD)' from the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n Here you'll see a list of previously generated reports that you can view and download. \n You can also generate a sample report by select 'Generate example report' in the top right corner. \n This will open up the 'Generate Example Export' form where you can set a data range for your report. \n \n Selecting 'Generate report' will download the example report in .csv format."}, {"id": 18362647425309, "title": "GPAD Exception Reporting", "section": "Reporting", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18362647425309", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n One of the key metrics assessed for GPAD reporting is the percentage of patients who waited two weeks or less for an appointment. However, there are valid reasons why an appointment might exceed the two-week limit. Therefore, you're able to report certain appointments as 'Exception Reported Appointments' in Medicus. These exceptions won't be factored into the reporting, and therefore you won't be unfairly penalised. This user guide will show you how to record an Exception Reported Appointment.. \n Eligible appointment exception reasons \n You're able to record one of the following exception reasons against an eligible appointment: \n \n Patient preferred an appointment on a future date or at a specific time. \n Clinician requested follow-up appointment after providing care or advice. \n Patient preferred an appointment with a specific clinician or practice user. \n Patient preferred appointment in a specific location. \n \n You'll also be able to select more than one reason if required. \n Note:  an appointment is eligible for exception reporting if it is scheduled for more than 14 days after the booking date, and the NHS National Slot Type Category is recorded as a General Consultation Routine, Home Visit, Care Home Visit or Care Related Encounter. \n Recording an exception reason \n Whilst booking an appointment, if the appointment is eligible to record an exception reason for, you'll see a message box informing you of this and allows you to select an exception reason. \n \n Viewing and editing an exception reason \n Once an appointment has been booked, if no exception reason has been selected, the below messaging will be displayed on the appointment details. \n \n Select the pencil icon in the top right hand corner of the 'Details' box to edit the appointment if you'd like to retrospectively add an exception reason. \n If an exception reason is added to an eligible appointment, this can be found under the 'Additional Information' section of the appointment details. \n \n Note:  if an appointment is booked through NHSapp or GP Connect and the appointment is eligible for an exception reason, the exception reason is automatically set to 'Patient preferred an appointment on a future date or specific time'."}, {"id": 20522773605277, "title": "Registering a Patient Without an NHS Number", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/20522773605277", "roles": ["Receptionist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n Not all patients have an NHS number but still need to be registered at the GP practice. This user guide will show you how to register a patient without an NHS number. \n Creating a new registration \n To register a new patient, navigate to the 'Patient Administration' module from the modules menu in the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n You'll then be taken to the patient list. \n To register a new patient, select the 'New registration' button in the top right hand corner of the page. \n \n You'll be taken to a pop-out prompting you to select the registration type. Select a registration type from the list. \n \n Registering without an NHS Number \n You are required to search for a patient on PDS first before being allowed to register a patient without an NHS number. This is to make sure there isn't a record on the PDS for the patient already. \n Note: you must be logged in with your NHS Smartcard to search for a patient on the NHS. \n Once the search yields no results, you'll an option to 'Register without NHS number'. \n \n This will open up the 'Request GMS Permanent Registration' form where you an enter the patient details manually. \n Note:  the acceptance type can only be 'First acceptance' or 'Immigrant'. \n \n Once you've completed the form select 'Complete & send to PCSE'. \n The system will then: \n \n Create the new patient record \n Create the new permanent registration \n Send the NHAIS acceptance message \n Create the complete permanent registration task \n \n However, no PDS link or request for GP2GP transfer will be created. \n The patient will be issued a new NHS number and send it back to the practice once registration acceptance has been approved. \n Note:  until the patient has an NHS number you won't be able to send issue them prescriptions vis EPS for make an NHS e-Referral."}, {"id": 16626072626717, "title": "Viewing the Patient List", "section": "Patient Registration", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/16626072626717", "roles": ["HCA", "ANP", "Nurse", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Receptionist", "Administrator", "Other Clinical"], "body": "Purpose \n The patient list in Medicus provides a simple grid of all patients registered at the practice. This guide will provide instruction on how to access and use the patient list. \n Navigating to the patient list \n To access the patient list, navigate to the 'Patient Administration' module from the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n You'll then be taken to the patient list. \n Patient list format \n By default, the page lists all patients who have an active permanent registration, temporary registration or immediate necessary treatment registration. \n The patient list is sorted A-Z by surname, then first name. \n The columns in the patient list are: \n \n Patient (patient name) \n NHS Number \n Usual GP \n Registration Status \n \n \n Selecting a patient from the list will take you to their care record. \n List filters \n The patient list is able to be filtered by: \n \n Registration status \n Usual GP \n \n By default, inactive patients are filtered out, but you can manually amend this if required. \n When filters are applied, you are able to see how many patients are selected by viewing the 'x patients selected' text."}, {"id": 18561401919517, "title": "The Prescription Audit Report", "section": "Prescribing", "url": "https://medicus-health.zendesk.com/hc/en-gb/articles/18561401919517", "roles": ["ANP", "Paramedic", "Pharmacist", "Administrator"], "body": "Purpose \n The prescriptions audit report displays a list of all prescriptions authorised from Medicus in the last year which your organisation can utilise for various use cases, for example: \n \n Conducting a medications audit on a certain medication given a recent safety alert from MHRA. \n Conduct a medications audit on a certain medication given a recent recall request for that medication. \n \n This user guide will show you how to locate and interpret the prescription audit report in Medicus. \n Navigating to the prescription audit report \n First, select 'Prescribing' from the modules menu from the left hand side navigation bar. \n \n Once in the Prescribing module, select 'Prescription Audit' to be taken to the Prescription Audit Report. \n \n Viewing the prescription audit report \n The report lists all of the prescriptions authorised within the last year, ordered by the most recent start date. \n This can be reordered or filtered by either date or product. \n \n Exporting the prescription audit report \n If you'd prefer to complete your analysis on the data from a CSV file you can export the audit report. \n To export the report into CSV format, select the 'CSV' export link. \n \n You can then access the report from your downloaded files."}];
window.QUIZZES  = {"HCA": [{"question": "When a patient arrives for their appointment, what is the quickest way to mark them as arrived in Medicus?", "options": ["Open the appointment in the Appointment Book and select 'Click here to mark them as arrived'", "Go to the patient record, open the Admin tab and update the status manually", "Send a Medicus Chat message to the clinician to confirm the patient has arrived", "Right-click the appointment slot and select 'Set arrival status'"], "correct": 0, "explanation": "From the View Appointment Details slideover in the Appointment Book you can arrive a patient in one click using 'Click here to mark them as arrived'."}, {"question": "A patient calls to say they cannot attend their appointment. How do you mark it as a DNA (Did Not Attend) in Medicus?", "options": ["Delete the appointment from the diary", "Open the appointment, select 'More actions' and choose 'Did not attend'", "Move the appointment to a future date automatically", "Send the patient a portal message asking them to rebook"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The DNA status is set via 'More actions' within the appointment details. This preserves the appointment record and flags the non-attendance correctly."}, {"question": "Where does the patient banner appear in Medicus, and what key information does it display?", "options": ["It appears only on the homepage and shows today's appointments", "It appears at the top of the patient record and shows name, DOB, NHS number, address and key clinical alerts", "It appears in the task list and shows outstanding actions", "It appears in the search results and shows the patient's GP"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The patient banner is displayed at the top of every patient record screen, giving quick access to demographic details and clinical alerts such as allergies and warnings."}, {"question": "How do you add a new appointment to a clinical diary that is fully booked?", "options": ["You cannot add appointments to a full diary - the patient must call back", "Use the 'Squeeze in' option within the diary to add an extra slot", "Delete an existing appointment to free up space", "Add the appointment to a different clinician's diary without asking them"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus allows you to 'squeeze in' an additional appointment to a fully booked diary slot when clinically necessary, without removing existing bookings."}, {"question": "Where can you record a patient's blood pressure reading in Medicus?", "options": ["Only in a consultation, which must be started by a clinician", "In the patient record under the Observations section, accessible to HCAs", "By sending a task to the GP asking them to record it", "In the Appointments tab under 'Pre-appointment notes'"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "HCAs can record observations such as blood pressure directly in the patient record's Observations section without needing to open a full clinical consultation."}, {"question": "What should you do if you accidentally open the wrong patient's record?", "options": ["Close the browser tab and reopen Medicus", "Close the patient record immediately without making any changes and open the correct patient", "Log out and back in to clear the session", "Document in the notes that the wrong record was opened"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "You should close the incorrect patient record immediately without making any changes. Medicus logs all access to patient records for audit purposes."}, {"question": "A patient has pressed the panic button in a clinical room. Where does this alert appear in Medicus?", "options": ["It sends an email to all staff", "It appears as a prominent alert on the Medicus homepage for all logged-in users", "It only notifies the practice manager", "It sends a text message to the on-call GP"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Medicus panic button triggers a visible alert on the homepage for all currently logged-in users, enabling an immediate response from any available staff member."}, {"question": "How do you search for a patient in Medicus using their NHS number?", "options": ["NHS number search is not available - you must use surname and date of birth", "Enter the NHS number in the patient search bar at the top of the screen", "Go to Reports and run a patient lookup query", "Use the Patient Registration section and browse the list"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The global patient search bar in Medicus accepts NHS numbers, names, and dates of birth, making it the quickest way to locate a specific patient."}, {"question": "When recording a vaccination administered by the HCA in Medicus, which section of the patient record is used?", "options": ["The Prescribing section, as vaccinations are medications", "The Vaccinations section within the patient record", "The Consultation section, requiring a GP to co-sign", "The Documents section, by uploading a paper record"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Vaccinations are recorded directly in the dedicated Vaccinations section of the patient record, allowing HCAs to document immunisations without opening a full consultation."}, {"question": "A patient asks to book a telephone appointment with their regular GP. Where in Medicus do you do this?", "options": ["The patient must request this through the Patient Portal only", "Use the Appointment Book, select the GP's diary, choose a telephone appointment slot and book it", "Telephone appointments cannot be booked in Medicus - use a separate phone system", "Send a task to the GP asking them to call the patient"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Telephone appointments are booked in the same Appointment Book as face-to-face slots. You select the appropriate appointment type (telephone) when booking."}], "ANP": [{"question": "When creating a new consultation in Medicus, what is the first step?", "options": ["Open the patient record and select 'New Consultation' from the Consultations tab", "Send a task to the GP to authorise the consultation", "Open the Appointment Book and right-click the patient's slot", "Navigate to Reports and start a new clinical entry"], "correct": 0, "explanation": "New consultations are initiated directly from the patient record by selecting 'New Consultation' in the Consultations tab, allowing the clinician to document the encounter immediately."}, {"question": "Which authentication method is required before issuing an electronic prescription via EPS in Medicus?", "options": ["Username and password only", "NHS Smartcard (CIS2) authentication", "A phone call to the pharmacy to confirm identity", "Supervisor countersignature in the consultation notes"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "EPS prescriptions must be signed using NHS Smartcard (CIS2) authentication. Without a valid Smartcard session, electronic prescriptions cannot be issued to the NHS Spine."}, {"question": "Where in Medicus do you record a patient's allergy to penicillin?", "options": ["In the consultation notes as free text only", "In the Allergies section of the patient record, which links to clinical warnings", "In the Prescribing section when attempting to prescribe", "By sending a task to the practice administrator"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Allergies are recorded in the dedicated Allergies section of the patient record. This populates clinical warnings and is checked automatically when prescribing."}, {"question": "How do you add a SNOMED CT code to a consultation entry in Medicus?", "options": ["Type the free text and Medicus automatically assigns a SNOMED code", "Use the code search within the consultation to find and select the appropriate SNOMED CT term", "SNOMED coding is done separately by the administrator after the consultation", "SNOMED CT is not used in Medicus - it uses ICD-10 codes"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus includes an integrated SNOMED CT code search within the consultation screen, allowing clinicians to search for and apply the correct clinical term directly."}, {"question": "When creating an NHS e-Referral (e-RS) from Medicus, what information must be included?", "options": ["Only the patient's name and the service required", "Clinical reason for referral, relevant history, and the selected e-RS service and priority", "A scanned letter approved by the GP partner", "The patient's insurance details and consent form"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "e-RS referrals from Medicus require clinical details, the reason for referral, relevant history, and selection of the correct NHS e-RS service and priority level."}, {"question": "Where do you view and action investigation results returned to Medicus?", "options": ["They are emailed to the requesting clinician automatically", "In the Investigations section of the patient record, where results are filed and can be actioned", "In the Reporting module under 'Pending results'", "Results are only visible in the lab system - Medicus does not display them"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Returned investigation results appear in the Investigations section of the patient record. Clinicians can review, action, and add comments before filing them."}, {"question": "How do you issue a fit note (Med 3) in Medicus?", "options": ["Print a blank fit note template from the Documents section", "Use the Fit Note function within the consultation or from the patient record to generate and sign a Med 3", "Fit notes must be handwritten - Medicus does not support electronic fit notes", "Ask the receptionist to generate one from the Admin module"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus includes a Fit Note generator that can be accessed within a consultation or from the patient record, allowing clinicians to create, customise and digitally sign a Med 3."}, {"question": "What is the purpose of the LTC (Long Term Condition) recall function in Medicus?", "options": ["It automatically books appointments for all patients", "It identifies patients due for structured reviews based on their coded conditions and schedules recall actions", "It sends prescriptions to patients without a consultation", "It manages staff annual leave scheduling"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The LTC recall module identifies patients due for condition-specific structured reviews, helping practices manage ongoing care for conditions such as diabetes, hypertension, and asthma."}, {"question": "How do you update a consultation that was created in error with the wrong date?", "options": ["Delete the consultation and create a new one with the correct date", "Use the retrospective consultation feature to create or amend a consultation entry for the correct date", "Add a correction note to the existing consultation without changing the date", "Contact Medicus support to correct the database record"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus supports retrospective consultation entries, allowing clinicians to create or amend consultation records for a past date when documenting care that occurred outside normal workflow."}, {"question": "When requesting a blood test for a patient in Medicus, how is the request transmitted to the laboratory?", "options": ["Print a paper request form and give it to the patient", "The investigation request is sent electronically via the integrated laboratory requesting system", "Email the laboratory directly with the patient details", "Telephone the laboratory and provide the patient's NHS number"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus supports electronic investigation requesting, transmitting test requests directly to the integrated laboratory system. This reduces paper use and speeds up result return."}], "Nurse": [{"question": "When recording a patient's blood pressure in Medicus, which reading fields are required?", "options": ["Systolic only", "Systolic and diastolic readings, plus the date and time of measurement", "Systolic, diastolic, and the patient's weight", "Diastolic only, as the systolic is calculated automatically"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "A complete blood pressure observation in Medicus records systolic and diastolic values along with date and time, ensuring an accurate clinical record for ongoing monitoring."}, {"question": "How do you record that a childhood immunisation has been administered to a patient in Medicus?", "options": ["Add a free-text note in the consultation", "Open the Vaccinations section of the patient record and record the vaccine, batch number, site, and date", "Send a task to the GP to document it on your behalf", "Update the national immunisation register directly - Medicus does not store vaccination records"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Vaccinations are documented in the Vaccinations section, capturing vaccine details, batch number, route, anatomical site, and date. This feeds into the patient's immunisation history."}, {"question": "A patient with diabetes is due their annual review. Where in Medicus do you find the structured review template?", "options": ["In the Documents module under 'Templates'", "In the Consultations section when starting a new consultation - select the relevant LTC template", "Structured review templates are not available in Medicus", "In the Reporting module under 'QOF templates'"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus consultation templates include LTC structured review forms. When creating a new consultation, nurses can select the appropriate disease-specific template to guide the review."}, {"question": "How do you record a wound dressing procedure in a patient's Medicus record?", "options": ["Write a free-text note in the patient banner", "Open a consultation and add the procedure with the appropriate SNOMED CT code and any relevant observations", "Add it to the patient's task list", "Record it in the Practice Administration module"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Procedures including wound care are documented within a consultation entry using SNOMED CT codes to ensure the record is searchable and clinically coded correctly."}, {"question": "Where do you view a patient's complete immunisation history in Medicus?", "options": ["In the Consultation history, by scrolling through all past entries", "In the Vaccinations section of the patient record, which shows all recorded immunisations", "By running a report from the Reporting module", "Immunisation history is only available via NHS Spine lookup"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Vaccinations section of the patient record provides a chronological view of all immunisations recorded in Medicus, including vaccine names, dates, batch numbers, and sites."}, {"question": "A patient's LTC recall is showing as overdue. How do you add a future review action to their record?", "options": ["Set a reminder in your personal diary", "Use the Future Actions feature in the Care Record to schedule a recall action with a due date", "Send a task to the receptionist to book an appointment", "Overdue recalls resolve automatically when the patient books in"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Future Actions in the Care Record allow clinicians to schedule patient-specific recall actions with target dates, supporting proactive management of long-term conditions."}, {"question": "An inbound letter from a hospital clinic has been scanned and uploaded to Medicus. Where do you find it?", "options": ["In the patient's task list", "In the Documents section of the patient record, under inbound documents", "In the Reporting module under 'Received correspondence'", "In the Practice inbox - only administrators can access scanned letters"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Scanned and electronically received documents appear in the Documents section of the patient record, where they can be reviewed, actioned, coded, and filed by clinical staff."}, {"question": "How do you start a new consultation in Medicus for a patient you have just seen for a blood test?", "options": ["Find the patient's appointment and click 'Start consultation' from the appointment view", "Go to the patient record and select 'New Consultation' from the Consultations tab", "Both A and B are valid routes into a new consultation", "Nurses cannot create consultations - only GPs and ANPs can"], "correct": 2, "explanation": "A consultation can be started either from the Appointment Book (via the appointment) or directly from the patient record's Consultations tab - both are valid routes."}, {"question": "When completing a smear test in Medicus, what must be documented alongside the procedure code?", "options": ["Only the date is needed", "The result or adequacy, the sample type, and any relevant clinical observations", "A GP countersignature before saving", "The patient's consent form number from the paper records"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Cervical screening entries in Medicus require documentation of sample type, adequacy/result, and clinical findings alongside the SNOMED code to meet screening programme requirements."}, {"question": "A child is due their 12-month vaccinations. How do you check which vaccines are outstanding in Medicus?", "options": ["Call the child health department for the immunisation schedule", "Review the Vaccinations section - Medicus shows the immunisation schedule and highlights outstanding vaccines based on age and history", "Check the patient's paper Red Book", "Run a QOF report to identify outstanding childhood immunisations"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus displays the childhood immunisation schedule against the patient's recorded vaccination history, clearly highlighting which vaccines are due or overdue based on their age."}], "Paramedic": [{"question": "As an independent prescribing paramedic, which authentication is required to issue an EPS prescription in Medicus?", "options": ["Username and password login only", "NHS Smartcard (CIS2) authentication", "Countersignature from a supervising GP", "A separate prescribing PIN sent by the pharmacy"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "All EPS prescriptions in Medicus, including those issued by independent prescribers such as paramedics, require NHS Smartcard (CIS2) authentication to sign electronically."}, {"question": "Where do you document a patient assessment and clinical findings after a home visit in Medicus?", "options": ["In the Patient Portal so the patient can see the record", "In the Consultations section of the patient record using a retrospective or same-day consultation entry", "In the Task module as a clinical note", "Email the GP surgery with the findings for them to document"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Clinical findings from a home visit are documented as a consultation in the patient record. Medicus supports retrospective consultation entries for care documented after the event."}, {"question": "How do you access a patient's Summary Care Record (SCR) from within Medicus?", "options": ["SCR is not accessible from Medicus - use a separate NHS spine portal", "Via the Care Record section of the patient record, which links to the SCR when CIS2 authentication is active", "By phoning the patient's previous GP practice", "Only the practice manager can access SCR data"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus integrates with NHS Spine to display the Summary Care Record within the patient record. Active CIS2 authentication is required to access SCR data."}, {"question": "A patient discloses a previously unrecorded allergy during assessment. How do you record this in Medicus?", "options": ["Add a free-text warning in the consultation notes only", "Record it in the Allergies section of the patient record so it triggers clinical warnings during prescribing", "Inform the receptionist who will update the record", "Write it in the referral letter and let the hospital record it"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "New allergies must be recorded in the Allergies section of the patient record to ensure the information is flagged as a clinical warning and checked during any future prescribing."}, {"question": "When requesting an urgent investigation for a patient in Medicus, how do you flag it as urgent?", "options": ["Phone the laboratory directly to request urgency", "Select the 'Urgent' priority option when creating the investigation request in Medicus", "Add 'URGENT' in the notes field of a routine request", "Only GPs can mark investigations as urgent"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus includes a priority selection when creating investigation requests, allowing clinicians to flag requests as urgent, which is transmitted to the laboratory as part of the electronic request."}, {"question": "How do you record medication you have administered to a patient during an emergency in Medicus?", "options": ["Record it as a new prescription in the Prescribing section", "Document it within the consultation using the Medication Administration or Procedure fields with appropriate SNOMED coding", "Email the GP to update the medication list", "Administered medications are not recorded in Medicus - use a paper patient report form"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medications administered (as opposed to prescribed) are documented within the consultation record using appropriate SNOMED CT codes, keeping an accurate account of clinical interventions."}, {"question": "Where in Medicus do you find a patient's current medication list?", "options": ["Only in the most recent consultation note", "In the Prescribing or Medications section of the patient record, showing active and repeat medications", "In the Patient Portal - visible to patients but not clinicians in this view", "By running a monthly prescribing report"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Prescribing/Medications section of the patient record displays active and repeat medications, providing an up-to-date overview for any clinician reviewing the patient."}, {"question": "You need to refer a patient to the acute medical unit following assessment. How is a referral created in Medicus?", "options": ["Phone the hospital directly - Medicus does not support referrals", "Use the Referrals section or e-RS integration within Medicus to create a clinical referral with supporting information", "Ask the GP to create the referral on your behalf", "Create a task for the administrator to arrange the referral"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus supports referral creation directly, including NHS e-RS integration. Paramedics with appropriate access can create referrals containing clinical information from the assessment."}, {"question": "How do you view the clinical history and past consultations for a patient you have not seen before?", "options": ["Request a printed summary from reception", "Open the patient record and review the Consultations tab which shows all past consultation entries", "Access is restricted to the patient's registered GP only", "Past consultations are only available if the patient has been seen in the last 12 months"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Consultations tab in the patient record provides a full chronological history of all consultations recorded in Medicus, accessible to any authorised clinical user."}, {"question": "After completing a home visit consultation in Medicus, what is the correct way to ensure the record is saved and available to the wider team?", "options": ["Close the browser - Medicus auto-saves everything", "Finalise and save the consultation record; it then becomes visible to all authorised users in real time", "Email the completed note to the practice inbox", "The record is only saved after a GP reviews and countersigns it"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Once a consultation is saved/finalised in Medicus, it is immediately accessible to all authorised team members, supporting continuity of care and real-time record keeping."}], "Pharmacist": [{"question": "When creating a new prescription in Medicus, which drug dictionary is used to select medications?", "options": ["BNF printed reference only", "The dm+d (Dictionary of Medicines and Devices) integrated within Medicus", "A custom practice formulary that must be built from scratch", "Free-text entry only - no drug dictionary is integrated"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus uses the dm+d (Dictionary of Medicines and Devices) for prescribing, ensuring all medications are selected from an approved NHS drug dataset linked to EPS."}, {"question": "A patient submits a repeat prescription request via the Patient Portal. Where does this appear for the pharmacist to action?", "options": ["In the pharmacist's personal email inbox", "In the Prescription Requests queue within Medicus, where it can be reviewed and approved or rejected", "Directly in the Prescribing section of the patient record without any action needed", "In the Task module as an unassigned task"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Repeat prescription requests submitted online appear in the Prescription Requests queue, allowing the pharmacist to review clinical appropriateness before approving or rejecting."}, {"question": "What is the difference between a routine and a non-routine prescription request in Medicus?", "options": ["There is no difference - both are processed identically", "Routine requests follow the standard approval workflow; non-routine requests require additional clinical review or override", "Non-routine requests are for controlled drugs only", "Routine requests can only be approved by a GP; non-routine requests can be approved by a pharmacist"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Routine requests follow the standard repeat prescribing workflow. Non-routine requests are flagged for additional clinical review, for example when a medication is outside the usual prescribing interval or requires specific authorisation."}, {"question": "When reviewing a patient's medication regimen in Medicus, where do you find a complete view of their active medications including dose and frequency?", "options": ["In the last consultation note only", "In the Prescribing/Medication Regimen section of the patient record", "By running a monthly prescribing audit report", "In the Patient Portal - only patients can view their full medication list"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Medication Regimen section of the patient record shows all active prescriptions with dose, frequency, and quantity, giving pharmacists a complete view for medication review."}, {"question": "Before issuing an EPS prescription in Medicus, what does the system automatically check against the patient's allergy record?", "options": ["Nothing - allergy checking is a manual responsibility", "The prescribed medication is cross-checked against the patient's recorded allergies and a warning is displayed if a conflict exists", "Only controlled drugs are checked against allergy records", "Allergy checking only occurs if the pharmacist manually runs the check"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus automatically cross-references prescribed medications against the patient's allergy record during prescribing. A clinical warning is displayed if a potential allergy conflict is detected."}, {"question": "How do you report a suspected adverse drug reaction to the MHRA via the Yellow Card scheme from within Medicus?", "options": ["Post a paper Yellow Card form to the MHRA", "Use the Yellow Card reporting link available within Medicus to submit the report electronically to the MHRA", "Email the MHRA directly with the patient details", "Adverse drug reactions are reported by the dispensing pharmacy only, not the prescriber"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus provides access to the MHRA Yellow Card reporting system. Pharmacists can initiate an electronic Yellow Card report for suspected adverse drug reactions directly from the system."}, {"question": "What does the Prescription Audit Report in Medicus allow a pharmacist to review?", "options": ["Staff timesheets and prescription workload per clinician", "Prescribing patterns, volumes, and individual prescription history to support clinical governance and audit", "Only the cost of prescriptions issued in the previous month", "Controlled drug registers only"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Prescription Audit Report enables pharmacists to review prescribing patterns, volumes, and clinical appropriateness across the practice or for individual prescribers, supporting governance and PDSA cycles."}, {"question": "A patient asks for their prescriptions to be sent to a different pharmacy. How is a pharmacy nomination changed in Medicus?", "options": ["The patient must change their nomination directly via the NHS App", "Update the patient's pharmacy nomination in their record within Medicus, which updates the EPS nomination on the NHS Spine", "Phone the old pharmacy and ask them to transfer the nomination", "Pharmacy nominations cannot be changed in Medicus - GP must do this"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Pharmacy nominations can be updated directly in the patient record in Medicus. This change is transmitted to the NHS Spine EPS system, redirecting future electronic prescriptions to the new pharmacy."}, {"question": "When co-authorising a medication that has been initiated by a GP, what does the pharmacist need to verify before approving the repeat?", "options": ["Only that the patient's address is correct", "Clinical appropriateness including dose, indication, monitoring requirements, and allergy status", "That the prescription has been printed and signed on paper", "That the pharmacy has stock of the medication"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Pharmacist co-authorisation in Medicus involves reviewing clinical appropriateness: correct dose, clear indication, up-to-date monitoring, and absence of contraindications or allergy conflicts."}, {"question": "Where in Medicus do you view a patient's SCR (Summary Care Record) to check medications from other prescribers?", "options": ["Via the NHS spine portal in a separate browser window", "Within the patient record via the Care Record or SCR link, accessible with active CIS2 authentication", "By phoning NHS Digital directly", "SCR data is not available in Medicus"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus integrates with NHS Spine to surface SCR data within the patient record. CIS2 Smartcard authentication is required to access this information."}], "Dispenser": [{"question": "Where do routine prescription requests appear for dispensers to process in Medicus?", "options": ["In the dispenser's personal task list", "In the Prescription Requests queue, where requests can be reviewed and approved in order", "Directly on the patient's medication list without any queue", "In the Reporting module under 'Pending prescriptions'"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "All prescription requests, whether submitted online or at the counter, appear in the Prescription Requests queue. Dispensers work through this queue to process and approve routine requests."}, {"question": "How do you bulk approve a batch of routine repeat prescription requests in Medicus?", "options": ["Routine requests cannot be bulk approved - each must be individually reviewed", "Select multiple requests in the Prescription Requests queue and use the bulk approve function", "Ask the pharmacist to run an overnight batch approval process", "Export the requests to a spreadsheet and re-import after checking"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus allows dispensers to select multiple routine repeat requests and approve them in bulk, improving efficiency for standard repeat medication processing."}, {"question": "How is an FP34D dispensing claim submitted via Medicus?", "options": ["By posting paper FP34D forms to NHS BSA monthly", "Through the FP34D PPA Claims function in Medicus, which compiles and submits the claim electronically", "By emailing a spreadsheet of dispensed items to NHS Prescription Services", "FP34D claims are not supported in Medicus - a separate dispensing system is required"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus supports electronic submission of FP34D PPA dispensing claims through its integrated claims function, removing the need for paper-based monthly submissions to NHS BSA."}, {"question": "A patient requests an over-the-counter item from the dispensary. How is this recorded in Medicus?", "options": ["It is not recorded - OTC sales are cash only with no Medicus record", "Using the Over-the-Counter medication recording feature, which logs the sale against the patient's record", "By creating a new consultation for the patient", "By sending a task to the pharmacist to document it"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus supports recording of over-the-counter medication sales against patient records, providing a complete medication history that includes OTC items dispensed by the practice dispensary."}, {"question": "Before dispensing a prescription, you notice the patient has a recorded allergy to a component of the medication. What does Medicus display?", "options": ["Nothing - allergy checking is not linked to dispensing workflows", "A clinical warning alert highlighting the allergy conflict", "The prescription is automatically cancelled", "An email is sent to the prescriber automatically"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus displays a clinical warning when a dispensed item conflicts with a recorded allergy. The dispenser must review and escalate to the prescriber before dispensing."}, {"question": "A patient's pharmacy nomination is currently set to an external pharmacy but they want prescriptions dispensed in-house. How do you change this?", "options": ["Phone the external pharmacy and ask them to release the nomination", "Update the pharmacy nomination in the patient record within Medicus to the practice dispensary", "Ask the patient to change it via the NHS App only", "Nominations cannot be changed once set"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Pharmacy nominations are managed within the patient record in Medicus. Updating the nomination changes it on the NHS Spine EPS system, routing future prescriptions to the practice dispensary."}, {"question": "When reviewing a patient's medication regimen before dispensing, what key information should you check?", "options": ["Only the medication name", "Medication name, dose, frequency, quantity, and any special instructions or allergy flags", "Only whether the prescription has been electronically signed", "The patient's appointment history"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Before dispensing, the complete medication details - name, dose, frequency, quantity, and instructions - should be verified, alongside allergy flags to ensure safe dispensing."}, {"question": "What is the correct process for recording a prescription that has been dispensed and collected by the patient in Medicus?", "options": ["Mark the prescription as dispensed in the Prescription Requests section once the patient has collected", "No action needed - collection is recorded automatically", "Email the prescribing GP to confirm collection", "Add a note in the patient's task list"], "correct": 0, "explanation": "Once a patient collects their dispensed medication, the dispenser marks the prescription as dispensed in the relevant section of Medicus, completing the dispensing audit trail."}, {"question": "During the FP34D claims process, what items need to be included to ensure the claim is accurate?", "options": ["Only prescription items dispensed to patients over 65", "All dispensed prescription items for the claim period, including quantity, drug name, and endorsements", "Only expensive medications above a certain cost threshold", "Only items dispensed on paper FP10 prescriptions"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "FP34D claims must include all dispensed prescription items for the period, with correct drug names, quantities, and any endorsements required by NHS Prescription Services for accurate reimbursement."}, {"question": "How do you find a patient's prescription history in Medicus to check what has been dispensed previously?", "options": ["Run a practice-wide dispensing report from the Reporting module", "Open the patient record and review the Prescribing section, which shows the history of issued and dispensed prescriptions", "Contact NHS Prescription Services for the dispensing history", "Dispensing history is not stored in Medicus"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Prescribing section of the patient record in Medicus holds a history of all prescriptions issued and dispensed, allowing dispensers to review previous dispensing activity."}], "Pharmacy Technician": [{"question": "Where do you find repeat prescription requests submitted by patients online in Medicus?", "options": ["In the patient record under the Consultations tab", "In the Prescription Requests queue, accessible from the main navigation", "In the Administrator's inbox only", "In the Patient Portal admin panel"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Online and in-person repeat prescription requests are consolidated in the Prescription Requests queue in Medicus, from which pharmacy technicians can review and process them."}, {"question": "What is the process for re-authorising a repeat medication that has run out of issues in Medicus?", "options": ["Delete the old medication and create a new prescription from scratch", "Use the re-authorisation function in the Prescribing section to request or apply an extension of the repeat authorisation", "Ask the patient to book an appointment with the GP before any action is taken", "Re-authorisation is not available in Medicus - each expired repeat must be rewritten"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus includes a re-authorisation workflow for repeat medications that have exhausted their issued quantity, allowing pharmacy technicians to flag or process renewals within the system."}, {"question": "When checking a patient's medication regimen for a structured medication review, where is this information found in Medicus?", "options": ["In the Consultations tab, by reading through all past notes", "In the Prescribing/Medication Regimen section showing all active, repeat, and acute medications", "In the Reporting module under 'Patient Medication Summary'", "Via the Patient Portal only - patients manage their own medication lists"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Medication Regimen section provides a complete view of a patient's active prescriptions, including dose, frequency, and authorisation status, essential for structured medication reviews."}, {"question": "How does a pharmacy technician record an over-the-counter sale in Medicus?", "options": ["OTC items are never recorded in Medicus", "Using the dedicated OTC recording function which logs the item against the patient's record", "By writing a consultation note", "By adding it to the patient's repeat medication list"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus includes OTC recording functionality, allowing practice dispensaries to log over-the-counter sales against patient records for a complete medication history."}, {"question": "How do you identify which items need to be included in the monthly FP34D PPA dispensing claim?", "options": ["By manually reviewing all prescriptions issued in the month", "Using the FP34D claims function in Medicus which collates all eligible dispensed items for the claim period", "By exporting a report from the Reporting module and manually checking each line", "NHS BSA sends a reminder list of items to include each month"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The FP34D claims function in Medicus automatically collates dispensed prescription items for the relevant claim period, reducing the risk of items being missed from the submission."}, {"question": "A patient's pharmacy nomination needs updating to a different pharmacy. Where in Medicus is this done?", "options": ["Only the patient can change their own nomination via the NHS App", "In the patient record, within the relevant prescribing or demographic section, which updates the nomination on the NHS Spine", "By phoning NHS BSA to request the change", "Pharmacy nominations are set at registration and cannot be changed"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Pharmacy nominations are updated in the patient record in Medicus. Changes are transmitted to the NHS Spine EPS system, re-routing future electronic prescriptions accordingly."}, {"question": "What action should a pharmacy technician take if a prescription request is flagged for clinical review before approval?", "options": ["Approve the request and add a note for the pharmacist to check later", "Leave the request in the queue and escalate to the pharmacist or prescriber for clinical review before processing", "Reject the request and ask the patient to book a GP appointment", "Contact the patient directly to ask about their symptoms"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Requests flagged for clinical review must be escalated to a pharmacist or prescriber. Pharmacy technicians should not approve clinically flagged requests without appropriate clinical sign-off."}, {"question": "When processing a prescription request for a controlled drug, what additional consideration applies in Medicus?", "options": ["Controlled drugs are processed identically to standard prescriptions", "Controlled drug prescriptions require prescriber authorisation and are subject to additional legal requirements that Medicus supports through its controlled drug workflows", "Pharmacy technicians cannot process any controlled drug requests", "Controlled drug requests are submitted via a separate system outside Medicus"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Controlled drug prescriptions are subject to additional legal requirements. Medicus incorporates specific controlled drug workflows, and prescriber sign-off is required before a CD prescription can be issued."}, {"question": "The Prescription Audit Report in Medicus can be used by pharmacy technicians for which purpose?", "options": ["To track staff attendance and workload", "To review prescribing volumes and individual prescription history for governance and reconciliation purposes", "To submit monthly NHS reporting returns", "To book patient appointments based on prescribing history"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Prescription Audit Report helps pharmacy technicians review prescribing volumes and history for reconciliation, governance, and clinical audit purposes within the practice."}, {"question": "How do you check whether an EPS prescription has been successfully transmitted to the NHS Spine after approval?", "options": ["Phone the patient's nominated pharmacy to ask if they received it", "Check the prescription status in the Prescribing section of the patient record, which shows EPS transmission status", "Wait 24 hours and check back the following day", "EPS transmission is not tracked in Medicus"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Prescribing section of the patient record in Medicus displays the EPS transmission status for each prescription, confirming whether it has been successfully sent to the NHS Spine."}], "Receptionist": [{"question": "How do you register a new permanent patient at the practice in Medicus?", "options": ["Create a temporary record and wait for the patient's NHS number to be verified", "Use the Patient Registration section to create a new patient record, complete the required demographic fields, and submit the registration to NHAIS/PCSE", "Ask the patient to register via the Patient Portal only", "Registrations are done exclusively through NHS England centrally"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "New permanent patient registrations are completed in the Patient Registration section of Medicus. The record is created with demographic details and the registration is submitted electronically to NHAIS/PCSE."}, {"question": "A patient calls to cancel their appointment. What is the correct way to do this in Medicus?", "options": ["Delete the appointment from the diary so the slot disappears", "Open the appointment in the Appointment Book and select the cancel option, which frees the slot for rebooking", "Mark the appointment as DNA", "Move the appointment to a 'cancelled' diary column"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Cancelling an appointment in Medicus is done via the appointment details, freeing the slot for another patient. DNA is reserved for patients who do not attend without cancelling."}, {"question": "How do you register a patient who is staying temporarily in the area and needs urgent care?", "options": ["Temporary patients cannot be registered in Medicus", "Use the Temporary (INT) registration option in the Patient Registration section", "Register them as a permanent patient and remove them later", "Ask the patient to attend A&E instead"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus supports temporary and immediately necessary treatment (INT) registrations, allowing practices to see patients not on their permanent list and submit the appropriate registration to NHAIS."}, {"question": "A patient reports they have moved house. Where do you update their address in Medicus?", "options": ["In the patient's portal account - they must update it themselves", "In the patient record's demographic section, where address and contact details can be edited", "By sending a task to the practice administrator", "Address changes require a paper form to be sent to NHS England"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Patient demographic details including address are updated directly in the patient record. Changes are saved in Medicus and relevant updates are reflected in the patient's NHS registration."}, {"question": "When booking an appointment for a patient, how do you check the patient's communication preference (e.g. whether they want a reminder by text or letter)?", "options": ["Ask the patient every time they book", "Check the patient's Communication Preferences in their record before booking", "Communication preferences are set practice-wide and apply to all patients", "Communication preferences are only set during initial registration and cannot be viewed later"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Each patient record in Medicus includes a Communication Preferences section. Receptionists should check this when booking to ensure reminders and correspondence are sent in the patient's preferred format."}, {"question": "You believe a patient has a duplicate record in Medicus. What should you do?", "options": ["Delete one of the records immediately", "Use the Merge Duplicate Records function to flag and merge the records, preserving the clinical history from both", "Leave both records and add a note to each saying 'possible duplicate'", "Register a new record and ignore the old ones"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus has a duplicate record merge function that combines the demographic and clinical data from both records safely, ensuring the patient has a single accurate and complete record."}, {"question": "A patient wishes to deregister from the practice. What is the process in Medicus?", "options": ["Archive the patient record immediately", "Process the deregistration in the Patient Registration section, which notifies NHAIS/PCSE to remove them from the practice list", "Send the patient's records to their new practice by post", "Mark the patient as 'inactive' in their record"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Deregistrations are managed in the Patient Registration section, submitting the removal to NHAIS/PCSE electronically. GP2GP will transfer the clinical record to the new practice once they register elsewhere."}, {"question": "A patient calls to say they need an appointment but the clinical diary is fully booked. What option does Medicus offer?", "options": ["Tell the patient to call back tomorrow", "Check for cancellation slots, use the 'squeeze in' function if clinically necessary, or add the patient to a waiting list", "Book them with a clinician at a different practice", "Create a task for the GP to phone the patient instead - appointments cannot be added to full diaries"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus provides options for managing urgent demand including checking for cancellation slots and squeezing additional appointments into a full diary when clinically necessary."}, {"question": "How do you search for a patient in Medicus if you only know their date of birth and partial surname?", "options": ["You must have the full surname to search", "Enter the partial surname and date of birth in the patient search bar - Medicus will return matching records", "Run a report from the Reporting module to find patients by date of birth", "Ask the patient for their NHS number before searching"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Medicus patient search accepts partial names combined with other identifiers such as date of birth, allowing receptionists to locate patients even with incomplete information."}, {"question": "Where can you view a list of all patients currently registered at the practice in Medicus?", "options": ["Only in a monthly report generated by the administrator", "In the Patient List within the Patient Registration or Patient Records section", "Via NHS England's national patient registration portal", "The patient list is not accessible to receptionists - only the practice manager can view it"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus provides a Patient List view within the system, allowing authorised staff including receptionists to view and search the full list of registered patients."}], "Administrator": [{"question": "How do you add a new staff member to Medicus?", "options": ["Ask Medicus support to add them remotely", "Use the User Management section to create a new user account, assign a job role, and set appropriate RBAC permissions", "Give the new staff member an existing user's login credentials", "New users are added automatically when they log in with their NHS Smartcard"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "New staff are added via User Management in Medicus. The administrator creates the account, assigns the appropriate job role, and sets role-based access controls (RBAC) to match the staff member's clinical or administrative function."}, {"question": "When a staff member leaves the practice, what is the correct action in Medicus?", "options": ["Delete their user account immediately", "Archive the user account in User Management, which preserves audit trails while preventing further access", "Change their password so they cannot log in", "Move their account to a 'former staff' team"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Departing staff accounts should be archived in User Management. Archiving preserves the audit trail for all actions the user performed while employed but immediately revokes their system access."}, {"question": "Where in Medicus do you configure the appointment diary for a new clinical session?", "options": ["In the Reporting module under 'Session planning'", "In the Appointment Management or Diary Configuration section, where session types, slot durations, and availability are set", "By sending a task to the clinical lead", "Diary configuration is managed by Medicus centrally"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Appointment diaries including session types, slot durations, and availability are configured in the Appointment Management or Diary Configuration area, giving practices full control over their clinical scheduling."}, {"question": "How do you set up automatic task assignment in Medicus so that certain tasks go to specific teams?", "options": ["Tasks are always manually assigned - automatic routing is not available", "Configure automatic task assignment rules in the System Configuration or Task Management settings, linking task types to specific teams or roles", "Automatic task routing is set up by each individual user in their profile settings", "Contact Medicus support to configure task routing on your behalf"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Medicus supports automatic task assignment through configuration rules that route task types to designated teams or roles, reducing manual triage and ensuring tasks reach the right people promptly."}, {"question": "What is the GPAD (GP Appointment Data) extract in Medicus and how often must it be submitted?", "options": ["A monthly financial report submitted to NHS BSA", "A weekly extract of appointment data submitted to NHS England as part of national general practice reporting requirements", "A quarterly patient satisfaction survey", "An annual staff workload return submitted to the ICB"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "GPAD is a weekly NHS England reporting requirement. Medicus generates the appointment data extract which must be submitted weekly, providing national data on GP appointment capacity and activity."}, {"question": "How do you configure data sharing settings in Medicus, for example enabling SCR updates or EMIS data sharing?", "options": ["Data sharing is configured automatically at system installation and cannot be changed", "Via the Data Sharing Configuration section in System Configuration, where sharing agreements and permissions are managed", "By contacting NHS England directly to approve sharing arrangements", "Data sharing settings are managed by the ICB and pushed to practices remotely"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Data Sharing Configuration in Medicus System Configuration allows administrators to manage sharing agreements including SCR update permissions, EMIS sharing, and other NHS data sharing arrangements."}, {"question": "Where do you set up and manage teams in Medicus for task routing and staff organisation?", "options": ["In each individual user's profile settings", "In the User Management section under Teams, where teams can be created, named, and staff assigned", "Teams are preconfigured by Medicus and cannot be modified", "In the Staff Scheduling module under 'Group management'"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Teams are created and managed in the User Management section under Teams. Staff members are assigned to teams which are then used for task routing, diary configuration, and clinical governance."}, {"question": "How do you set up a staff member's working schedule in Medicus?", "options": ["Staff schedule themselves via their personal Medicus profile", "In the Staff Scheduling section, where shifts, working days, and session patterns are configured for each staff member", "By creating an appointment slot in their name for each working day", "Staff schedules are imported from an external HR system only"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Staff scheduling in Medicus is managed in the dedicated Staff Scheduling section, where administrators configure working days, session patterns, and availability for all clinical and administrative staff."}, {"question": "A new GP has joined who will be an independent prescriber. What must be configured in their Medicus user account to enable EPS prescribing?", "options": ["Nothing - all users can prescribe by default", "Their prescriber role and prescribing permissions must be set in User Management, and their NHS Smartcard (CIS2) details must be linked to their account", "They must apply to Medicus support for a prescribing licence", "EPS prescribing is enabled automatically after 30 days"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "To enable EPS prescribing, the administrator must configure the correct prescriber job role and permissions in User Management, and ensure the GP's Smartcard details are correctly set up for CIS2 authentication."}, {"question": "How do you generate the weekly GPAD exception report in Medicus?", "options": ["GPAD exception reporting is done via NHS England's separate web portal", "Use the GPAD Exception Reporting function in the Reporting section to identify and submit records that could not be included in the standard extract", "Exceptions are handled automatically by the system without administrator action", "The ICB manages GPAD exception reporting on behalf of all practices"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The GPAD Exception Reporting tool in Medicus Reporting allows administrators to identify appointment records that failed the standard GPAD extract and submit them as exceptions to NHS England."}], "Other Clinical": [{"question": "How do you create a new consultation in Medicus as a clinical staff member?", "options": ["Ask the GP to open the consultation and then add your notes to it", "Open the patient record and select 'New Consultation' from the Consultations tab", "Start a consultation via the Task module only", "Clinical staff other than GPs and ANPs cannot create consultations in Medicus"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Clinical staff with appropriate permissions create new consultations from the Consultations tab in the patient record, allowing direct documentation of clinical encounters."}, {"question": "Where do you record a procedure you have performed during a patient visit in Medicus?", "options": ["In the patient's task list as a completed item", "Within a consultation entry using appropriate SNOMED CT procedure codes", "In the Reporting module under 'Clinical activity'", "In the patient banner as a clinical alert"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Procedures are documented within a consultation in Medicus using SNOMED CT codes, ensuring the record is clinically coded, searchable, and visible to the wider care team."}, {"question": "You need to refer a patient to a specialist service. How is a referral created in Medicus?", "options": ["Phone the specialist directly and ask them to add the patient", "Use the Referrals section in Medicus or the integrated NHS e-RS to create and submit the referral", "Ask the patient to self-refer using the NHS App", "Email the referral letter to the specialist from your NHS email"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Referrals are created in the Referrals section of Medicus, with integration into NHS e-RS for electronic referral submission to secondary care services."}, {"question": "A patient's blood test results have returned. Where do you find and action these in Medicus?", "options": ["Results are emailed to the requesting clinician's NHS email", "In the Investigations section of the patient record, where results are displayed and can be actioned", "Only the GP who ordered the test can view the results", "In the Practice inbox, accessible only to administrators"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Investigation results are returned to the Investigations section of the patient record in Medicus, where the requesting or reviewing clinician can view, comment on, and action them."}, {"question": "Where do you find the patient's clinical summary including significant diagnoses and ongoing conditions?", "options": ["In the most recent consultation note", "In the Care Record section of the patient record, which provides an overview of active problems, diagnoses, and significant history", "By running a QOF register report", "In the Patient Portal - accessible to the patient but not to clinical staff in this format"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The Care Record section of the patient record in Medicus provides a clinical summary including active problems, significant diagnoses, and ongoing conditions relevant to the patient's care."}, {"question": "How do you record a vaccination administered by a clinical member of staff in Medicus?", "options": ["Add a free-text note in the consultation", "In the Vaccinations section of the patient record, entering vaccine details, batch number, route, site, and date", "Send a task to the nurse to document the vaccination", "Upload a scanned record in the Documents section"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Vaccinations are recorded in the dedicated Vaccinations section, capturing all relevant details including vaccine type, batch number, route, site, and date, contributing to the patient's complete immunisation history."}, {"question": "How do you schedule a future recall or review action for a patient in Medicus?", "options": ["Set a personal reminder in your calendar", "Use the Future Actions feature in the Care Record to add a recall action with a target date linked to the patient's record", "Book a speculative appointment in the diary", "Send a task to the receptionist to book the patient in 3 months"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Future Actions in the Care Record allow clinical staff to schedule patient-specific recall or review actions with a due date, supporting proactive clinical management and LTC reviews."}, {"question": "An inbound letter from a hospital has appeared in Medicus. Where do you find and review it?", "options": ["In the Practice inbox, visible only to administrators", "In the Documents section of the patient record, where inbound documents can be reviewed, coded, and filed", "In the Consultation history as an attached file", "In the Patient Portal for the patient to review first"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Inbound documents including letters, discharge summaries, and clinic letters appear in the Documents section of the patient record, where clinical staff can review, code, and take action on them."}, {"question": "How do you record a patient's blood pressure and weight observation in Medicus as a clinical staff member?", "options": ["Only GPs can record observations in Medicus", "In the Observations section of the patient record, where clinical measurements can be entered directly", "In the Consultation notes as free text only", "Via the Patient Portal, asking the patient to self-report"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Clinical observations such as blood pressure and weight are recorded in the dedicated Observations section of the patient record, accessible to clinical staff with appropriate permissions."}, {"question": "Where do you check if a patient has any active allergies before administering a medication or vaccine?", "options": ["Ask the patient verbally and rely on their answer alone", "Review the Allergies section of the patient record and check the patient banner for allergy warnings", "Only the prescribing GP can check allergies", "Allergy information is only visible in the SCR, not in the patient record directly"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Active allergies are displayed in the Allergies section of the patient record and as clinical warnings in the patient banner. Clinical staff should always check both before administering any medication or vaccine."}]};
